1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 { This sharp and complex line was very popular in the pre-computer era. It was tried by a number of top-level players from this period. As a matter of fact, we cannot say that strong engines managed to completely refute White's concept. Objectively speaking, White is not getting a worse position by force. Nevertheless, nowadays, Black found reliable ways of handling this variation. Therefore, White's concept should be considered impractical. } 5... Bg6 6. Nge2 { [%cal Gh2h4,Gh7h5,Ge2f4] White should start with this move. The idea is to harass the g6-bishop by playing Nf4 after the inclusion of the moves h2-h4 and ...h7-h5. } ( { The immediate } 6. h4 $6 { is obviously inferior in view of } 6... h5 { when White cannot keep the integrity of his kingside. After } 7. g5 c5 $17 { Black has a huge advantage since White's centre is falling apart. Additionally, the advance of the kingside pawns only created new weaknesses. } ) 6... c5 { The most straightforward continuation. Statically speaking, White's position is very dubious because of two important factors: 1) due to the misplaced c3-knight, White cannot support the centre with c2-c3 2) the advance g2-g4 created serious kingside weaknesses In order to compensate for the abovementioned strategic problems, White should play very energetically. } 7. h4 { This is by far the most popular continuation. Also, the immediate advance of the h-pawn is the best way of justifying the move 6.Nge2. } ( { The only reasonable alternative seems to be } 7. Be3 { In this case, our reaction is similar to the main line - } 7... h5 8. Nf4 Bh7 $1 { Remember this thematic idea. In this line, we are ready to sacrifice the h5-pawn in order to keep the light-squared bishop alive. For the time being, destroying White's centre is Black's main focus. } 9. Nxh5 { The most natural response. } ( { In an online game, White tried } 9. dxc5 { but after } 9... Nc6 10. Bb5 hxg4 11. Qxg4 Bxc2 $17 { Black got a clear advantage in the game 0-1 (22) Vlassov, N (2294) -Svane,R (2637) Chess.com INT 2021. White does not have the slightest compensation for his terrible pawn structure. } ) 9... Nc6 $15 ) 7... h5 8. Nf4 Bh7 $1 { This pawn sacrifice is the reason why the entire concept based on Nc3 followed by g2-g4 lost popularity. In return for the pawn, Black has a permanent compensation in view of his better pawn structure and safer king. Even though the arising positions are objectively balanced, Black's play is easier and more intuitive. To compensate for his structural problems, White should keep finding energetic and creative solutions. } 9. Nxh5 { This is the main move according to the theory. } ( { The main alternative is } 9. g5 { which was tried a couple of times by some very strong players including the Iranian top level grandmaster Maghsoodloo. White relies on his space advantage on the kingside. Also, Black should always reckon with the advance g5-g6. On the downside, Black gets access to the important f5-square. } 9... cxd4 { The simplest solution. Black immediately starts his counterplay in the centre. } 10. Nb5 { Of course, White will be happy to recapture the pawn with a knight. Besides improving the position of his knight, he will also enjoy control of the f5-square. The problem is that the entire operation is rather time-consuming. Additionally in many lines, the e5-pawn tends to be vulnerable. } ( { Note that the advance } 10. g6 { is almost never enough to create problems for Black. The following sequence is quite illustrative: } 10... Bxg6 11. Nxg6 fxg6 12. Ne2 Nc6 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Ne7 $15 { [%csl Re1][%cal Ge8f7,Ge7f5,Gf8e7] Black is already better in this position. He is ready to proceed with ...Nf5 followed by ...Be7. As for the king, we can safely put it on f7. It's not clear how White will handle his inferior structure and chronically weak king. } ) ( { Another version of the advance g5-g6 was seen in the game Minasion, A - Kovalenko, I, 2014 - } 10. Qxd4 $2 Nc6 11. Bb5 Ne7 { In this position, White is already strategically lost since he cannot compensate for all his structural problems. } 12. g6 { After Black having played ...Nge7, this advance is completely ineffective. The game went } 12... Nxg6 13. Nxh5 Qd7 $19 { when Black was already winning. White's position is falling apart. 0-1 (40) Minasian,A (2482) -Kovalenko,I (2626) Yerevan 2014 } ) 10... Be4 { This move is quite thematic for the lines with g2-g4. Before putting his bishop on the desirable f5-square, Black wants to provoke the advance f2-f3. Besides releasing the pressure on h5, by playing f2-f3, White also weakens the kingside. } 11. f3 { [%csl Re1] } 11... Bf5 12. Nxd4 Ne7 { [%cal Gb8c6,Gd8c7,Gg7g6,Ga7a6, Ga8c8] Black is already fighting for the advantage. As we are going to witness on numerous occasions, in all these structures, Black is happy to replace the f5-bishop with a knight. It goes without saying that if given the necessary time, Black will be happy to proceed with ...Nbc6 followed by ...g7-g6. White should play very energetically not to find himself in a totally broken position. } 13. Nxf5 { The only challenging continuation. } ( { Pointless is } 13. Bb5+ { when after } 13... Nbc6 $17 { it's clear that the b5-bishop is misplaced. } ) 13... Nxf5 14. Bd3 { Now, we should reckon with Bxf5. } ( { As usual, the advance } 14. g6 $6 { does not create problems for Black. We can just focus on the e5-pawn by playing } 14... Nc6 15. gxf7+ Kxf7 { [%csl Re5][%cal Gd8c7] with ...Qc7 to follow. Note that the h4-pawn is quite vulnerable as well. } ) 14... Qc7 $1 { Remember this important move. Due to the weakening f2-f3 advance, White cannot protect the e5-pawn by means of Qe2. } 15. Ne2 { The best continuation. White needs to free the f4-square for the bishop. } ( { The point of 14...Qc7 is that } 15. Bxf5 { will be answered with } 15... Qxe5+ $17 ) 15... g6 { Supporting the knight is necessary. } ( { In case of } 15... Qxe5 $6 16. c3 $44 { [%cal Gc1f4] White has an excellent compensation for the pawn. It's not easy for Black to deal with the threat of Bf4. } ) 16. Bxf5 gxf5 17. Be3 Nd7 18. f4 Bc5 $13 { [%cal Ge8f8,Gf8g7,Gg7g6] This position was reached in the game 1/2-1/2 (37) Shyam, N (2467) -Srihari, L (2407) Pune 2023. Having less space, Black is interested in exchanging minor pieces. Later on, in order to fully block White's kingside play, we can bring the king to g6. I would even take the black pieces in view of the possibility of playing along the c-file. } ) 9... Nc6 { In my opinion, this is the most natural continuation. All our moves will be directed at destroying White's centre. It goes without saying that 9...cxd4 is playable as well. } 10. dxc5 { This is White's best way of releasing the central tension. } ( { As usual, the move } 10. Bb5 { is not particularly challenging since Black can often make use of the vulnerable position of the bishop. Even though the most popular 10... cxd4 is completely playable here, my suggestion would be } 10... Ne7 $1 { Black develops a piece and is ready to recapture on c6 with a knight. } 11. Bg5 { This typical move is White's most challenging option. } ( { The "tricky" } 11. Bh6 $2 { backfires after } 11... Qc7 $1 { As a rule, we are almost never afraid of sacrificing the g7-pawn since taking it will spoil White's coordination. A possible continuation would be } 12. Nxg7+ Kd7 13. f4 a6 14. Bxc6+ Nxc6 $17 { White's centre is falling apart. Additionally, White's dark-squared bishop and knight are stuck on the kingside. } ) ( { The worst possible choice is } 11. dxc5 $2 { The problem is that after chasing the c3-knight away by means of } 11... d4 { the d5-square will be available for the queen. } 12. Bxc6+ Nxc6 13. Ne2 { This position was reached in the game 1-0 (38) Kotronias, V (2545) -Danielsen, H (2480) Reykjavik 1994. Now, the simple } 13... Qd5 14. Rh3 Qxc5 $19 { would have provided Black with a decisive advantage. } ) 11... Qb6 $14 { Strangely enough, this natural move turns out to be a novelty. Besides increasing the pressure on d4, Black underlines the unstable position of the b5-bishop. White should play very carefully, not to find himself in huge trouble. The most consistent is } 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Qe2 { trying to keep everything together. Now, Black can play the typical } 13... d4 { freeing the important d5-square for the queen. } 14. Na4 Qd5 { Black's position is already preferable. Depending on the circumstances, he can continue with either ...d4-d3 or ...0-0-0. The following sequence is quite characteristic - } 15. f3 d3 $1 16. Bxd3 Nd4 17. Nc3 Bxd3 18. cxd3 Qxf3 19. Qxf3 Nxf3+ 20. Ke2 Nxe5 21. Nf6+ gxf6 22. Bxf6 N7g6 23. Bxh8 Nxh8 $15 { Black has a huge advantage. Of course, you are by no means forced to remember this computer line. I provide it just to illustrate the potential of the position. } ) 10... Qa5 $5 { I like this tricky rare move which will probably take your opponent by surprise. White should now reckon with the threat of ... d5-d4. } ( { The main move } 10... Bxc5 { is completely playable as well. } ) 11. Rh3 { This move to ignore the threat of ...d5-d4 is not easy for a human. Quite typical for this line, White should keep finding subtle resources in order to maintain the balance. } ( { Another very interesting continuation is } 11. a3 $5 { With this move, White is setting an interesting trap. Black's most precise move is } 11... Qxc5 $1 ( { White's idea is that } 11... d4 $6 { is very well met by } 12. b4 $1 { The point is that } 12... Nxb4 $2 { is losing on the spot. } ( { More tenacious is } 12... Qc7 { Nevertheless, after } 13. Nb5 Qxe5+ 14. Qe2 $16 { White's advantage is undisputable. } ) 13. axb4 Qxa1 ( { The alternative } 13... Qxb4 { does not help either. After } 14. Bb5+ Kd8 15. Rh3 $18 { White is winning. } ) 14. Bb5+ Kd8 15. Bg5+ $18 { [%csl Ra1] Black is dropping the queen. } ) 12. Nb5 $1 { Once again, the only reasonable move. Otherwise, White's position is strategically unsound. Black will simply organize the advance ...d5-d4. Black's best choice is to go for the following sequence: } 12... Bxc2 13. Qd2 Ba4 14. Nc7+ Kd8 15. Nxa8 Nd4 16. Be2 Nc2+ 17. Kf1 Nxa1 18. b4 Qc2 $13 { The position is very complex but I would definitely take Black. } ) ( { This is one of the two moves that have been tried in practice. After this continuation, Black is already fighting for an advantage. } 11. Bb5 Ne7 { [%cal Ga7a6] Since we are ready to recapture on c6 with the knight, the advance ...a7-a6 becomes a real threat. } 12. a3 $6 { This imprecise move has been played in two games. To be honest, I think that White's position is so chaotic that everyone would go wrong at some point. } 12... O-O-O { [%csl Rb5,Gh7][%cal Gd5d4] Black is ready to follow with ...d5-d4. } 13. Bf4 ( { Another game saw } 13. Bg5 $6 d4 14. b4 Qc7 15. Ne2 Nxe5 $17 { when Black obtained a huge advantage. 0-1 (49) Brobakken,G (2250) -Andriuschenko,N (2551) ICCF email 2005 } ) 13... d4 14. b4 Qc7 15. Ne2 { This position was reached in the game 0-1 (57) Gromov, S (2293) -Iordanyan, E ICCF email 2012. At this point, Black could have played } 15... Be4 16. Rh3 Nxe5 $17 { [%cal Ge7g6] with an obvious advantage. The next move is going to be ...N7g6. } ) ( { In another game, White played the natural-looking } 11. Bd2 $6 { Such passive moves, however, just don't work in this type of position. After } 11... Qxc5 { Black is already clearly better. White should decide how to deal with ...d5-d4. } 12. Bg5 $2 { After this mistake White is losing on the spot. 1-0 (58) Luberanski,J (2228) -Hryharovich, A (2153) Bydgoszcz 2023. The best would have been } 12... d4 13. Nb5 Bxc2 $19 { with a winning position. } ) 11... d4 { [%csl Gh3] This is one of the two good options. In both cases, your opponent will be forced to play very precisely in order to maintain the balance. } ( { Another very interesting option is } 11... a6 $5 { [%cal Ga5c5] After taking the b5-square under control, Black can take on c5 with a queen without fearing Nb5. The following sequence is pretty logical - } 12. a3 d4 13. b4 Nxb4 14. axb4 Qxa1 15. Nd5 Rb8 ( { Of course, not } 15... exd5 $2 { since after } 16. Ra3 Qb1 17. Bb5+ $18 { White is winning on the spot. } ) 16. Ra3 Qb1 17. Bd3 Bxd3 18. cxd3 exd5 19. Rb3 Qa2 20. Ra3 Qb1 $11 { With a draw by repetition. } ) ( { The immediate } 11... Qxc5 $6 { can be answered with } 12. Nb5 Nb4 13. Rc3 { We can now see one of the points behind the move 11. Rh3! After } 13... Nxc2+ 14. Qxc2 Bxc2 15. Rxc5 Bxc5 16. Nc7+ Kd7 17. Nxa8 $36 { Black will need to spend some time in order to regain the piece. Meanwhile, White will develop a dangerous initiative. } ) 12. b4 { Now, White should find a couple of only moves just not to lose immediately. } 12... Qxb4 13. Rb1 Qa5 14. Rb5 Qc7 15. Na4 { The position is balanced, but with White's pieces dispersed all over the board, Black's play is practically easier. I have analyzed the following line - } 15... Nge7 16. Bg2 Qxe5+ 17. Kf1 Be4 18. Rxb7 Bxg2+ 19. Kxg2 Qd5+ 20. Qf3 Qxf3+ 21. Rxf3 Nd8 22. Rb5 Ng6 23. Rh3 Nc6 $44 { Black has excellent compensation for the pawn in view of his active pieces and good central control. The c6-knight keeps under control the entire queenside. One of the possible ideas is ...0-0-0 followed by ...Rd5. In some cases, Black can also consider the maneuver ... Ng6-e5-d7 followed by ...a7-a6. Objectively speaking, the position remains balanced. } *
