1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. g4 { In my opinion, without the inclusion of 4. Nc3, this move is practically more dangerous. As we have seen in the previous line, strategically speaking, the knight is not well placed on c3. On the other hand, now Black has the extra option of } 4... Be4 { which is indeed the most precise continuation from a theoretical standpoint. } 5. f3 Bg6 6. e6 { This thematic pawn sacrifice is the main idea behind White's entire concept. The idea is to hinder the development of Black's kingside. } ( { Less precise is } 6. h4 { As it will soon become clear, in some cases, the pawn is better placed on the h2-square. Our typical response is } 6... h5 { It's always advisable to prevent White from gaining further space on the kingside by means of h4-h5. } 7. e6 { Once again, this positional pawn sacrifice is White's only constructive idea. } ( { In case of a slow move such as } 7. Bd3 { , we can just go for } 7... Bxd3 8. Qxd3 e6 $15 { [%cal Gc6c5] with ...c6-c5 to follow. It's far from clear why White weakened the kingside. } ) 7... Qd6 { When the g3-square is weakened by the advance h2-h4, this typical queen sortie becomes quite a decent option. } 8. exf7+ Bxf7 { [%cal Gb8d7,Ge7e5] Black is doing perfectly fine in this structure. Our main idea is to prepare the advance ...e7-e5 by means of ...Nd7. In this structure, Black usually castles long. Note that without the inclusion of the moves h2-h4 and ...h7-h5, in this position White would have had the possibility of playing f3-f4, preventing the advance ...e7-e5. Below, we shall take a look at some example lines: } 9. Be3 { This move was played in the high-profile game Vallejo Pons, F - So, W, 2017. } ( { Another characteristic line would be } 9. Ne2 hxg4 10. fxg4 Nd7 11. Bf4 e5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 $17 { when Black has a huge advantage due to his better central control and safer King. } ) ( { Another game saw } 9. g5 $6 { which is both positionally and tactically bad. After } 9... Qg3+ 10. Ke2 e6 11. Nh3 Qc7 $17 { Black has an obvious advantage in the game 0-1 (41) Chandler, P (2107) -Donchenko, A (2563) Heusenstamm 2016 } ) 9... hxg4 10. fxg4 Nf6 11. Nc3 { If allowed to castle long, White might develop a dangerous initiative. His position, however, is way too overextended. } 11... Qe6 { Black is just winning the g4-pawn. } ( { Another good option would have been } 11... Qg3+ 12. Bf2 Qxg4 13. Be2 Qf5 $15 { [%cal Gb8d7,Ge7e5] followed by ... Nbd7 and ...e7-e5. White does not have sufficient compensation for the pawn. } ) 12. Kd2 $2 { This move is already a decisive mistake. } ( { White should have opted for } 12. Qe2 Nxg4 13. Bg5 Qxe2+ 14. Ncxe2 Bg6 $15 { [%cal Gg6e4,Gb8d7, Ge7e5] Even in this case, however, the compensation is hardly enough. After placing his bishop on e4, Black will prepare the thematic ...e7-e5. } ) 12... Nxg4 13. Bg5 Nf2 14. Qf3 Nxh1 15. Qxh1 Qd6 $19 { Black was already winning since White does not have the slightest compensation for the sacrificed material. 0-1 (30) Vallejo Pons,F (2717) -So,W (2810) Tbilisi 2017 } ) 6... fxe6 { With the white pawn being still on h2, this recapture is more precise than 6... Qd6. } ( { Still, } 6... Qd6 { remains a playable option. The problem is that White has the possibility of playing } 7. exf7+ Bxf7 8. Nc3 Nd7 9. f4 $14 { This move wouldn't have been possible with the inclusion of the advance h2-h4 and .. .h7-h5. In my opinion, White can pretend on a slight advantage in this structure. 1/2-1/2 (32) Tari, A (2641) -Carlsen, M (2835) Baku 2023 } ) 7. h4 { White wants to provoke the weakening ...h7-h5 before exchanging the light-squared bishops via d3. } ( { The immediate } 7. Bd3 $6 { is premature in view of } 7... Bxd3 8. Qxd3 c5 $15 { [%cal Gb8c6] with ...Nc6 to follow. Note that 9. dxc5 will be comfortably met by 9...e5. } ) 7... c5 $5 { This move has been played in only 1 game so far. Black immediately starts attacking the centre. We are planning to proceed with ...Nc6 and start preparing the advance ... e6-e5. Sometimes, this advance can be executed even at the price of a pawn sacrifice.The best White can do is gain space on the kingside by playing } ( { Another important direction is } 7... h5 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qd6 { which is perfectly playable for Black. This is also the suggestion of GM Pavel Eljanov in his second Caro-Kann database. Nevertheless, chances are that your opponent will be better prepared for this line. Therefore, I decided to opt for 7...c5!? which will surely take your opponent out of his comfort zone. } ) 8. h5 Bf7 9. f4 { An important move in White's strategy. Taking the e5-square under control is extremely important. } ( { Another interesting possibility that I have examined is } 9. c3 { stabilizing the centre and planning to answer } 9... Nc6 { with } 10. f4 { This approach however is a bit slow and Black can therefore make use of White's overextended position - } 10... Nh6 $1 { [%cal Gd8b6] I like this move. Besides preventing Nf3, Black is ready to occupy the f5-square in response to g4-g5. He is now planning to increase the pressure on d4 by means of ...Qb6. A possible line would be } 11. Be3 Qb6 12. Nd2 cxd4 13. cxd4 g6 $1 { Another useful move practically eliminating White's space advantage on the kingside. Black wants to get control of the f5-square by means of ...gxh5. } 14. hxg6 Bxg6 $15 { Black is better in view of his superior activity and White's overextended position. White cannot play } 15. f5 $2 exf5 16. Bxh6 fxg4 $17 { when Black's advantage is almost decisive. } ) 9... Nc6 10. Nf3 { The most natural continuation. } ( { Another possible direction is } 10. dxc5 e5 11. Nf3 exf4 12. Bxf4 e6 $13 { [%cal Gf8c5,Gg8e7] Even though the position remains balanced, Black's play is practically easier. He is ready to proceed with ...Bxc5 followed by ...Nge7. In view of his overextended position, White can easily go wrong. } ) 10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 { This position was seen in the game Ponkratov, P - Makarian, R, 2020. Now, instead of 11...Qb6 which was played in the game, my suggestion would be } 11... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6d7,Ge6e5] Our main idea is to prepare the advance ...e6-e5 by means of ...Nd7. As mentioned earlier the advance ... e6-e5 often implies a pawn sacrifice. } 12. Nc3 { The most reasonable continuation. Besides proceeding with the development, White keeps his central control. } ( { I have also examined } 12. g5 Nd7 13. Nc3 ( { In case of } 13. Bh3 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 e5 15. fxe5 e6 $15 { Black is already slightly better in view of his stable structure and White's vulnerable pawns. } ) 13... e5 14. fxe5 e6 $13 { The position remains unclear but Black's play is definitely easier. Very often in these lines, White's development tends to be insufficient to sustain the space advantage. } ) 12... Nd7 { Once again, this key move is the best solution to Black's problems. The ...e6-e5 advance is now on the agenda. The following sequence is just an illustration of White might happen in such positions - } 13. Bb5 e5 14. fxe5 e6 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Bxc6 Rb8 17. Qd3 Be7 $13 { Black has an excellent compensation for the sacrificed pawn . He is ready to castle on the next move. In a practical game, White would have problems supporting his overextended position and finding a safe haven for the king. } *
