1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nd2 e6 5. Nb3 a6 6. Nf3 c5 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. c3 Qxc5 { We have arrived at our thematic structure. Black is planning to develop the knights on e7 and c6. The queen will eventually land on the c7-square. If White fails to carry out the advance f2-f4, the e5-pawn might become quite vulnerable. Therefore, the following couple of moves are quite logical - } 10. Be3 Qc7 11. Nd4 { [%cal Gf2f4] Threatening the f5-bishop and preparing f2-f4. } 11... Ne7 { An important thing to know is that in this structure we are never afraid of replacing our light-squared bishop with a knight on f5. In this fixed position, White's bishop pair is not an important asset. } ( { Taking the pawn with } 11... Qxe5 $2 { does not work in view of } 12. Qb3 $18 { when Black's position is falling apart. } ) 12. f4 Nbc6 13. Be2 { Since the position has been stabilized, it's time to draw some strategic conclusions. By playing f2-f4, White managed to safely protect the e5-pawn. On the other hand, the advance f2-f4 weakens the light squares and makes the e3-bishop a bit more passive. Black should apply the so-called light square strategy. The reason is rather simple: three black minor pieces control the light squares versus only two white minor pieces. Hence, the perfect endgame for Black would be queen and knight versus queen and dark-squared bishop. In such a scenario, White will have nothing to oppose to our play on the light squares. Another typical idea for Black is to eliminate White's space advantage with the advance ... f7-f6. In this case. the backward e6-pawn will be compensated by the weakness of the light squares in White's camp. As we will see in the coming examples, it's far from easy for White to take advantage of his space advantage. } 13... Be4 { The bishop is very well placed on e4 in this pawn structure. As a rule, the f5-square should be reserved for the knight. } 14. O-O O-O 15. Nf3 { Usually, White is interested in preserving the knight. As pointed out earlier, in this fixed pawn structure, the dynamic potential of the bishops is not too high. } ( { Let's suppose that White starts with } 15. Qd2 { Black will then be more than happy to exchange the knights by means of } 15... Nxd4 16. Bxd4 { In this typical situation, we have two possible ideas: One very natural idea would be } 16... Nf5 { By chasing the d4-bishop away, Black wants to prepare the advance ...f7-f6. } ( { The alternative } 16... Rfc8 { [%cal Gb7b5] indicates Black's intention of taking over on the queenside. Black is ready to start a kind of a minority attack by means of the advance ...b7-b5. Preventing this idea with } 17. a4 { weakens the light squares on the queenside. Black can make use of these weaknesses by means of the maneuver } 17... Nc6 18. Bf2 Na5 $13 { with an excellent counterplay. } ) 17. Bf2 { Whenever possible, White wants to avoid exchanges of minor pieces. As we will see in the following examples, in this structure, endgames with only heavy pieces on the board are almost always favourable for Black. } 17... f6 18. exf6 Rxf6 { [%cal Ga8f8] Black is ready to put pressure on the f4-pawn by doubling the rooks along the f-file. His idea is to further weaken the light squares in White's camp by provoking the advance g2-g3. } 19. Bd3 { Trying to eliminate the strong e4-bishop which blocks the e-file. } 19... Bxd3 { The most natural move. Black got his dream piece configuration. } ( { Note that we can even allow our opponent to take on e4 himself. For instance, the position arising after } 19... Rg6 20. Bxe4 dxe4 21. Rae1 Rd8 22. Qe2 Qc6 { is far from one-sided. White should now watch for the advance e4-e3. After } 23. Qxe4 Qxe4 24. Rxe4 Rd2 $13 { Black enjoys an excellent counterplay. } ) 20. Qxd3 Rc8 $13 { Black is doing completely fine. The potential of our play on the light squares provides very good compensation for the relatively weak e6-pawn. } ) 15... h6 { This typical move is designed to prevent any Ng5 ideas. Additionally, in some cases Black can even consider destroying White's centre with ...g7-g5. } ( { Another natural possibility would have been } 15... f6 16. exf6 Rxf6 $13 { Black has an excellent counterplay. If we manage to provoke the weakening g2-g3 advance, we can even consider opening the position with ... e6-e5. In this way, the white king will become quite vulnerable. } ) 16. a4 Rfd8 { This move is usually connected with the advance ...d5-d4 which becomes a decent option when the d5-pawn is not safely blocked. For instance, after } 17. Kh1 { Black could have played the immediate } 17... d4 $1 { illustrating the point behind ...Rfd8. } ( { In the game, Black went for } 17... Na5 $13 { which is a decent option as well. Eventually, Abdusattorov managed to win. } ) 18. Nxd4 Nf5 19. Bg1 Ncxd4 20. cxd4 Qc6 $17 { Black has a tremendous play on the light squares. White is already in serious trouble. } *
