1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nd2 e6 5. Nb3 a6 6. Nf3 c5 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. c3 Qxc5 10. Nd4 { In my opinion, this move is more useful than the natural 10.Be3 which only helps Black queen occupy the perfect c7-square. Obviously, we should continue with the typical } 10... Ne7 { getting ready to replace the f5-bishop with a knight. } 11. Qa4+ $5 { This tricky move forces the transition into an endgame which is equal but requires a little bit of precision. } 11... Nbc6 12. Be3 { Now, White's idea becomes clear. Since the c7-square is no longer available for the queen, Black has nothing better than going for the endgame arising after } 12... Qa5 13. Qxa5 Nxa5 14. Nxf5 Nxf5 15. Bb6 Nc4 { This is the clear cut way to the equality. } ( { if you want to play more complex position, you can try } 15... Nc6 16. f4 g5 $1 { Remember this typical break designed to destroy White's centre. A logical continuation would be } 17. Bd3 Nfe7 18. g3 Kd7 $13 { [%cal Gg5f4, Gg3f4,Ga8g8,Gh7h5] with a very complex battle ahead. Our next move is going to be ...Rag8. Afterward, depending on the reaction of the opponent, we will either follow with ...gxf4 or ...h7-h5. Such imbalanced positions offer good chances of outplaying our opponent. } ) 16. Bxc4 dxc4 17. a4 { [%cal Ga4a5,Ga1a4] This is White's key idea. After fixing the b7-pawn, Wesley is planning to follow with Ra4, thus asking some questions related to the relatively vulnerable c4-pawn. Nevertheless, Black has a clear plan of stabilizing the position. We should start with } 17... Ne7 $1 { [%cal Ge7d5] In this structure, the knight is optimally placed on d5. } 18. a5 Nd5 19. Ra4 { In my opinion this move is already dubious, since the rook endgame is more than acceptable for Black. } ( { White should have played } 19. Bd4 { White's plan is easy to understand. He should combine the pressure on c4 with kingside activity. Gaining space on the kingside should be top priority for both sides. Therefore, our most precise continuation is } 19... f5 $1 { Together with the maneuver ... Nf5-e7-d5, this is the only thing that you should know to equalize in this line. A possible follow-up would be } 20. Kd2 ( { The structure arising after } 20. exf6 gxf6 $13 { [%cal Ge8f7,Gh8d8,Ga8c8,Ge6e5,Gf7e6] is perfectly acceptable for Black. After putting our rooks on c8 and d8, we can consider expanding with ...e6-e5 followed by ...Ke6. } ) 20... Rc8 21. h4 h5 $13 { Another thematic move. The fight for kingside space is very important in this structure. The position is objectively equal but Black's play is really simple. After an eventual ...f5-f4, we can even dream of an eventual transfer of the king to f5. Also, in some cases, Black can try to prepare the advance ...g7-g5. } ) 19... Nxb6 { The simplest solution. } ( { The game went } 19... Rc8 20. Bd4 Kd7 ( 20... f5 $11 ) 21. Kd2 h5 22. Re1 h4 23. Re4 Rh5 24. Be3 Rf5 25. Ke2 Nxe3 26. Kxe3 Rc5 27. f4 g5 28. g3 hxg3 29. hxg3 gxf4+ 30. gxf4 f6 31. exf6 Rxa5 32. Rxa5 Rxa5 33. Re5 Ra1 34. f5 Rf1 35. fxe6+ Ke8 36. f7+ Ke7 37. Kd4 b5 38. Kc5 Rf2 39. Re3 Rf5+ 40. Kb6 b4 41. cxb4 Rb5+ 42. Kxa6 Rxb4 43. Rf3 { [%emt 0:01:00] } ) 20. axb6 Rc8 $15 { [%cal Ge8e7,Gc8c5,Gh8c8,Gc8c6] Although White should be able to hold this endgame, Black's play is really simple and straightforward. He will proceed with ...Ke7 followed by ...Rc5, and ...Rhc8-c6. White should be very careful not to find himself in serious trouble. } 1-0
