1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nd2 e6 5. Nb3 a6 6. Nf3 c5 7. Nxc5 Bxc5 8. dxc5 Qa5+ 9. c3 Qxc5 10. Nd4 Ne7 11. Be3 Qc7 12. f4 O-O 13. Be2 Nbc6 { White can try the tricky } 14. Nb3 $5 { As we have already mentioned, White is interested in preserving the knight. In my opinion, this retreat is more challenging than the common Nf3. One of the main advantages is that the typical ...Be4 can often be countered with Nc5. Additionally Black should always reckon with the advance g2-g4. In my opinion, our best bet is } 14... Rfd8 { As we know, preparing ...d5-d4, even at the price of a pawn sacrifice, is a typical strategy when the d4-square is vacant. According to computer analysis, we are ready to answer } 15. O-O { with } 15... d4 $1 16. Nxd4 { White has nothing better than this recapture. } ( { After } 16. cxd4 Nd5 17. Qd2 Nxe3 18. Qxe3 Bc2 $15 { Black is already better since White cannot keep the d4-pawn. } ) 16... Nxd4 17. Bxd4 ( { Another possibility is } 17. cxd4 Be4 18. Rc1 Qd7 19. Qd2 Nf5 $44 { when Black enjoys an excellent compensation for the pawn. } ) 17... Nc6 { The most precise. Eventually, White will end up with a weak pawn on d4. The following sequence is quite characteristic - } 18. g4 Be4 19. Qd2 Nxd4 20. cxd4 Qb6 21. Rad1 Rac8 22. Qe3 Bd5 $44 { Black has enough compensation for the pawn. } *
