1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nd2 e6 5. Nb3 a6 6. Nf3 c5 { White can try to sustain the centre with } 7. c3 { Now, taking on c5 is already an option that Black should consider. In my opinion, the most precise continuation is } 7... c4 { This decision is strategically risky. Now, as there is no tension in the centre, White has a free hand on the kingside. On the other hand, Black has decent counterplay on the queenside. In contrast to the usual French structures, here our light-squared bishop is out of the pawn chain. It goes without saying that this is favourable for Black. On the downside, the position of our bishop often allows White to win some important tempis while developing his kingside initiative. I advocate entering this strategically complex structure only when White wasted some tempis in the opening (here he played Nd2-b3) . } 8. Nbd2 Nc6 9. Be2 b5 { In my opinion, Black should start playing on the queenside without wasting time. } 10. Nf1 { The most ambitious plan. Depending on the concrete situation, white will play either Ng3 or Ne3. As we will see in a while, Black should always reckon with the advance of the h-pawn. } 10... Bg6 { This is the most precise move. Retreating the bishop from the vulnerable f5-square should be our priority. An alternative would have been 10...h6. The problem with this advance is that sometimes it's better for Black to keep the option of ...h7-h5 in response to h2-h4. } 11. h4 { This is the only dangerous plan. Seizing as much space as possible on the kingside is the most important part of White's strategy. Although it might seem counterintuitive, Black's best response is } 11... h5 { We should prevent White from gaining too much space on the kingside at any price. } ( { Let's take a look at the following instructive line - } 11... h6 12. h5 Bh7 13. Ne3 { [%cal Gf3h4,Gg2g3,Gf2f4] White is now ready to progress on the kingside by means of Nh4 followed by g2-g3 and f2-f4. The problem is that the h5-pawn heavily limits Black's ability to oppose White's kingside strategy. The following sample line is quite illustrative - } 13... a5 14. O-O { [%cal Gf3e1, Ge2g4,Gf2f4] Besides the idea of g2-g3 and Nh4, White also prepares Ne1 followed by f2-f4 and Bg4. } 14... Nge7 { Sooner or later, Black must play this developing move. The problem is that it allows } 15. Nh4 { The position arising after } 15... Nc8 16. g3 Be7 17. Nhg2 O-O 18. f4 $14 { is in White's favour. At any moment, Black should reckon with f4-f5 followed by Nf4. At the same time, our queenside activity is a bit slow. } ) 12. Ng5 { [%cal Gf1g3] White immediately tries to use the weakened g5-square. Also, the h5-pawn is quite vulnerable. We should be ready for Ng3 on the next move. } ( { In case of } 12. Ng3 { Black has enough time to organize his counterplay. } 12... b4 13. O-O bxc3 14. bxc3 Qa5 15. Bd2 Rb8 16. Ng5 Rb2 $13 { Black's queenside counterplay turns out to be quite dangerous. } ) 12... b4 { It goes without saying that Black should play extremely energetically in this position. Otherwise, we will lose the h5-pawn for nothing. The following sequence is quite illustrative of the nature of the position. } 13. Ng3 bxc3 14. bxc3 Qa5 15. Bd2 Nxd4 $1 { This dynamic resource is the cornerstone of our counterplay, The game might continue } 16. cxd4 c3 17. O-O cxd2 18. Bxh5 Rxh5 19. Nxh5 Rc8 20. Nf4 Bc2 21. Qe2 Nh6 $44 { [%cal Gf8b4] Black has excellent compensation for the exchange. The next move is going to be ...Bb4. Of course, you are by no means obliged to remember these lines. Understanding the guiding principles in such positions is what matters most. } *
