1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nd2 e6 5. Nb3 {As we know, our move order is based on 5...a6. In this concrete case, however, the move order is not that important because we will get our thematic structure.} c5 6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. Nxc5 Qa5+ 8. c3 Qxc5 9. Be3 Qc7 10. f4 Nc6 11. Nf3 Nge7 12. Be2 {We are already quite familiar with this type of position. At this point, I decided to start with} h6 {By taking the g5-square under control, Black often wants to discourage White from meeting ...Be4 with Ng5.} 13. O-O Be4 14. Nd4 a6 {Exactly the same position could have arisen out of the 5...a6 move order. The position of interest arises after the moves} 15. Qd2 O-O 16. Rad1 Rac8 17. h3 {Now, I went for} Nxd4 {As we know. exchanging minor pieces is what Black wants in this structure. It's especially important for us to get rid of White's strong d4-knight.} 18. Bxd4 Nc6 {Another important move. After eliminating the d4-bishop, Black will be able to carry out the advance ...f7-f6. It goes without saying that ...Nf5 would have been possible as well.} 19. Qe3 Nxd4 20. Rxd4 {White is forced to recapture on d4 with a piece.} ({A typical mistake would be} 20. cxd4 $2 {trying to sustain the centre. Black's play on the c-file is too dangerous. After} Qa5 $17 {[%cal Ga5a2,Gc8c2] White has no satisfactory defence against the double threat of ...Qxa2 and ...Rc2.}) 20... f6 21. exf6 Rxf6 {[%cal Gc8f8] As usual, Black is ready to increase the pressure on f4 by means of ...Rcf8.} 22. Bd3 {This move is quite logical. White should eliminate our strong bishop in order to make use of the backward e6-pawn.} Bxd3 23. Rxd3 Rcf8 {It's time to draw some conclusions. In this kind of endgame with heavy pieces on the board, Black is usually slightly better because of the possibility of playing on the "f" and "c" files. White's main problem is the inferior activity of his rooks. The central pawn chain e6-d5 limits the activity of the white minor pieces. Note that the f4-pawn is far more vulnerable than the one on e6. After forcing the opponent's pieces to the defence of the f4-pawn, Black can further increase the pressure by means of simple moves such as ...Qd6 followed by ...Rc8-c4.} 24. Rd2 b5 {Gaining space on the queenside is always advantageous. Now, at any moment White should reckon with the advance ...b5-b4. After this break, White will either be left with a weak pawn on c3, or he will allow Black to have a protected passed pawn on d5. Since this was an online blitz game, I will not analyze the moves in too much detail. The idea of showing this game is to illustrate the nature of such endgames.} 25. Rdf2 Qd6 26. Qd4 Rc8 27. Qe3 {Finding himself in a position without constructive ideas, White starts shuffling around with his pieces.} Rc4 28. g3 Re4 29. Qd3 Qc5 $15 {[%cal Ge4e3,Ga6a5,Gb5b4] Even though precise play would allow White to maintain the balance, Black's position is obviously preferable. White should take measures against ...Re3. The idea of .. .a6-a5 followed by ...b5-b4 also comes into consideration. Later on, I managed to exploit the advantages of my position.} 30. Kg2 Re3 31. Qd2 a5 32. Rf3 Re4 33. Qf2 Qc6 34. Kh2 b4 35. cxb4 axb4 36. a3 Qc4 37. axb4 Re2 38. Kg1 Rxf2 39. R1xf2 Qxb4 40. Kg2 d4 41. Rd3 Qc4 42. Rfd2 e5 43. fxe5 Rf5 44. Rxd4 Qf1+ 45. Kh2 Rf2+ 0-1

