1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nd2 e6 5. Nb3 c5 6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. Nxc5 Qa5+ 8. c3 Qxc5 9. Be3 Qc7 10. f4 Ne7 11. Nf3 Nbc6 12. Be2 h6 13. O-O Be4 14. Nd4 a6 15. Qd2 O-O 16. Bd3 {Once again, White wants to exchange Black's active e4-bishop. The problem is that after exchanging two pairs of minor pieces, Black will completely solve his space issues. Additionally, White will remain with his worst minor piece - the dark-squared bishop.} Bxd3 17. Qxd3 b5 {This move, played on general grounds, is quite typical for Black games. Of course, it would have been better to exchange the knights immediately.} 18. Rad1 $6 {With this pointless move, White is playing into Black's hand.} ({Better would have been} 18. Nc2 {keeping the knight.}) 18... Nxd4 19. Bxd4 Nf5 {As we know, in order to carry out the typical ...f7-f6 advance, we need to exchange or kick back the d4-bishop.} 20. g4 {Even though this advance is positionally risky, White has nothing better.} Nxd4 21. cxd4 {We have reached an important position. Black is not quick enough to utilize the control of the c-file while White is ready for the advance f4-f5. There is an important rule which is very useful in this kind of French structure. Provided that the light-squared bishops have been exchanged when White has pawns on g4, f4, e5, and d4, our thematic reaction is} f5 $1 {This move often allows Black to eliminate White's space advantage. White's kingside attack is practically stopped.} 22. h3 ({Of course, the position arising after} 22. exf6 Rxf6 {[%cal Ga8f8] is favourable for Black. We know that even with the pawn being on g2 (instead of g4) , Black's position would be quite comfortable.}) 22... Qe7 23. Qg3 Rac8 {Black starts his queenside play. His position is already preferable from a practical point of view.} 24. gxf5 $6 {This positional mistake gives Black a huge advantage.} Rxf5 $17 {Black is already clearly better. Later on, I managed to convert the advantage without too much of a problem.} 25. Rc1 Rc4 26. Rxc4 bxc4 27. Kh2 Kh7 28. Rf2 Qa7 29. Rg2 Qf7 30. Rf2 g5 31. Qg4 Rxf4 32. Rxf4 gxf4 33. Kg2 Qg6 34. Kf2 Qc2+ 35. Kf3 Qe4+ 36. Kf2 Qxd4+ 37. Kg2 Qxe5 38. Kf3 Qe3+ 39. Kg2 Qg3+ 0-1

