1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Be3 { This move is designed to build a strong pawn centre. If given the opportunity, White is ready to proceed with c2-c3 followed by Nd2 and f2-f4. There are, however, two main drawbacks associated with this system. Very often, the e3-bishop tends to be vulnerable to ...Ne7 (h6) -f5 ideas. Additionally, if the moves f2-f4 and ...Qb6 are included, the unprotected e3-bishop makes the opposition on the diagonal a7-g1 favourable for Black. The second drawback is the problematic b2-pawn. Therefore, if White delays Nd2, ...Qb6 is always an issue. } 4... e6 { This is the strategic approach. I have decided to recommend this line because it's entirely based on understanding. } ( { The ambitious } 4... Qb6 { is also quite a decent option. Actually, this move was recommended by Pavel Eljanov in his second Caro-Kann database. } ) 5. Nd2 { This is probably the most precise move order. White is now ready to answer ...Qb6 with Nb3. } ( { Another important direction is } 5. c3 Qb6 6. Qb3 Nd7 { [%cal Gf7f6] Black is now ready to attack the centre with ...f7-f6. White's idea is to keep the space advantage by means of } 7. Nd2 f6 8. f4 { The problem is that Black has the powerful } 8... g5 { Remember this thematic idea. White's centre is now falling apart. } 9. exf6 { With this move, White not only parts with the space advantage, but also allows Black to execute an elegant positional idea. } ( { An alternative is } 9. Ngf3 gxf4 10. Bxf4 Bh6 $1 { The most precise continuation. Every exchange makes White's centre more vulnerable. } 11. Bxh6 { White has nothing better than going for the exchange. } ( { After } 11. Bg3 fxe5 12. Nxe5 Ngf6 $13 { [%csl Gd4,Gd5][%cal Gh6c1,Gf5b1] Black's bishops are extremely powerful. In some cases, even the white king might be in danger. } ) 11... Nxh6 12. exf6 ( { Exchanging the queens with } 12. Qxb6 axb6 { only helps Black. Now, the a8-rook is actively participating in the game. Fighting for the e5-square with } 13. exf6 Nxf6 14. Ne5 { [%csl Gc8,Gf5] does not bring any dividends. Balck can challenge White's control of e5 by means of simple moves - } 14... Nf7 15. Ndf3 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Nd7 $15 { Black is already slightly better. } ) 12... Nxf6 $13 { [%cal Gh8g8,Gf6e4] Black has an excellent counterplay in this position. Sooner or later, the queens will be exchanged. At any moment, we can play moves such as ...Rg8 followed by ...Ne4. The control of the g-file is a very important factor in such positions. 1/2 (23) Grischuk,A (2663) -Leko,P (2745) /Linares 2001 } ) 9... g4 $1 { This is the idea. With one move, Black is practically killing all white minor pieces. We can take the f6-pawn whenever we want. One of my online blitz games went } 10. a4 Ngxf6 11. a5 Qc7 12. Ne2 Bd6 $17 { Black already has a huge advantage. We can now, consider the advance of the h-pawn. It's far from easy for White to untangle in this position. } ) 5... Nd7 { The most flexible continuation. Black keeps all the options on the table. Depending on White's response, we can play ...Qb6, ...f7-f6, or ...Ne7 followed by ...Bg6 and ...Nf5. Sometimes, even ...c6-c5 comes into consideration. } 6. Ngf3 { The most natural continuation. White develops a piece and keeps the centre under control. } ( { After } 6. c3 Qb6 7. Qb3 { we are going to transpose to 5.c3. } ) ( { If White makes unnatural and slow move such as } 6. Be2 { This is usually a sign that we should strike with } 6... f6 { [%cal Ge5f6,Gg8f6] As we will see on many occasions, the fight for the e5-square is a central theme in this variation. } 7. Ngf3 { Once again, White has nothing better than this natural move. } ( { When you see the advance } 7. f4 { this means that you should seriously consider } 7... Qb6 { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gf6e5,Gf4e5,Gd7e5,Gd4e5,Gb6e3] Now, it becomes obvious why the e3-bishop is vulnerable after the advance f2-f4. Black is threatening to win a pawn with ...fxe5 followed by ...Nxe5. } 8. exf6 { This is a move Black usually wants to provoke. } ( { The move } 8. Nb3 $6 { is basically a pawn sacrifice, but White doesn't have sufficient compensation for the pawn. Before taking on e5, it's a good idea to insert the moves ... a7-a5 and ...a2-a4 - } 8... a5 9. a4 fxe5 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gd7e5] } 10. Nf3 exf4 11. Bxf4 Ngf6 $17 { Black has an obvious advantage. } ) 8... Ngxf6 { Had the white pawn been on f2, this structure would have been more or less acceptable for him. With a pawn on f4, however, White has two major problems - passive dark-squared bishops and weak light squares. One game saw } 9. Nb3 a5 10. a4 Bb4+ { It makes a lot of sense to include this check before putting the bishop on d6. The idea is to provoke the advance c2-c3 after which the b3-knight is quite vulnerable. } 11. c3 Bd6 12. Nf3 h6 13. g3 g5 $1 { Another thematic move in this structure. The advance ...g7-g5 is a typical device that Black uses to destroy White's centre. Taking twice on g5 does not work because Black will take on g3 at the end of the line. } 14. Ne5 { This position was reached in the game 1/2 (19) Pergel, L (2327) -Prohaszka, P (2506) /Zalakaros 2008/CBM 124 Extra. Now, the simplest would have been } 14... g4 $17 { [%cal Gh6h5] with ...h6-h5 to follow. Black enjoys complete control of the position. } ) ( { After } 7. exf6 { [%mdl 12] } 7... Ngxf6 { Black reaches a typically favorable pawn structure. We are ready to proceed with ...Bd6 and ...0-0. The only way of using the delayed Nf3 is } 8. g4 Bg6 9. h4 { [%cal Gh4h5,Yg4g5][%mdl 4] A very ambitious apporach. White is planning to gain further space with h4-h5 followed by g4-g5. On the other hand, if Black handles the position precisely, White's strategy might backfire. } ( { After } 9. g5 $6 Ne4 $15 { White does not have enough compensation for the kingside weaknesses. } ) 9... h6 10. Nh3 { [%cal Gh3f4] The most challenging continuation. The threat is Nf4. } ( { After } 10. h5 Bh7 { White's kingside pawns lose flexibility. Black is ready to follow with ...Bd6 and ... 0-0. Later on, he will try to get the advance ...e6-e5. } ) 10... Bd6 11. Nf4 Bxf4 { The most straightforward solution. The f4-knight shouldn't be tolerated for too long. } 12. Bxf4 Qe7 { [%cal Ge6e5] Once again, preparing the advance ... e6-e5 is Black's most logical idea. The following sequence seems quite logical to me - } 13. Rh3 O-O 14. g5 Ng4 15. Bxg4 Rxf4 16. Qe2 e5 $17 { with an obvious advantage for Black. } ) 7... Qc7 { [%cal Ge5f6,Gg8f6] A logical move. Black keeps putting pressure on e5. } 8. Bf4 { White wants to keep his space advantage. } ( { As we already know, the strucuture arising after } 8. exf6 Ngxf6 { is quite favourable for Black. The game might continue } 9. c4 Bd6 10. c5 Bf4 $13 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Ge6e5] Black is doing more than fine. In the next couple of moves, he is going to carry out the thematic advance ...e6-e5. } ) ( { The pawn sacrifice } 8. O-O fxe5 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Qxe5 { provides White with compensation which is enough only for equality. After } 11. Nf3 Qd6 { Kosintseva, T played } 12. c4 { in her game against Ushenina, A. Unfortunately for White, Black manages to complete the development without any problems. } ( { An alternative is } 12. Nd4 Nf6 13. Nxf5 exf5 14. c4 Be7 15. Qc2 Qd7 $11 { White's compensation for the pawn is enough only for equality. } ) 12... Nf6 13. Nd4 Bg6 14. Qb3 Qd7 15. Bf4 Bc5 $17 { This position occurred in the game 1/2 (19) -1/2 Kosintseva, T-Ushenina, A/15th European Team Championshi 2005 (35) . Black is about to complete the development. White does not have any compensation for the pawn. } ) 8... fxe5 9. dxe5 { The most principled choice. White wants to sustain the space advantage. } ( { Black does not have any problems after } 9. Nxe5 { [%csl Gd4,Ge5] since this structure is typically favourable for him. } 9... Bd6 10. Ndf3 { [%csl Ge5] The most solid continuation. As we will witness, however, White does not have enough resources to sustain the blockade on e5. } ( 10. g4 $6 { only creates additional weaknesses. } 10... Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Bg3 ( { In case of } 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. c3 e5 14. h4 O-O-O $15 { Black is alredy better in view of his central domination and White's vulnerable king. } ) 12... Bxg3 13. fxg3 O-O-O $13 { [%cal Ge6e5] Once again, playing with Black is far easier. He is ready to proceed with ...e6-e5. } ) ( { After } 10. Bg4 Bxe5 11. dxe5 Ne7 $15 { White will have hard time defending the e5-pawn. } ) 10... Ne7 11. O-O Nxe5 12. Bxe5 ( { The alternative } 12. Nxe5 { is harmless. For instance, after } 12... O-O 13. Bg3 Ng6 14. Nxg6 Bxg6 $13 { Black is doing more than fine. The advance ...e6-e5 is already on the agenda. } ) 12... Ng6 13. Bg3 O-O $13 { [%cal Gd6g3,Gh2g3,Ge6e5] Once again, the advance ...e6-e5 is coming. Black does not have any problems whatsoever. } ) 9... Ne7 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gg8e7,Ge7g6] It turns out that the e5-pawn is quite vulnerable. White should now reckon with the threat of ...Ng6 on the next move. } 10. Nd4 ( { After } 10. h4 $6 { [%csl Ge5] } 10... Ng6 11. Bh2 O-O-O 12. Ng5 Ndxe5 { White does not have compensation for the pawn. The most principled approach is } 13. g4 { This position was reached in the game Shirov - Bologan, 2006. At this point, Black could have played } 13... Be4 $1 14. f3 Bd6 $1 15. fxe4 Rhf8 $19 { Black is already winning since the white king is utterly vulnerable. } ) 10... Ng6 11. Be3 Qxe5 12. N2f3 Qf6 $15 { Once again, White does not have enough compensation for the pawn. } ) ( { This move supports the centre but makes the e3-bishop quite vulnerable. When we see this advance, a very typical reaction would be } 6. f4 Qb6 { Now, White should reckon with several pawn breaks - ...c6-c5, ...f7-f6, and ...g7-g5. } 7. Nb3 { stopping ...c6-c5, but putting the knight on a vulnerable position. } 7... a5 8. a4 g5 $1 { This typical idea is possible only because of the vulnerable e3-bishop. The idea is that fxg5 can be answered with ...Nxe5. } 9. Nf3 g4 10. Nfd2 h5 $15 { Black is already better due to his kingside space advantage and more active pieces. } ) 6... Ne7 7. Nh4 { The most principled choice. White is going after the bishop pair. } ( 7. Be2 h6 { A typical move in such structures. Black is preparing ... Bh7 followed by ...Nf5. } 8. O-O Bh7 9. Nb3 { The most challenging option. White frees the d2-square for the bishop and fights against the advance ...c6-c5. } ( { Dubious is } 9. c4 Nf5 { With the dark-squared bishop already being commited to e3, this is the most principled choice. } ( { It goes without saying that the structure arising after } 9... dxc4 10. Nxc4 Nd5 $13 { is also quite playable for Black. } ) 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Qb3 Rb8 { [%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Black is now ready to complete the development by means of ...Be7 followed by ...0-0. We are not in a hurry to take the bishop on e3 yet since this opportunity will not go away. Black is doing fine. } ) ( { The ambitious } 9. g4 { fighting against ...Nf5 will most likely backfire. Black can immediately strike in the centre with } 9... f6 $1 10. c4 { White wants to hold his space advantage at any price. } ( { In case of } 10. exf6 gxf6 { [%cal Gd8b6,Ge8c8] Black has a very strong counterplay. We will proceed with ...Qb6 followed by ...0-0-0. In the long run, the weakening g2-g4 advance will tell. } ) 10... fxe5 11. dxe5 c5 $1 { This precise move practically refutes White's concept. Now, the threat is ...d5-d4. The following sequence is quite characteristic for the position. } 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Qb3 Qb6 14. Bb5 O-O-O 15. Nc4 Qc7 16. Nd6+ Bxd6 17. exd6 Qxd6 18. Qa3 Nxe3 19. fxe3 Qb6 20. Bxd7+ Rxd7 21. Rac1 Rd5 22. b4 c4 23. Rxc4+ Kb8 $15 { Black is better in view of his superior bishop and safer King. } ) 9... Nf5 10. Bd2 Rc8 { Organizing the advance ...c6-c5 is our best attempt to create counterplay. } 11. a4 { This typical move is designed to grab queenside space by means of a4-a5.Black is now ready for this thematic break. } ( { Another thematic continuation is } 11. Rc1 { The idea is that White can answer . ..c6-c5 with c2-c4. The following line shows the main strategic ideas in the position. } 11... Be7 12. Bd3 O-O 13. g4 { This advance is White's only constructive plan in the position. } 13... Nh4 14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Nxh4 Bxh4 16. f4 Kg8 { [%cal Gf7f6] Removing the king from the exposed position and preparing the thematic . ..f7-f6. After } 17. f5 Bg5 $13 { [%cal Gc6c5] Black has excellent counterplay in this complex position. The advance ...c6-c5 is already on the agenda. } ) 11... c5 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Nxc5 Nxc5 14. Bb5+ Kf8 $13 { [%cal Gh7g6,Gf8g8] Black is doing fine in this complex position. Our first priority is bringing the king into safety by means of ... Bg6 followed by ...Kg8-h7. Once Black manages to stabilize the position, his compact pawn structure, as well as lack of weaknesses, will offer good long-term prospects. } ) 7... Qb6 { Fortunately, Black is just in time to play this important move which is based on a subtle tactical nuance. } 8. Nb3 { Unfortunately for White, this time the advance ...c6-c5 cannot be stopped. } ( { Too slow is } 8. Rb1 { After } 8... h6 { [%cal Gf5h7] } 9. Nxf5 Nxf5 10. c3 O-O-O $5 11. Qf3 f6 $13 { Black has fantastic counterplay. } ) 8... c5 $1 { This is the point! White should act quickly in view of the threat of ...c5-c4. } 9. g4 { The following couple of moves are quite logical - } ( { The tactical justification of Black's last move is } 9. dxc5 $4 Qb4+ { [%csl Rh4][%cal Gb4h4]  winning a piece. } ) 9... Bg6 10. dxc5 Qc7 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. f4 { So far, White has been playing in the most principled fashion. It turns out, however, that his development is not sufficient to sustain the huge space advantage. Hence, White's position is vulnerable to different kinds of strikes. After } 12... g5 13. fxg5 Qxe5 14. Qd4 Nc6 15. Qxe5 Ndxe5 16. Bf4 Nxg4 17. Be2 Nge5 $15 { Black is already slightly better, in view of his better central control and superior pawn structure. } *
