{ In this example, we will examine the move 4.c4. Even though this advance is more effective after the inclusion of the moves h2-h4 and ...h7-h5, we need to handle the arising positions with care. The first critical position arises after the moves } 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. c4 e6 5. Nc3 Bb4 { This fighting continuation is my suggestion for Black. At any moment, Black is ready to exchange the dark-squared bishop for the c3-knight. After this exchange, Black is going to apply to so-called light square strategy. The reason is that we control the light squares with three minor pieces while only two white minor pieces do so. } 6. Qb3 { This is by far White's main continuation. Black should immediately clarify his intentions. } ( { Another thematic structure arises after } 6. cxd5 cxd5 { Practice has shown that Black is doing perfectly fine in this structure. He can proceed with simple moves such as ...Nc6, ...Nge7, and ...0-0. It goes without saying that at any moment Black is ready to give the dark-squared bishop for the knight. White's most challenging continuation is } ( { A positional mistake would be } 6... exd5 $6 { since after } 7. Bd3 Bxd3 8. Qxd3 $16 { White's kingside majority is pretty dangerous. } ) 7. h4 { Besides gaining space on the kingside, White starts playing against the f5-bishop. The threat is g2-g4, thus winning a piece. } ( { Harmless is } 7. Bd3 { when the game might continue } 7... Ne7 8. Ne2 Nbc6 9. O-O O-O 10. Be3 { At this point, Black has different options at his disposal. The most straightforward continuation is the break } 10... f6 { eliminating White's space advantage. } ( { A decent alternative is } 10... Rc8 11. a3 Bxc3 12. Nxc3 h6 13. g4 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 f5 $15 { Black was already better in the game 0-1 (39) Alekseenko, K (2687) -Ter Sahakyan,S (2605) Chess.com INT 2022. Later on, it will be difficult for White to fight against Black's play on the light squares. } ) 11. exf6 Rxf6 $15 { [%cal Ga2a3,Gb4d6] Black managed to achieve a fantastic French structure. White cannot use the weakness of the e5-square. Additionally, we are no longer planning to part with the dark-squared bishop. For instance, the advance a2-a3 will be met by ...Bd6. } ) ( { In a couple of games White played } 7. Qa4+ { which seems completely harmless. A reasonable follow-up would be } 7... Nc6 8. Bb5 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Ne7 10. Ne2 { This position was reached in the game 1/2-1/2 (56) Okike, D (2177) -Solon, N (2306) Chess.com INT 2021. At this point, the simplest would have been } 10... a6 11. Bxc6+ Nxc6 12. Ng3 Bg6 $15 { when Black is slightly better in view of the superior pawn structure. Later on, he will start playing against the backward c3-pawn. } ) 7... h6 { The most precise reaction. Besides preventing White's threat, Black also keeps the dark squares under control. } 8. g4 Be4 { Once again, before putting the bishop on h7, it is useful to provoke the weakening f2-f3 advance. } 9. f3 Bh7 10. h5 { This move, played by Caruana, is the most consistent continuation. White keeps gaining space on the kingside. Later on, he can follow with Bd3. After the exchange of the light-squared bishops, Black should reckon with the advance of the f-pawn. } ( { In case of } 10. a3 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Nc6 12. Ne2 f6 13. exf6 Qxf6 $13 { Black is doing perfectly fine. We are ready to proceed with ...0-0-0 followed by ... Nge7. This complex position is practically easier for Black in view of White's vulnerable king. 0-1 (26) Daggupati,B (2513) -Liang,J (2529) Los Angeles 2023 } ) 10... Nc6 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 { This position occurred in the game 1/2-1/2 (69) Caruana,F (2747) -Shimanov,A (2616) Almaty 2022. At this point, Black's most resolute reaction would have been } 12... Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Nge7 14. Ne2 Qd7 $13 { [%cal Gf3f4,Gf7f5] Black is doing fine. An important nuance in this pawn structure is that the advance f3-f4 should always be met with ...f7-f5. } ) ( { Another popular direction is } 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 { In this position, Black has more than one good option. The most popular plan includes 7...Ne7 followed by . ..8...c5. In my opinion, however, even more precise is the immediate } 7... c5 $13 { which surprisingly turns out to be a novely. Black is planning to increase the pressure on the centre with ...Nc6. The best computer line goes } 8. dxc5 Qa5 9. cxd5 Qxc3+ 10. Bd2 Qxe5+ 11. Be3 Qxd5 12. Bb5+ Nc6 13. Qxd5 exd5 14. Bxc6+ bxc6 $13 { [%cal Gf7f6,Gg8e7,Ge8f7] followed by ...f7-f6 and ...Kf7. White still needs to prove compensation for the pawn. } ) ( { In case of } 6. Nf3 Ne7 7. Qb3 a5 $13 { we reach a position that is pretty similar to the main line. All the thematic ideas remain valid. } ) 6... a5 $1 { An important inclusion. Black is ready to part with the dark-squared bishop, but only after provoking the advance a2-a3. There two reasons why a2-a3 plays into Black's hand. First of all, after a2-a3, White does not have the option of developing the dark-squared bishop via a3. At the same time, by putting the pawn on a3, White also further weakens the light squares on the queenside. } 7. a3 dxc4 { An important inclusion. By forcing the white bishop to c4, Black is getting ready to win an important tempo with ...b7-b5. Additionally the queen is now putting pressure on d4. } 8. Bxc4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 { Even though this is the more common recapture, it allows Black to seize the control of the light squares in a thematic way. } ( { Another important structure arises after } 9. Qxc3 { The fact that one pair of minor pieces has already been exchanged makes White's space advantage less significant. Additionally, Black's superior structure provides good compensation for White's bishop pair. Here is how the play might continue - } 9... Ne7 10. Ne2 Nd7 11. O-O Nb6 12. Ba2 Nbd5 13. Qf3 O-O { After completing the development, Black is doing perfectly fine. He is now ready to start putting pressure on d4. Our plan includes moves such as ...Qb6 followed by ...Rfd8, ... Bg6, and ...Nf5. On many occasions, we can even consider the advance ...c6-c5. } 14. Bg5 { This natural continuation is not threatening at all. Black wants to play ...Qb6 anyway. } ( { More ambitious would be } 14. Ng3 Bg6 15. h4 { when Black should figure out how to handle White's kingside initiative. The best approach would be } 15... h6 16. h5 Bh7 17. Ne4 Nf5 18. Rd1 Kh8 $13 { Black is doing fine. White should already reckon with the advance ...f7-f6. } ) 14... Qb6 15. b3 h6 16. Be3 { This position was reached in the game 0-1 (35) Sliwicka, A (2333) -Girya, O (2464) Tornelo INT 2020. Now, Black should have played } 16... Nxe3 17. fxe3 ( { In case of } 17. Qxe3 Rfd8 $17 { Black is again considerably better in view of his more active pieces and better pawn structure. The pressure on d4 is really annoying. } ) 17... c5 $17 { with a huge advantage. White's position is falling apart. } ) 9... b5 { This move marks the beginning of a typical positional operation which is designed to get full control of the light squares. The following couple of moves are quite logical - } 10. Be2 a4 11. Qb2 Ne7 12. Nf3 Nd7 13. O-O Nb6 { Black is controlling the entire complex of light squares. The knights will be placed on c4 and d5. At the same time, White's bishop pair is completely meaningless. Below, I provide an online blitz game of mine which provides a typical illustration of the main ideas in the position. } 14. Nh4 Be4 15. Qd2 h6 16. Bb2 $2 Ned5 17. g3 Nc4 18. Bxc4 bxc4 19. Rae1 Bd3 $19 20. f4 Bxf1 21. Rxf1 Rb8 22. f5 Qg5 23. Bc1 Qxd2 24. Bxd2 Rb2 25. Rf2 Rb3 26. fxe6 fxe6 27. Ng6 Rg8 28. Nf4 Nxf4 29. gxf4 Rxa3 { At this point, White resigned. } *
