{ In this example, we shall take a look at one of the oldest systems against the Caro-Kann Defence - Advance Variation with 4.Bd3. The basic position of this line arises after } 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Bd3 Bxd3 5. Qxd3 e6 { For a very long time, this variation was considered to be quite harmless for Black. Such an evaluation was always justified by the fact that after the exchange of the light-squared bishops, Black enjoys a dream version of the French Defence. Modern computers, however, proved that things are far from simple. It turns out that if Black keeps making standard moves, White's kingside attacking prospects shouldn't be underestimated. In this example, I will show all the must-know strategic ideas as well as the most important theoretical variations. Due to the rich history of this line, thousands of games have been played from this position. It is therefore impossible to examine every single little move. Nevertheless, keep in mind that regardless of what your opponent plays, the character of the position wouldn't change much. } 6. Ne2 { This is the most challenging continuation. Modern practice shows that the white knights are optimally placed on e2 and f3. } ( { Another important direction is } 6. Nf3 { when Black can immediately strike with } 6... c5 { Obviously, we want to increase the pressure on the centre by means of ...Nc6 and ...Qb6. There are, however, some important subtleties. At this point, White should play } 7. c3 ( { Going after the b7-pawn by means of } 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Qb5+ { is quite dubious.After } ( { Obviously, after } 8. c4 Ne7 $11 { Black has nothing to worry about. } ) 8... Nd7 9. Qxb7 Ne7 10. O-O O-O $44 { [%cal Ge7g6] Black has more than enough compensation for the the pawn. Our next move is going to be ...Ng6. } ) 7... Nc6 8. O-O a6 $5 { To my surprise, this precise move has never been played in this exact position. While waiting for White to clarify his intentions, Black is making a useful waiting move.The most natural follow-up would be } ( { It's important to know that } 8... Qb6 $6 { can be answered with } 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. b4 $1 Be7 11. Na3 a6 12. c4 $36 { when White better development and space advantage provide him with tremendous initiative. } ) 9. Be3 cxd4 10. cxd4 Nge7 11. Nc3 Nf5 $11 { with equality. Black is ready to complete the development with ...Be7 followed by ...f7-f6. } ) ( { Natural but less precise is } 6. f4 { This move not only restricts the dark-squared bishop but also weakens the light squares.Black will continue with } 6... c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. Nf3 Nh6 { This flexible move is possible because the advance f2-f4 closes the way of the bishop. Black is now ready to increase the pressure on the centre with ...Qb6 and ...Nf5. } 9. Be3 ( 9. O-O Qb6 $15 { is even a better version for Black since White can no longer develop the dark-squared bishop. } ) 9... Qb6 10. Nbd2 { This is the main point behind the move order starting with 9.Be3. Now, 10...Qxb2 can be answered with 11.Rb1. Black's play, however, is very easy - } 10... Nf5 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Bxc5 Qxc5 13. Nb3 Qb6 $15 { Black is already better in view of his compact structure and more active pieces. It's far from easy for White to find a safe haven for the king. At the same time, he must reckon with the advance ...a7-a5-a4. } ) 6... c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. O-O Qb6 $1 { It is very important to start with this precise move. } ( { The type of position White is looking for arises after } 8... Nge7 9. Nd2 Nf5 10. Nf3 cxd4 11. cxd4 Be7 { With the knights being placed on e2 and f3, White can start active actions on the kingside by means of the thematic } 12. g4 $1 { when after } 12... Nh4 13. Nxh4 Bxh4 14. f4 Rc8 15. Bd2 $14 { White has a clear advantage. Black does not have any counterplay in return for White's kingside activity. } ) 9. a3 { Before going for Nd2-f3, White takes the b4-square under control. } ( { The immediate } 9. Nd2 { is very well met by } 9... cxd4 10. cxd4 Nb4 { This continuation practically forces a draw. } ( { If you want to keep fighting, a good alternative would be } 10... a5 11. Nf3 Qa6 12. Qd1 a4 $13 { with a complex battle ahead. 0-1 (37) Villanueva,M (2465) -Moussard,J (2621) Barcelona 2021 } ) 11. Qb3 Nc6 $11 { White has nothing better than repeating the position. } ) ( { With the knight being place on e2, instead of f3, the idea } 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. b4 { does not work quite well. After } 10... Bf8 $1 11. Bf4 Nge7 $15 { [%cal Ge7g6] Black is already better due to the vulnerable e5-pawn. He is ready to follow with ...Ng6 on the next move. } ) 9... Qa6 $1 { This is the key idea that you should remember. By immediately challenging the queen, we do not allow White to achieve the optimal attacking setup based on Nd2-f3. } 10. Qd1 { White should refrain from exchanging queens. } ( { Note that the structure arising after } 10. Qxa6 bxa6 { [%cal Gc5c4] is quite favourable for Black. The possibility of playing along the b-file is far more important than the doubled pawns which cannot be attacked. Black is now threatening to fix the b2-pawn by means of ... c5-c4. At this point, a logical sequence would be } 11. b4 cxd4 12. cxd4 Rb8 { [%cal Ga6a5] An important move. The threat is ...a6-a5. } 13. Nbc3 Nge7 $13 { [%cal Ge8d7,Ge7c8,Gc8b6,Gb6c4] Black is doing fine due to White's queenside weaknesses. After putting the king to d7, we can consider the maneuver ... Ne7-c8-b6-c4. It goes without saying that whenever White puts a knight on c5, we will immediately take it. } ) 10... Nge7 { A natural follow-up. } ( { A good alternative is } 10... Rc8 11. Be3 { This position occurred in the game 0-1 (35) Andriska,Z (2062) -Kovacs,A (2120) Hungary 2010. Now, Black could have played } 11... Nge7 { with the idea of meeting } 12. dxc5 { with } 12... Nxe5 13. Nd4 Nc4 $13 { [%cal Ge6e5,Gg7g6] Black has all the chances to take over in this position. We can already consider further expanding in the centre with ...e6-e5. } ) 11. dxc5 { The most principled choice. Otherwise, Black is doing fine after ...Nf5. } 11... Nxe5 12. Nd4 { This position was reached in the game 1-0 (34) Oberoi, S (2283) -Chandra, A (2479) Rockville 2022. Now, the simple } 12... Nd3 13. a4 Nxc5 $11 { would have provided Black with a decent position which is objectively equal. } *
