1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Ne2 { The main idea of this system is to proceed with Ng3 followed by h2-h4. We will focus just on this main option. All other possibilities that White might try are less challenging and lead to structures that we know. } 4... e6 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 h5 7. Be2 { This is White's main point. The h5-pawn cannot be protected. Nevertheless, Black has an excellent counterplay in the centre. } ( { Sometimes, White tries } 7. Bd3 { After } 7... Bxd3 8. Qxd3 c5 9. c3 Nc6 $15 { Black is already slightly better. The White knight is misplaced on f3 in this French type of play. } ) 7... c5 $1 { This is the right approach. We should immediately strike in the centre. } 8. c3 Nc6 { It turns out that we the white knight being on g3, the pressure on d4 is very effective. White should probably defend the pawn with } 9. Be3 ( { After } 9. Bxh5 $2 Bxh5 10. Nxh5 cxd4 11. cxd4 Qb6 $19 { White's position is falling apart. } ) ( { Another bad move is } 9. Nxh5 $2 cxd4 10. cxd4 Bxh5 11. Bxh5 g6 12. Be2 Rxh4 13. Rxh4 Qxh4 $17 { with a tremendous advantage for Black. } ) 9... Qb6 { Black is playing in a French style. White cannot keep the position intact without accepting major concessions. } 10. Qb3 { This move allows a transition into an endgame which is clearly favourable for Black. } ( { After } 10. b3 cxd4 11. cxd4 Nb4 12. O-O Nc2 $17 { Black is winning an exchange. } ) 10... c4 $1 11. Qxb6 axb6 12. Nd2 b5 $17 { [%cal Gb5b4] Black has an obvious advantage. The queenside play is very strong. The next move is going to be ...b5-b4. } *
