{ This lecture is dedicated to White's most challenging line against the Caro-Kann Defence - the Short System. This variation is characterized by the moves } 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 { Thousands of games have been played from this position. Black has tried a variety of different systems. White, however, always manages to put an annoying positional pressure. Black's main problem is that the lack of space makes it difficult to develop the kingside pieces. After a long consideration, I have decided to recommend the pet line of Eljanov - } 5... Nd7 6. O-O a5 $5 { This is probably the most useful waiting move in the position. As you will see in this lecture, gaining space on the queenside is very important for both sides. Depending on White's reaction, Black will decide how to develop the kingside pieces. If allowed, Black will obviously follow with ...a5-a4. One of the main points behind our system is that the most popular and natural } ( { The immediate } 6... f6 $6 { can be met with } 7. c4 fxe5 8. dxe5 Bc5 9. Nc3 { [%csl Rc5][%cal Gc3a4] with Na4 to follow. White has an obvious advantage. Hence, the inclusion of the moves a2-a4 and ...a7-a5 is very useful for Black. } ) 7. a4 { is well met by } 7... f6 { Black's idea is to proceed with ...fxe5 followed by ...Bc5. The system with 6. ..a5 is quite rare and fresh. Therefore, I consider it to be a very good practical weapon against the Short Variation. Once again, the knowledge of the typical structures and strategic ideas is way more important than the concrete theory. } *
