1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7 6. O-O h6 { This useful prophylactic move has been tried in many games. Black makes for the bishop and prevents White from exchanging it. Another idea is that in some positions, Black can go for ...g7-g5. } 7. a4 $5 { I like the entire concept starting with a2-a4 and consider it to be the most promising plan in this pawn structure. White is planning to gain even more space with a4-a5. The b1-knight can be developed via a3 to c2. As it regularly happens in this system, after closing the queenside, White can focus on his kingside play. } 7... Ne7 ( { Another possibility is } 7... a5 { preventing the capture of space. After that, however, it is very difficult to carry out the planned advance c6-c5 since the b5-square will become very weak. White can make use of this weakness by means of the maneuver Nb1-a3-b5. } 8. c3 Ne7 9. Na3 $5 Bh7 { Black struggles to coordinate his minor pieces due to the lack of space. With his last move, he frees the f5-square for the knight. } ( { In this position, the move } 9... g5 { is risky. White should follow with } 10. Ne1 { [%cal Gf2f4,Ge1d3] In this structure, this is a typical knight maneuver. White relocates the knight to d3 and prepares the break f2-f4. } 10... Bg7 11. Nd3 $5 ( { The straightforward } 11. f4 { is also good enough. The game may follow with } 11... gxf4 12. Nd3 Qb6 13. Kh1 Ng6 14. Nxf4 Nxf4 15. Rxf4 $16 { when White is clearly better. 1-0 (25) Zhigalko,S (2635) -Tari,A (2593) Khanty-Mansiysk 2017 } ) 11... Qc7 12. Nc2 f6 ( { In this pawn structure, castling long is very dangerous, because White can open the queenside with b2-b4. For example: } 12... O-O-O 13. b4 f6 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. bxa5 Qxa5 16. Ba3 Ng6 17. Bb4 Qc7 18. a5 $18 { [%cal Ga5a6] White has a winning attack. } ) 13. Bh5+ Kd8 14. f4 gxf4 15. exf6 Nxf6 16. Bxf4 $16 ) 10. Nc2 Nf5 { The knight is not stable on this square because White can easily execute the advance g2-g4. } ( { Safer would be } 10... c5 { In this case, however, the weakness of the b5-square might tell in the long run. } 11. Nfe1 { [%cal Ge2d3, Gh7d3,Ge1d3,Gf2f4] White clears the way of the queen and prepares Bd3. After the exchange of the bishops, the d3-square will be occupied by the knight. } 11... Nc6 12. Bd3 Bxd3 13. Nxd3 cxd4 14. cxd4 Rc8 15. Be3 Qb6 { With the black pawn being on a7, instead of a5, this would have been a normal position. Now, White can play } 16. Na3 $1 { underlining the weakness of b5. } 16... Bxa3 17. Rxa3 Ne7 18. Rb3 Qa6 19. Rb5 { Once again, White makes use of the weak b5-square. } 19... O-O 20. g4 $14 { [%cal Gg1h1,Gf1g1,Gd3f4,Gg4g5] White opens a second battlefield. Later on, he can continue with the kingside play by means of simple moves such as Kh1, Rg1 followed by Nf4 and g4-g5. } ) 11. Bd3 Be7 12. g4 $1 { White makes use of the unstable f5-knight. } 12... Nh4 13. Nxh4 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 Bxh4 15. f4 Qb6 16. Kg2 $16 { White has a huge advantage. Actually, in this position there is no safe place for Black's king. If Black castles short, then White can proceed with f4-f5. In the case of castling long, White always has b2-b4. } ) 8. a5 $1 { White keeps following his plan. } 8... a6 ( { Allowing a5-a6 is dangerous. For example, } 8... g5 { is well met by } 9. a6 $1 { breaking Black's pawn chain and creating new weaknesses. } 9... b5 { Too dangerous. After the moves ... b7-b5 and g7-g5, the black king cannot find a safe place. } ( { The modest } 9... b6 { does not solve the problems either. White just plays the thematic } 10. Ne1 $5 { [%cal Gf2f4] preparing f2-f4. } 10... c5 { With the b5-square being weakened, this advance is not a good idea. } ( { Nevertheless, it is very difficult to give Black an advise. Normal moves also lead to a very bad position. For example, after } 10... Bg7 11. f4 Qc7 12. Bh5 gxf4 13. Bxf4 Bg6 14. Na3 O-O-O 15. Nd3 $16 { White has a big advantage. The queenside can be easily opened with c2-c4. } ) 11. c3 $16 Nc6 12. Na3 { [%cal Ga3b5] A recurring idea in such positions. The knight is going to occupy the b5-square. } 12... Be7 13. Nb5 O-O 14. f4 $16 { Black is strategically lost due to his kingside weaknesses. } ) 10. Nbd2 f6 11. Nb3 Bg7 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Bd2 $16 { White has a clear advantage due to Black's numerous weaknesses. } ) 9. b4 $1 { By fixing the structure on the queenside, White completely eliminates Black's counterplay. In the future, before starting to play on the kingside, White can consider bringing his knight to c5. } 9... Nc8 { The knight will be relocated to the square b5-square. } ( { An aggressive idea is } 9... Qc7 { Black is planning to castle long and start pushing the kingside pawns. Nevertheless, White's queenside play is faster. The following line is a good illustration of White's strategy in such positions. } 10. Nc3 O-O-O 11. Na4 g5 12. Nd2 f6 13. exf6 Nxf6 14. Nb3 Ng6 15. Rb1 Bd6 16. Nbc5 { White does not care about the h2-pawn. In such positions, time is what matters! } 16... Bxh2+ 17. Kh1 Rde8 18. b5 $1 cxb5 19. Bxb5 axb5 20. Rxb5 $18 { White managed to open the queenside and Black is lost. } ) ( { Another possibility is } 9... Bh7 { planning ... Ng6. As often happens, however, black minor pieces lack space. Therefore, Black cannot coordinate his forces. } 10. Nc3 Ng6 11. Rb1 f6 12. Na4 Be7 13. Bd3 O-O 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Re1 $16 { White enjoys a big advantage since Black has poor coordination and many weaknesses. 1/2 (30) Kravtsiv,M (2644) -Bernadskiy,V (2547) Kiev 2018 } ) 10. c3 Na7 11. Ne1 $5 { A thematic manoeuvre. White is planning to exchange the light-squared bishops via d3. At the same time, after the exchange, the queen can occupy the favourable g4-square. } 11... Nb5 ( 11... Qc7 12. Na3 O-O-O 13. Bd3 Bxd3 14. Nxd3 Be7 15. Bd2 Kb8 16. Qe2 $14 ) 12. Bd3 Bxd3 13. Nxd3 Be7 ( 13... Qc7 { looks dubious. After a long castling, the black king will not feel safe. } 14. Bd2 O-O-O 15. Na3 Nxa3 16. Rxa3 Be7 17. Ra2 $16 ) 14. Qg4 g6 15. Be3 Kf8 16. Rc1 Kg7 17. Nd2 $14 { White has a solid advantage due to his extra space and mobile pieces. } *
