{ Together with ...f7-f6, the advance ... c6-c5 is Black's main source of counterplay in the Advance Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence. Nevertheless, this break usually requires some preparation. Let's take a look at the position on the diagram. Given White's superior development, Black cannot play the immediate ...c6-c5 in view of c2-c4. Hence, Black should start developing his pieces. The typical way of preparing ...Ne7 is } 1... h6 $1 { The idea of this thematic move is to make room for the light-squared bishop. } ( { The immediate } 1... Ne7 { is dubious in view of } 2. Nh4 { when White is getting the bishop pair. } ) 2. Re1 { [%cal Gd2f1,Gf1g3] By means of this move, White usually prepares the maneuver Nd2-f1-g3. } 2... Ne7 3. Nf1 Bg6 $1 { [%cal Gc6c5] Another key moment for your understanding of these positions. Before playing ...c6-c5, Black usually retreats with the bishop. The problem is that the immediate ... c6-c5 can be met by dxc5 followed by Nd4. There is, however, another logical question. Which is the best retreat square for the bishop - h7 or g6? Practice, as well as computer analysis, show that the g6-square is slightly preferable. The point is that by putting the bishop on g6 Black prevents the maneuver Ng3-h5. } 4. Ng3 c5 $13 { Finally, we are ready for this thematic advance. Black enjoys more than sufficient counterplay. His next moves will be ...Nc6 followed by ...Be7, and ...0-0. } *
