{ Now, we shall take a look at the positions with a backward pawn on d4. This important structure is typical not only for the Advance Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence, but also for Queen's Gambit Accepted. In return for the weak d5-square and the backward d4-pawn, White enjoys a considerable space advantage provided by the e5-pawn. In this concrete example, we will see that the type of position arising after the exchange of the light-squared bishops can be dangerous for Black. The problem is that without his light-squared bishop, Black has problems defending the king. For instance, in this position, White can follow with } 1. Neg5 $1 g6 2. h4 $16 { with h4-h5 comming next. Black is already in danger. } *
