{ In this example, we will see how to correctly handle the positions with a backward pawn on d4. The basic position of our variation arises after } 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7 6. O-O a5 { The structure with a backward pawn on c4 will occur when White goes for the advance c2-c4. The most straightforward way to get this structure is the continuation } 7. c4 { After this move, White usually follows with Nc3. } ( { An interesting alternative is } 7. Nbd2 { If White does not play c2-c4 or a2-a4, we always keep gaining space on the queenside with } 7... a4 { In this position, the continuation } 8. c4 { When the knight is on d2, taking on c4 is not advisable. Black should start with the thematic } 8... h6 { [%cal Gg8e7] making room for the bishop and preparing .. .Ne7. } ( { After } 8... dxc4 $6 9. Nxc4 $16 { White has a huge advantage. Due to the hole on d6, Black cannot complete the development. } ) 9. a3 { The most natural continuation. For the time being, White fixes the a4-pawn, thus planning to continue with Re1 followed by Nf1. } ( { Another interesting idea is } 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Nb1 { [%cal Gb1c3] planning to attack the a4-pawn by means of Nc3 on the next move. Additionally, White can also make use of the weakened b5-square. The following sequence seems quite logical - } 10... Ne7 11. Nc3 a3 12. Nb5 Nc6 13. bxa3 Be7 $13 { Black's harmonious development and active pieces provide him with excellent compensation for the pawn. } ) 9... Ne7 10. Re1 dxc4 { Having played ...Ne7, Black is ready to take on c4. The idea is to answer } 11. Nxc4 { with } 11... Nd5 { [%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Black is now ready to complete the development by playing ...Be7 followed by ...0-0. If left undisturbed, we can later consider attacking the centre with ...c6-c5. In the long run, the queenside space provided by the a4-pawn will become an important factor. White's most principled approach is } 12. Bd3 { As we have seen in the previous example, in this structure, White wants to exchange the light-squared bishops. As we know, after such an exchange the black king often tends to be vulnerable. In this concrete position, however, Black's queenside space makes his counterplay very powerful. The following sequence is quite characteristic - } 12... Bxd3 13. Qxd3 b5 { We should start our queenside play without wasting time. } ( { It's important not to rush with the castle. For instance, after } 13... Be7 14. Bd2 O-O 15. Re4 $40 { White has a dangerous attack. He is ready to follow with Rg4. } ) 14. Ncd2 Be7 15. Ne4 Qb6 { [%cal Gc6c5] Another important move. Black is ready to strike with ...c6-c5. } 16. Bd2 c5 $15 { Black enjoys an excellent counterplay. } ) 7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 Ne7 9. Nc3 Bg6 $1 { Another important typical idea that you should remember. The idea of this prophylactic move is to meet Bd3 with Nf5, thus preventing the exchange of the light-squared bishops. } 10. Bd3 { The most logical continuation. } ( { An important alternative is } 10. Nh4 { White's main idea is to develop a kingside activity by means of f2-f4 followed by g2-g4, and f4-f5. On the downside. with his last move, White releases his central control. The following sequence and logical and instructive - } 10... Nb6 11. Be2 a4 $1 { [%cal Ge7f5] It's always useful to gain as much queenside space as possible before clarifying our intentions. Additionally, it turns out that depriving White of the move Qb3 is useful in many cases. } ( { The immediate } 11... Nf5 $6 { plays into White's hand - } 12. Nxf5 Bxf5 13. g4 Bg6 14. f4 { We can see the main point behind the entire concept starting with 10.Nh4. Black should now reckon with the advance f4-f5. } 14... Qd7 15. Be3 { In this structure the most typical way of fighting against White's space advantage is } 15... f5 { Unfortunately, however, in this concrete position, White can obtain a solid advantage. } ( { Another instructive line is } 15... Be7 $2 16. Qb3 { Now, we can see why Qb3 should have been prevented. } 16... Bd8 17. f5 exf5 18. d5 $18 { White is winning. } ) 16. Qb3 { Once again, this queen sortie causes problems for Black. } 16... Nd5 17. Nxd5 exd5 18. h3 $16 { White's advantage is undisputable. } ) 12. a3 { Fixing the a4-pawn and asking Black to show his cards. } ( { In case of } 12. Bg4 { Black has a choice. The move } 12... Ned5 { is the most natural response. } ( { It's important to point out that the position arising after } 12... Nf5 13. Nxf5 Bxf5 14. Bxf5 exf5 15. a3 Be7 $13 { is also quite playable for Black. Black is ready to increase the pressure on d4 by playing ...Qd7 and ...Rd8. At the same time, the f5-pawn provides space and controls the important e4-square. } ) 13. Nxg6 hxg6 $13 { Black enjoys an excellent counterplay. In this fixed position, White's bishop pair is not significant. } ) 12... Nf5 { Once we have prevented Qb3, this move is absolutely playable. The logical follow-up would be } 13. Nxf5 Bxf5 14. g4 Bg6 15. f4 Qd7 16. Be3 Be7 { Given the fact that White does not have the active Qb3 resource, Black can just proceed with the development. We can strike with the thematic ...f7-f5 only when White is ready to play f4-f5 himself. For instance, after } 17. Rf2 O-O 18. Qf1 { [%cal Gf4f5] the most precise reaction would be } 18... f5 $13 { with enough counterplay. } ) 10... Nf5 { [%cal Gd7b6,Gd8d7] This is the point behind the bishop retreat. Now, White cannot exchange the light-squared bishops. At the same time, Black is ready to increase the pressure on d4 by means of simple moves such as ...Nb6 and ...Qd7. The following sequence seems quite logical - } 11. Be4 Nb6 12. Qd3 Qd7 13. Re1 a4 14. a3 Be7 15. Bf4 O-O 16. h3 h6 $13 { [%cal Gb6d5] with ...Nd5 to follow. It transpires that White's activity is not sufficient to compensate for the backward d4-pawn. } *
