1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7 6. O-O a5 { One of the main points of this move is to provoke a2-a4 before striking in the centre with ...f7-f6. } ( { Note that without the inclusion of the moves ...a7-a5 and a2-a4, the break } 6... f6 $6 { does not work well. The problem lies in the line } 7. c4 fxe5 8. dxe5 Bc5 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Nc3 Ne7 11. Na4 $1 { With pawns on a4 and a5, this idea wouldn't have been possible. Now, Black's dark-squared bishop lacks stability. After } 11... O-O 12. Nxc5 Nxc5 13. Nd4 $16 { White has a huge advantage. He is ready to start pushing the kingside majority. } ) 7. a4 f6 { Now, this break works perfectly fine. After taking on e5, Black will develop his dark-squared bishop on the stable c5-square. Let's suppose that White play in analogy to the line mentioned above: } 8. c4 fxe5 9. dxe5 Bc5 { [%cal Gg8e7,Ge7g6] Now, the c5-bishop cannot be harrassed by means of the maneuver Nc3-a4. Black is ready to complete the development with ...Ne7 followed by ...0-0. } 10. Nbd2 { In this concrete position, it's preferable to develop the knight via d2. The idea is to proceed with Nb3 on the next move. In this pawn structure, the white knight has nothing to do on c3. } ( { Another important structure arises after } 10. cxd5 exd5 { Practice, as well as computer analysis, show that Black is doing perfectly fine in this pawn structure. Black enjoys a compact pawn structure and superior piece activity. In many cases, the e5-pawn tends to be vulnerable. Very often Black manages to block this pawn by putting a knight on e6. } ) 10... Ne7 { This important position will be examined in a bunch of model games. After castling, Black is going to put pressure on e5 by means of ...Ng6. The play along the f-file, in combined with the strong c5-bishop, might become quite dangerous for White. White usually tries to put pressure on Black's position by installing a knight on d4. As we are going to witness however, Black's concept works quite well tactically. } *
