1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7 6. O-O a5 7. Nbd2 { [%cal Gf1e1,Gd2f1,Gf1g3] With this move, White usually shows his intention to focus on the kingside by playing Re1 followed by Nd2-f1-g3. In such positions, you can often see the solid c2-c3 which is designed to secure the central stability. Of course, sometimes the move 7.Nbd2 is connected with c2-c4. We have already examined this approach. } 7... a4 { This is the right strategy. While waiting for the opponent to show his cards, we keep gaining space on the queenside. } 8. c3 h6 { We know the purpose behind this typical move. By extending the diagonal for his light-squared bishop, Black is getting ready for the move ...Ne7. } ( { As we know, the immediate } 8... Ne7 { is well met by the typical } 9. Nh4 $14 { Depending on what Black does, White will either take the bishop or go for a kinside pawn expansion. } ) 9. Re1 Ne7 10. Nf1 Bg6 $1 { The correct move. Black not only retreats the bishop from the vulnerable f5-square but also prevents the annoying idea Nf1-g3-h5. } 11. Ng3 c5 { Only now, everything is ready for this typical advance. Most probably, the next move is going to be ...Nc6. } 12. Bd3 { There is nothing more logical than this continuation. In order to get some attacking chances, including the access to the h5-square, White should exchange the light-squared bishops. } 12... Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nc6 { Black starts his typical queenside play. A possible idea is ...cxd4 followed by ...Nd7-b6-c4, and ...Qb6. As we will see on multiple occasions, the space provided by the a4-pawn contributes a lot to Black's queenside play. } 14. Nh5 { The most logical continuation. Black wants to provoke the weakening .. .g7-g6. Nevertheless, it turns out that the black king is perfectly safe in the centre. The game continued } 14... cxd4 15. cxd4 g6 16. Nf4 Nb6 17. Bd2 Nc4 18. Bc3 Be7 { So far, both sides have been playing only logical moves. White does not have kingside attack as Black is ready to put his king on d7 at any moment. On the other hand, White should reckon with Black's queenside play based on ... Qb6-a6 followed by either ...a4-a3, or ...b7-b5-b4. } 19. b3 $6 { In my opinion, this move is already a step in the wrong direction. The problem is that the advance of the b-pawn weakens the queenside. } ( { More to the point would have been } 19. g3 { when the logical sequence } 19... Qb6 20. Kg2 Qa6 21. h4 a3 22. b3 Nb2 $13 { [%cal Gg6g5] would lead to an unclear position with an excellent counterplay for Black. At any moment, White should reckon with the advance ... g6-g5. } ) 19... Na3 20. g3 Qb6 21. Red1 $2 { This move is already a huge mistake since it allows Black to execute a favourable exchange of the queens. } ( { Better would have been } 21. Rec1 { planning to answer 21...Qb5 with 22.Qd1. In this case, Black could have continued with } 21... Kd7 22. Bb2 axb3 23. axb3 Nb5 $13 { with a pleasant French type of positions. We are going to develop our queenside play by means of simple moves such as ...Nb4 and ...Rhc8. } ) 21... Qb5 $1 { Now, White cannot avoid the exchange of the queens since the d1-square is no longer available. After } 22. Bb2 Qxd3 23. Nxd3 Nb5 $17 { Black got a huge advantage in the endgame. I strongly advise you to take a look at the remaining part of the game which is quite instructive as well. } 24. Rab1 axb3 25. axb3 Kd7 26. Rdc1 b6 27. Ra1 Ba3 28. Bxa3 Nxa3 29. Nde1 Ra7 30. Nc2 Rha8 31. Nxa3 Rxa3 32. Rab1 Na5 33. Rc3 Rc8 34. Rxc8 Kxc8 35. Nd2 Ra2 36. Nf3 Rc2 37. b4 Nc6 38. b5 Na5 39. h4 Nc4 40. Rb3 Kd7 41. Kg2 Ra2 42. Rb4 Ne3+ 43. Kg1 Ng4 44. Rb3 Nxf2 45. Nh2 Ne4 46. Ng4 h5 47. Nh6 Ke7 48. Ng8+ Kf8 49. Nf6 Ra4 50. Nd7+ Ke7 51. Nxb6 Ra1+ 52. Kg2 Ra2+ 53. Kg1 Kd8 54. Rf3 Kc7 55. Nxd5+ exd5 56. Rxf7+ Kb6 57. e6 Re2 58. Rg7 Kxb5 59. Rxg6 Nd2 60. g4 hxg4 61. h5 g3 62. Rf6 Kc6 63. h6 Rh2 64. Rf8 Kd6 *
