1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7 6. O-O a5 7. a4 f6 8. Nbd2 $5 { In many cases, this move turns out to be more useful than the advance c2-c4. For instance, in this position, the entire concept based on 8...fxe5 followed by ...Bc5 does not work in view of Nb3. On the downside, with his last move, White closes the diagonal of his dark-squared bishop. Therefore, Black has the possibility of playing } 8... Nh6 { This flexible move helps Black to increase the pressure on e5 by playing ... Nf7, either immediately or after ...fxe5. } 9. Nb3 { This is White's most natural choice. Black should now reckon with the threat of Bxh6. } ( { An important alternative is } 9. Re1 { creating an annoying opposition along the e-file. In order to make sure that the e-file will remain closed, Black should start with } 9... fxe5 10. Nxe5 { The most principled choice. In the future, White will rely on the mobility of his kingside pawns. } ( { Another important direction is } 10. dxe5 Be7 11. Nd4 O-O 12. g4 { Due to the vulnerable e6-pawn, the concept based on Nd4 followed by g2-g4 should always be taken into consideration. Black's superior development, however, provides the important resource of } 12... Qb6 { challenging the stability of White's position. After } 13. Nc4 $1 dxc4 14. gxf5 Nxe5 $13 { the position remains unclear. In a practical game, however, everyone would take Black due to the vulnerable white king. } ) 10... Nxe5 11. dxe5 Bg6 { [%cal Gh6f5] As we already know, retreating the bishop to g6 is quite typical for this pawn structure. Now, Black is ready to proceed with . ..Nf5. } 12. Nb3 Nf5 13. Bd3 { This position occurred in the game 1/2-1/2 (25) Petrov,M (2530) -Dautov,R (2592) Germany 2023. Now, Black should have continued with the natural } 13... Be7 { planning to complete the development with ... 0-0. White should play very energetically. } 14. Bxf5 { After forcing the black bishop into the f5-square, White is planning to proceed with Nd4 followed by g2-g4. } ( { Another interesting idea is } 14. Nd4 { In this case, however, Black can play } 14... Nxd4 15. Bxg6+ hxg6 16. Qxd4 Kd7 $13 { [%cal Gd8f8,Gf8f5] I really like this beautiful concept. Every French Defence player knows that the king is safely placed on d7 in such structures. Black is now ready to display kingside activity by employing the maneuver ...Qf8-f5. } ) 14... Bxf5 15. Nd4 O-O 16. g4 { The point behind White's previous play. Once again, Black's good coordination and active pieces provide him with enough resources - } 16... Be4 17. Nxe6 Qb6 18. Be3 Qxb2 19. Bd4 Qxc2 20. Qxc2 Bxc2 21. Rec1 Be4 22. Nxf8 Rxf8 $44 { with sufficient compensation for the exchange. } ) 9... Nf7 10. Re1 { By creating the opposition on the f-file, White indirectly protects the e5-pawn. It turns out that Black has an additional idea in mind - } 10... g5 $1 { This move solves all the problems. Besides gaining space on the kingside, Black is planning to increase the pressure on the centre by playing ...Bg7. } 11. exf6 { White should open the centre as soon as possible. His hopes are based on the play against the backward e6-pawn. } 11... Qxf6 12. Bd3 { By exchanging the strong f5-bishop, White is planning to challenge Black's stability. Nevertheless, after } 12... Bxd3 13. Qxd3 g4 14. Nfd2 h5 $13 { [%cal Gf8d6,Ge8g8] Black is in full control. If allowed, he will proceed with ...Bd6 followed by . ..0-0, and eventually ...e6-e5. The following game, left without text annotations, is a good practical example of what you can expect in such positions. } 15. Qe2 Nd8 16. Nf1 Bd6 17. Bd2 b6 18. c4 O-O 19. Rac1 Qg6 20. Bc3 Nf6 21. c5 bxc5 22. dxc5 Bc7 23. Be5 Bxe5 24. Qxe5 Ne4 25. Ng3 Ng5 26. Nd4 h4 27. Nge2 Ndf7 28. Qf4 e5 29. Qf5 Qxf5 30. Nxf5 Ra7 31. Nxh4 Rb8 32. Rc2 Rab7 33. Nf5 Kf8 34. Rb1 Rb4 35. Neg3 e4 36. Ne2 Ne6 37. Rd2 Ne5 38. Ned4 Nxd4 39. Nxd4 Rxa4 40. b3 Rab4 41. Ra1 Ra8 42. h4 gxh3 43. Kh2 hxg2 44. Kxg2 a4 45. bxa4 Raxa4 46. Rxa4 Rxa4 47. Nxc6 Nxc6 48. Rxd5 Kf7 49. Kg3 Ne7 50. Rd1 Ke6 51. Re1 Ke5 52. Kg4 Rc4 53. Re2 Nd5 54. Ra2 Rxc5 55. Ra8 Rc6 56. Ra5 Rg6+ 57. Kh3 Rg5 58. Kh2 Kf4 59. Ra3 Nf6 60. Ra6 Nd7 61. Ra3 Ne5 62. Ra8 Nd3 63. Ra2 Kf3 64. Rc2 Rg2+ 65. Kh3 Nf4+ 66. Kh4 Rg4# { 0-1 (66) Liang, J (2474) -Ghasi,A (2506) Casablanca 2023 } *
