{The next couple of model games will be dedicated to the positions with a pawn pawn on e5. The first example is a very nice model game in which you can see Black's light-square strategy in action.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7 6. O-O a5 7. a4 f6 8. Bf4 {Played with the intention to overprotect the important e5-pawn. On the other hand, the bishop is not optimally placed on the semi-open f-file, in opposition with the black f8-rook.} fxe5 {Theoretically speaking, this is not the most precise continuation since it allows White to establish a firm control of the e5-square.} ({Better would have been the suggestion of Eljanov. Below, I provide some of the important analysis from his database My Caro-Kann - Part 1.} 8... Ne7 $1 {planning to attack the bishop by means of ...Ng6.} 9. exf6 Nxf6 (9... gxf6 $2 10. Nh4 $1 Bg6 11. Bg4 f5 12. Be2 Bf7 13. Nd2 (13. Bd6 $2 Bg7 $13 {1/2-1/2 Zhigalko,S (2612) -Daneshvar, B (2419) Wch Rapid Almaty 2022 (2)}) 13... Nc8 14. Nhf3 $16) 10. Bd3 $1 {The only way to create problems for Black. Otherwise, Black will follow with the natural ...Ng6 followed by either ...Bd6 or ...Be7.} ({Nothing gives} 10. c4 Ng6 11. Bg3 Nh5 12. Nc3 Be7 13. Bd3 O-O $13 {Once again, Black has more than sufficient counterplay.}) ({Harmless is} 10. Nbd2 Ng6 11. Bg3 {This position was reached in the game 0-1 (36) Vatsal, S (2269) -Tarhan, A (2388) Abu Dhabi 2023. Now, the most precise would have been} Nh5 $1 12. Re1 Nxg3 13. hxg3 Qf6 $13 {[%cal Gf8d6,Ge8g8] with ...Bd6, and ...0-0 to follow. Later on, Black will try to carry out the advance ...e6-e5. As a rule, Black is doing fine in this structure when he has good control of the e5-square.}) 10... Ng6 $1 {Black must finish development quickly. Taking back with the pawn on f5 is desirable, as e6 is Black's main weakness.} 11. Bxf5 exf5 (11... Nxf4 $2 12. Re1 $16) 12. Bg5 (12. Be5 Nxe5 13. Qe2 Qc7 14. dxe5 Ne4 15. c4 O-O-O $13) 12... Qd7 $1 {A non-standard way to get dynamic counterplay. White now has two conceptually different approaches:} 13. Bxf6 {The positional approach. White creates weaknesses and hopes to exploit them later.} ({With} 13. c4 $5 {, White can continue playing dynamically:} dxc4 {The most precise continuation. The following lines show that Black has decent counterplay in all the lines.} (13... Ne4 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Nc3 Bb4 16. h4 $1 h6 17. Bc1 O-O 18. h5 Ne7 19. Ne5 Qd8 20. Bf4 $36) 14. Qe2+ Be7 15. Qxc4 (15. Nbd2 b5 16. Ne5 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Nd5 18. e6 Qc7 $13) (15. Na3 b5 16. Ne5 Qd5 17. Rfd1 Nxe5 18. dxe5 Qe4 $1 19. Re1 Qxe2 20. Rxe2 Nd5 21. Bxe7 Kxe7 22. axb5 cxb5 23. Nxb5 g6 24. Nd6 c3 25. bxc3 Nxc3 26. Rc2 Ne4 $11) 15... Ne4 $1 {Keeping control of the e5-square while blocking the e-file as long as necessary.} 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Nc3 O-O-O 18. g3 Rhe8 19. Qb3 h5 $13) 13... gxf6 14. Nbd2 Bd6 15. c3 (15. Re1+ Kf7 16. Kh1 Rhg8 17. c3 Kg7 18. Nf1 Kh8 19. Qc2 Rg7 20. Ne3 Ne7 21. Nh4 Rg5 $13 {Just like in the mainline, Black can generate sufficient counterplay on the g-file.}) 15... O-O 16. Ne1 (16. Qc2 Kh8 17. Kh1 Rg8 $13) 16... Kh8 {At first the engine shows an edge for White, but then doesn't seem able to prove it.} 17. Nd3 Rg8 18. Qh5 (18. Kh1 f4 $1 19. Qh5 (19. Nf3 Nf8 $1 20. Nh4 Rg4 $13) 19... Ne7 20. Rae1 Nf5 $13 {transposes to the mainline.}) 18... f4 $5 {Gaining more space on the kingside and preparing a knight transfer to f5.} (18... Nf4 $13) 19. Kh1 Ne7 $1 20. Rae1 Nf5 {GM Pavel Eljanov: '' GM Pavel Eljanov: 'transposes to the mainline.'} 21. Rg1 Rg6 22. Qf3 Nh4 23. Qh5 Qf5 24. Qxh4 Qxd3 $11) 9. dxe5 $6 {This move plays into Black's hand.} ({White should have played} 9. Nxe5 {fighting for the e5-square. A logical continuation would be} Nxe5 10. Bxe5 Nf6 11. Bh5+ Nxh5 12. Qxh5+ Bg6 13. Qe2 $14 {with a slight advantage for White.}) 9... Bc5 {Black has full control of the important diagonal a7-g1. He is now ready to complete the development by means of ...Ne7 followed by ...0-0. The following couple of moves are quite natural.} 10. Nbd2 Ne7 11. Nb3 O-O $5 {Obviously, this is a double-edged decision. By exchanging his dark-squared bishop for a knight, Black shows his intention to play on the light squares.} ({Objectively speaking, even stronger would have been} 11... Bb6 {planning to proceed with ...0-0 followed by ...Ng6. The following sequence seems to be quite reasonable -} 12. Nfd4 Ng6 13. Be3 Ndxe5 14. Nxf5 exf5 15. Nd4 Bxd4 16. Qxd4 O-O $15 {/=. Even though the position is objectively balanced, White still needs to prove compensation for the pawn.}) 12. Nxc5 Nxc5 {The character of the position is already clarified. In return for his dark-squared bishop, Black has two major advantages: 1) every piece exchange makes the e5-pawn more vulnerable 2) Black dominates on the light squares. All black minor pieces is capable of controlling the light squares while only two white pieces can do so. Ideally, Black would like to exchange the light-squared bishops and a pair of knights. In such a case, White will remain with his useless dark-squared bishop. It goes without saying, that in such a case, White will have a hard time neutralizing the powerful tandem queen & knight.} 13. Nd4 Bd3 $1 {Black's position holds thanks to this nuance. Black makes use of the vulnerable f4-bishop.} 14. Be3 {This bishop retreat is the most natural move in the position.} ({Nevertheless, getting rid of the dark-squared bishop by means of} 14. Bg5 Bxe2 15. Qxe2 h6 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 {would have made a lot of sense. In this position, White could play} 17. Qe3 $13 {with a tiny initiative. We should point out that with only knights on the board, space advantage is a significant factor.}) 14... Bxe2 15. Qxe2 Qd7 16. c3 b6 {[%cal Gc5a6,Gc6c5] A good positional move. Black wants to proceed with ...Na6 followed by ...c6-c5. Given the fact that White's kingside majority is not mobile, it's not easy for him to find a constructive plan.} 17. Qc2 Na6 18. Rad1 c5 19. Nb5 Nc7 {Black is playing according to the plan. After exchanging the light-squared bishops, he wants to trade off a pair of knights as well. In this case, White will remain with his useless dark-squared bishop.} 20. Nd6 Nf5 21. Nxf5 exf5 $13 {[%cal Gc7e6,Gd7c6] Another instructive moment. The protected passed pawn on e5 is not dangerous at all. Black can safely block it with the knight. Additionally, the f5-pawn provides space on the kingside. Even though the position remains balanced, Black's play is easier from a practical perspective. After mutual mistakes, Marcelin eventually managed to win.} 22. f4 Qc6 23. Rd2 Rad8 24. Qd1 Rd7 25. b3 Qe6 26. Qf3 Rfd8 27. Rfd1 d4 28. cxd4 Qxb3 29. dxc5 Rxd2 30. Rxd2 Rxd2 31. Bxd2 Qxf3 32. gxf3 Nd5 33. Kf2 Kf7 34. Ke2 bxc5 35. Bxa5 Nxf4+ 36. Kd2 Ke6 37. Kc3 Ng6 38. Bc7 Nxe5 39. a5 Nc6 40. a6 Nb4 41. a7 Nd5+ 42. Kc4 Nxc7 43. Kxc5 g5 44. Kc6 Na8 45. Kb7 Kd7 46. Kxa8 Kc7 47. h3 Kc8 48. h4 g4 49. h5 g3 0-1

