{In this game, we will see what happens when White opens the position to the maximum by sacrificing the e5-pawn.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7 6. O-O a5 7. a4 f6 8. c4 {The most principled continuation. In order to use his lead in development, White wants to open the position.} fxe5 9. cxd5 {Logical, but as we will see - slightly premature. In this case, Black manages to sustain his stability since the tactics work well for him.} ({More sensible is} 9. dxe5 {We are going to examine this continuation in the following model games.}) 9... exd5 $1 {The right recapture. Besides achieving a compact pawn structure. Black is getting rid of the weak e6-pawn.} 10. dxe5 Bc5 {As usual, the bishop is perfectly placed on this diagonal. He is now ready to complete the development with ...Ne7 followed by ...0-0. In such positions, the e5-pawn is not dangerous since the rest of White's army does not support it. If given time, Black will easily surround the central passer.} 11. Nd4 {The most logical continuation. White should start active play as soon as possible. The advance g2-g4 is already on the agenda.} Ne7 12. g4 {Again, the best continuation. Highly energetic play is required in this position.The following couple of moves are quite forced -} ({In case of} 12. Nc3 Nxe5 13. Bh5+ N5g6 $17 {White does not have any compensation for the pawn. 0-1 (37) Ter Sahakyan,S (2625) -Shams,M (2167) Yerevan 2022}) 12... Bxb1 13. Rxb1 Nxe5 14. Ne6 Qd6 15. Nxc5 {Of course, White should prioritize eliminating the dangerous dark-squared bishop.} ({Weaker is} 15. Nxg7+ $2 Kd7 $1 16. Nh5 Raf8 $17 {[%cal Gd6g6] when Black enjoys a dangerous attack. His next move is going to be ...Qg6.}) ({The alternative} 15. b4 $5 axb4 16. Nxc5 Qxc5 {leads to transposition.}) 15... Qxc5 16. b4 $1 {Without this strong dynamic resource, White will be just worse. If left undisturbed, Black will proceed with ...0-0 followed by ...N7g6-f4. In the long run, White's weak kingside will start telling.} axb4 17. Bb2 $2 {This is a huge mistake that leaves White without compensation for the sacrificed material.} ({Of course, better would have been} 17. Bd2 {In this case, Black has the option of playing for the initiative by giving the material back -} Qd6 18. Rxb4 O-O 19. Rxb7 d4 $13 {Even though the position is objectively balanced, playing with Black is easier in view of the vulnerable white king.}) 17... N7g6 $19 {Now, Black has a winning position since White does not have compensation for being two pawns down.} 18. Rc1 Qe7 19. f4 Nd7 20. Qd2 O-O 21. f5 Nge5 22. g5 Qd6 23. Rcd1 Rxa4 24. f6 g6 25. Qd4 Nf7 26. Rf2 Nc5 27. Qe3 b3 28. Bf3 Ne6 29. Qxb3 Rb4 30. Qc3 Nexg5 31. Bg2 Ne4 32. Bxe4 Rxe4 33. Kh1 Rfe8 34. Ba3 Qe5 35. Qxe5 Nxe5 36. Rb1 b5 37. Be7 Ra8 38. Bd6 Kf7 39. Rc2 Nc4 40. Be7 d4 41. Rd1 Ne3 42. Re1 Rxe7 0-1

