1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7 6. O-O a5 7. a4 f6 8. exf6 Ngxf6 {Usually, Black is quite happy to play this structure. As long as we have good control of the e5-square, White cannot put us under positional pressure. The weakness of the e6-pawn is an illusion since White cannot effectively attack it. Black has two main ideas in the arising positions: 1) play along the semi-open f-file 2) execute the advance ...e6-e5} 9. c3 Bd6 10. Bd3 O-O {An important point. We are perfectly ready to take on f5 with the pawn. In the game, however, White focused on the e6-pawn and played} 11. Re1 ({The structure arising after} 11. Bxf5 exf5 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gd8f6,Ga8e8] is perfectly fine for Black. Black's space and strong central control are more important than the weak e5-square. We are ready to proceed with ...Ne4 followed by ...Qf6, and ...Rae8.}) 11... Bg4 $1 {An important positional move. By pinning the f3-knight, Black is preparing the thematic ...e6-e5 advance. The game continued} 12. Nbd2 e5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Be2 {Black's superior piece activity and better pawn structure provide him with a huge advantage. In the game, I played} Ng6 $17 {which is enough to keep the advantage. Eventually, I won the game.} ({Even more precise, however, would have been} 14... Bxf3 $1 {when Black is simply winning.} 15. Nxf3 ({In case of} 15. Bxf3 Qb6 $19 {[%cal Ge5d3,Gd6c5] White cannot defend against all the threats on the diagonal a7-g1 and the semi-open f-file.}) 15... Neg4 $19 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gd8b6] Black is ready to follow with either ...Ne4, or ...Qb6. White cannot parry all the threats.}) 15. Nd4 Bd7 16. N2f3 Ne4 17. Bd3 c5 18. Nb5 Bg4 19. Bxe4 dxe4 20. Qd5+ Kh8 21. Nxd6 exf3 22. Nf7+ Rxf7 23. Qxf7 fxg2 24. Bg5 Qc8 25. Re3 Qg8 26. Qxg8+ Kxg8 27. Rae1 h6 28. Rg3 Bf5 29. Be3 b6 30. Kxg2 Nh4+ 31. Kg1 Kf7 32. f3 g5 33. Kf2 Rd8 34. Rgg1 Bc2 35. Re2 Bxa4 36. Rd2 Re8 37. Rd6 Re6 38. Rxe6 Kxe6 39. Re1 Bc6 40. f4 Kf5 41. fxg5 hxg5 42. Rg1 Nf3 43. Rg3 g4 44. h3 Ne5 45. hxg4+ Nxg4+ 46. Ke2 Bb5+ 47. Kd2 Bc6 48. Rh3 Nf6 49. Rh5+ Nxh5 50. b4 Nf6 51. bxc5 bxc5 52. Bxc5 Ne4+ 53. Ke3 Nxc5 54. Kd4 a4 55. Kc4 a3 56. Kb4 a2 57. Kxc5 a1=Q 58. Kxc6 Qxc3+ 59. Kd6 Qd3+ 60. Ke7 Qe4+ 61. Kf8 Qe5 62. Kg8 Qe6+ 63. Kh7 Qg6+ 64. Kh8 Qg1 65. Kh7 Kf6 66. Kh8 Qg7# {GrigorGrigorov won by checkmate} 0-1

