{This game is very important theoretically since it features White's most ambitious approach against our system. The first important position is occurs after} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7 6. O-O a5 7. a4 f6 8. c4 fxe5 9. dxe5 Bc5 10. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2b3] A very important idea. White wants to harass the c5-bishop by means of Nb3. Afterward, he is ready to continue with Nfd4 followed by the advance of the kingside pawns.} Ne7 11. Nb3 Ba7 $1 {In positions with a white pawn on c4, this is the best retreat square.} ({In case of} 11... Bb6 $6 12. Nfd4 {the move} Nxe5 $2 {runs into} 13. c5 $1 Bc7 14. g4 $18 {when White is basically winning.}) 12. Nfd4 {[%cal Gg2g4] The most natural move. White is preparing the advance g2-g4.} ({Less logical is} 12. Nbd4 {The problem with this move is that the f3-knight is blocking the advance of the kingside majority. Of course, Black is always ready to give the f5-bishop for a knight.} O-O 13. Bg5 {This move was played in the only game featuring this position. Given the fact that White has a space advantage, his decision to exchange minor pieces does not make a lot of sense.} h6 14. Bxe7 $6 {Consistent with the previous play but dubious.} ({Better would have been} 14. Nxf5 Rxf5 15. Bd2 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Rxe5 $13 {The position is complicated but White still needs to prove compensation for the pawn.}) 14... Qxe7 15. Nxf5 Rxf5 $15 {This position was reached in the game 0-1 (26) Fauth,D (2048) -Ohler, J (2273) Tegernsee 2023. Black is better in view of his superior boshop and the vulnerable e5-pawn.}) ({The most decent alternative to the game move is} 12. Bd2 {immediately asking some questions regarding the a5-pawn.} O-O {In my opinion, this pawn sacrifice is Black's most energetic reaction. That being said, 12...Bb8 is perfectly playable as well.} 13. Bxa5 Qe8 {Black is now ready to start attacking the e5-pawn by means of ...Ng6, and even ...Bb8. In some cases, the g6-knight can land on f4, thus marking the beginning of a dangerous attack. Hence, a logical follow-up would be} 14. Bc7 Bb8 15. Bxb8 Qxb8 $13 {[%cal Ge7g6] with ...Ng6 to follow. Obviously, Black will regain the pawn, keeping excellent counterplay in this complex position.}) 12... Nxe5 $1 {The point of Black's move order. Without this strong move, Black is strategically lost.} 13. g4 Be4 $1 {Again the most precise move. As often happens in this line, Black can afford to sacrifice the e6-pawn. Very often, the white king tends to be more exposed than the black one.} 14. Nxe6 Qd6 15. Nxg7+ Kd7 {This is the critical position. The position is balanced but White should play very carefully since his king is weaker. The ideas ...Rhg8 and ... Qg6 are always in the air.} 16. Nh5 {The most natural move. It makes a lot of sense to put the knight on a protected square.} ({The computer suggestion is} 16. Bf4 {In this case, Black can opt for the following sequence:} Nf3+ 17. Bxf3 Qxf4 18. Bxe4 Qxe4 19. Re1 Qxc4 {The play is extremely concrete and the value of every move is tremendous. Now, White should reckon with the threat of ... Rhg8. The most challenging try is} 20. Rc1 Qb4 21. Ne6 {The threat of Nec5 is very annoying and therefore Black should overprotect the e7-knight by means of} Rae8 $1 {Still, the computer tries to maintain the initiative with} 22. Nbc5+ Bxc5 23. Nxc5+ Kc8 {[%cal Gh7h5]} 24. Re3 {[%cal Ge3b3] with the nasty threat of Rb3. Nevertheless after the precise} h5 $1 25. g5 Ng6 26. Rb3 Qg4+ 27. Qxg4+ hxg4 28. Nxb7 Kd7 29. Nxa5 Nf4 $44 {Black has enough compensation for the pawn.}) 16... Raf8 {This natural continuation is not optimal. Nevertheless, practically speaking, Black's position is easier to handle. In the game, Black eventually managed to win.} ({More precise would have been} 16... Qg6 $1 {[%cal Ge4c2] when among everything else, Black is threatening ...Bc2. White's best chance lies in the following sequence:} 17. Bf4 Rhg8 18. Bxe5 Qxh5 19. Bg3 Qh3 20. Bf3 Bxf3 21. Qxf3 Qxg4 $13 {The position is complex but practically easier for Black.}) 17. c5 Bxc5 18. Nxc5+ Qxc5 19. Be3 Qb4 20. f3 Bg6 21. Qd4 Qxd4 22. Bxd4 Bxh5 23. Bxe5 Rhg8 24. Bg3 Bg6 25. Ra3 Nc8 26. Rb3 Nd6 27. Rc1 Rb8 28. Bf2 Rgf8 29. Re3 Rf4 30. b3 Rbf8 31. Bg3 R4f7 32. Re5 Rxf3 33. Bxf3 Rxf3 34. Bh4 Nc8 35. Rf1 Rxb3 36. Rf8 Rb4 37. Rg8 Rxg4+ 38. Bg3 Nd6 39. Rf8 Rxa4 40. Rf6 Ne4 41. Rfe6 Nxg3 42. hxg3 Rb4 0-1

