[EventDate "2023.09.18"]
[PlyCount "32"]
[SourceVersionDate "2023.12.05"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. c4 { In the first lecture, we have already dealt with the advance c2-c4, without the inclusion of the moves h2-h4 and ...h7-h5. Obviously, this inclusion favours White since the g5-square is an excellent outpost for his dark-squared bishop. Nevertheless, I am quite satisfied by the fact that Black can again stick to the concept advocated against the immediate c2-c4 - } 5... e6 6. Nc3 Bb4 { Our ideas quite similar to what I have shown in Lecture 1. For instance, after giving the dark-squared bishop for the knight, Black will try to adopt his usual light-square strategy. In case White opts for a slow play, we usually go for .. .Ne7 followed by ...c6-c5. The most critical continuation is } 7. cxd5 { Before starting his kingside play, White fixes the structure in the centre. } ( { As usual, we meet the move } 7. Qb3 { with } 7... a5 { Remember that we wait for a2-a3 before taking the c3-knight. As explained in the first lecture, the a3-pawn blocks the a3-square for the bishop and also further weakens the light squares on the queenside. The following game is a good illustration of Black's domination on the light squares. } 8. a3 dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 { In my opinion, this recapture is dubious since it allows Black to establish firm control of the light squares.Now, Black follows with his typical operation - } ( { With the inclusion of the moves h2-h4 and ... h7-h5, the alternative } 10. Qxc3 { makes even more sense. Black should now always reckon with Qg3 and Bg5. } 10... Ne7 { I prefer this continuation over 10...Nd7. The reason is that now the immediate 11.Qg3 does not work in view of 11...Qxd4. Hence, White should start with } 11. Ne2 { [%cal Gc3g3] preparing Qg3 on the next move. } ( { In such positions, you should always reckon with } 11. Bg5 { In my opinion, the best way of dealing with the pin is } 11... Nd7 12. Ne2 f6 $5 { Eliminating White's space advantage and taking better control of the dark squares is more important than keeping the integrity of the pawn structure. The position arising after } 13. exf6 gxf6 14. Bf4 Nb6 $13 { offers Black an excellent counterplay based on the g-file and the d5-square. After simple moves such as ...Nbd5 and ...Qd7, the king can eventually go to f7. } ) 11... Nd7 12. Qg3 { The critical test. Slow play would allow Black to arrange his desired setup - ...Nb6-d5, ...Qd7, and eventually ...f7-f6. } 12... Nb6 13. Ba2 a4 $1 { An important move. Black grabs space and fixes the queenside structure. I } ( { The alternative } 13... Bg6 14. Bg5 Nbd5 15. Rd1 $14 { leaves Black in a passive position without an obvious counterplay. } ) 14. Qxg7 { White has nothing better than taking the pawn. Black should now go for the following sequence: } 14... Rg8 15. Qh6 Rg6 16. Qxh5 Bg4 17. Qh8+ Rg8 18. Qh6 Bxe2 19. Kxe2 Qxd4 $44 { with a decent compensation for the pawn in view of the vulnerable white king and excellent spots for the knights. } ) 10... b5 11. Be2 a4 { fixing the structure and taking under control all the important light squares on the queenside. } 12. Qb4 Ne7 13. Bg5 { This position was reached in the game 0-1 (28) Koziorowicz, M (2315) -Pultinevicius, P (2546) Chess.com INT 2022 At this point, instead of the game move 13...Na6, Black could have played } 13... Nd7 { [%cal Gf7f6] preparing the advance ...f7-f6. In this position, White is the one who should care about equality. } ) ( { A decent approach is } 7. Ne2 Ne7 8. a3 { In this way, White obtains the bishop pair without spoiling the pawn structure. } ( { Worse is } 8. Ng3 { when Black can immediately strike with } 8... c5 $15 { Black is already better since White's centre is falling apart. } ) 8... Bxc3+ 9. Nxc3 Nd7 { The most flexible continuation. Black is ready to answer Bg5 with ...f7-f6. At the same time, the possibility of obtaining a structure with a backward d4-pawn is always on the table. } ( { The alternative } 9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 c5 $13 { is playable as well. } ) 10. Bg5 { This position occurred in the game 0-1 (53) Kaasen, T (2383) -Kharitonov, A (2543) Paleochora 2021 } ( { Note that in case of } 10. cxd5 { the best recapture would be } 10... exd5 { With the move h2-h4 and . .. h7-h5 included, this structure is often playable for Black. The reason is that White's kingside majority is less mobile. Therefore, Black can establish a blockade on the light squares. A very instructive line is } 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 f6 $1 { Pay attention to this important strategic move. First of all, we would like to provoke the move } 13. f4 { Besides blocking the dark-squared bishop, the advance f2-f4 also weakens the light squares. Now, Black can start building his thematic blockade with } 13... g6 $13 { [%cal Gd7f8,Gf6f5,Gf8e6] The idea is to proceed with ...Nf8 followed by ...f6-f5, and ...Ne6. Computer often gives a slight plus for White in such positions (due to the space granted by the e5-pawn. In practice, however, Black's play is easier. } ) 10... f6 $1 { Of course! This is the best way to get rid of the pin. We already know that the type of position arising after } 11. exf6 gxf6 12. Bf4 dxc4 13. Bxc4 Nb6 14. Ba2 Nbd5 $13 { is quite favourable for Black. } ) ( { The direct } 7. a3 { is best answered with } 7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Ne7 { [%cal Gc6c5] In this structure, our main idea is to execute the advance ...c6-c5 in a favourable way. Very often the central tension can result in a backward pawn on d4. Let's take a brief look at one of the games of Alexander Riazantsev. White played the natural but slow } 9. a4 { White is planning Ba3 on the next move. Black, however, immediately strikes with } 9... c5 10. Nf3 Nbc6 { White's centre is already quite shaky. In the game, White played } 11. dxc5 { Having the bishop pair, White is aiming at an asymmetrical pawn structure. Nevertheless, Black's better structure and superior piece activity are more important than the bishop pair.The most straightforward. The alternative 11...0-0 was strong as well. } ( { Another possibility is } 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Qd2 O-O $15 { [%cal Gc6a5] when Black is obviously better. White should now reckon with ...Na5. } ) 11... Qa5 12. Qb3 O-O 13. cxd5 Nxd5 $15 { This position occurred in the game 0-1 (42) Carlsson,P (2457) -Riazantsev,A (2634) Warsaw 2021. Black's advantage is out of the question. } ) 7... cxd5 { In this concrete position, we should stick to the symmetrical pawn structure. } ( { Worse is } 7... exd5 $6 8. Bd3 { After the exchange of the bishops, it will be difficult for Black to establish his usual blockade on the light squares. } ) 8. Bg5 { The most natural move. The bishop always occupies this key square after the inclusion of the moves h2-h4 and ... h7-h5. } ( { In my opinion, the immediate } 8. a3 { does not make too much sense since Black will take on c3 anyway. We will continue with } 8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Nd7 { [%cal Gd8c7,Gf7f6] Black is already planning to attack the centre with ...Qc7 followed by ...f7-f6. } 10. Bd3 { As we have already pointed out, in these structures, White tries to exchange the light-squared bishops. The reason is simple. After this exchange, Black's kingside becomes somewhat vulnerable. } ( { In case of } 10. Ne2 Qc7 11. Bd2 f6 $13 { Black enjoys an excellent counterplay. } ) 10... Ne7 11. Ne2 { This position occurred in the game 0-1 (40) Bazyrtsyrenov,K (2275) -Kostenko,P (2382) Cheliabinsk 2022. At this point, Black could have played } 11... Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Nf5 { Our idea is to obtain stability thanks to the control of the light squares. The d7-knight will obviously occupy the c4-square. Remember that the move } 13. Bg5 { should always be met with } 13... f6 { A possible line would be } 14. exf6 gxf6 15. Bf4 Nb6 16. Bg3 Kf7 17. Rb1 Qd7 $13 { Black enjoys decent counterplay in this complex position. } ) ( 8. Bd3 Ne7 9. Bg5 { is just a transposition. } ) 8... Ne7 9. Bd3 { The most precise move. Black uses the vulnerable c3-knight in order to get rid of the pin. The following couple of moves are quite logical: } 9... Qa5 10. Ne2 Nbc6 11. O-O Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Nf5 { Black managed to find good squares for all his pieces. Due to the vulnerable d4-pawn, the f5-knight cannot be challenged with Ng3. As for the annoying g5-bishop, we will try to get rid of it by means of ...Be7. The following practical example shows what might happen in such positions - } 13. a3 Be7 14. b4 Qd8 15. Bxe7 Ncxe7 16. g3 Qd7 $13 { This position occurred in the game 0-1 (48) Nasuta, G (2531) -Pultinevicius, P (2552) Legnica 2021. The position is complex, but Black has every chance to fight for an advantage in view of White's vulnerable queenside. } *
