1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 Qa5+ { Starting with this move is quite essential. The idea is to spoil White's coordination, thus preventing him from arranging the minor pieces in the perfect way. } ( { The problem with } 6... e6 { is that White can answer it with } 7. Bg5 { [%cal Gb1d2,Gg1f3] followed by Nd2 and Ngf3. Once White manages to arrange the minor pieces in this way, it's extremely difficult for Black to obtain counterplay. } ) 7. Bd2 { This move was popular several years ago. Nevertheless, practice has shown that Black has nothing to worry about in this line. White's idea is to win an important tempo in order to answer } 7... Qa6 { with } 8. e6 { This thematic pawn sacrifice is designed to hinder the development of Black's kingside. Additionally, in the future, White wants to make use of the weak squares e5 and g5. The first critical position arises after } 8... Qxd3 9. exf7+ Kxf7 10. cxd3 { The structure has been clarified. White's plan is to use the backward e7-pawn and the weak squares e5 and g5. At the same time, White's structure is compromised as well. What is even more important is that the inclusion of the moves h2-h4 and ...h7-h5 allows Black to achieve stability on the light squares. For instance, the important f5-square will be an excellent spot for the knight. Black has many good options in this position. The most popular choice is 10...Nh6 with the idea of ...Nf5. Later on, Black follows with ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7. There is nothing wrong with this approach which was excellently explained by GM Pavel Eljanov in his database My Caro-Kann - Part 2. In this lecture, however, I would like to suggest a relatively rare move that might catch your opponent by surprise. My suggestion is } 10... e6 { [%cal Gf8d6] This move indicates our priority to take the e5-square under control by means of ...Bd6. Later on, we will decide on the future of the knights. While the maneuver ...Nh6-f5 remains a valid option, in some cases, this knight can go to f7 as well. As for the other knight, both a6 and d7-squares are to be considered. } 11. Nf3 Bd6 12. Nc3 { [%cal Gc3e2,Gd2f4] This is the most natural move. White's idea is to exchange the dark-squared bishops by means of Ne2 followed by Bf4. } ( { Another interesting approach is } 12. Bc3 { [%cal Gb1d2] The c3-bishop is not as useless as it might seem at first glance. Besides overprotecting the important e5-pawn, this bishop often supports the advance of the queenside pawns. After Nbd2 and 0-0, White wants to put pressure on e6 by doubling the rooks on the e-file. In the following practical example, Black managed to neutralize White's strategic concept. } 12... Nh6 13. Nbd2 Nd7 14. O-O Rae8 { [%cal Ge8e7,Gb7b6,Gc6c5] It turns out that Black has no problems defending the e6-pawn. After ... Re7, we can proceed with ...b7-b6 followed by ...c6-c5. Note that the king is excellently placed on g6 in this position. } 15. Rfe1 Kg6 16. Re2 ( { One of Black's ideas is to answer the immediate } 16. Ng5 { with } 16... e5 { After } 17. Ndf3 Ng4 $11 { [%cal Ge8e7,Gh8e8] Black enjoys a comfortable equality. Later on, he will double the rooks on the e-file. } ) 16... Re7 17. a3 { [%cal Gc3b4] White is planning to exchange the dark-squared bishops via b4. Black, however, is just in time to parry this idea with } 17... b6 18. Bb4 c5 { Black is doing perfectly fine. After the moves } 19. Bc3 Ng4 20. dxc5 bxc5 21. b4 e5 22. Nb3 Rc8 23. bxc5 Nxc5 { draw was agreed in the game 1/2-1/2 (23) Chigaev, M (2643) -Kobalia, M (2594) Moscow 2021. } ) ( { White can also start with } 12. Ng5+ { In this case, we should answer by means of } 12... Ke7 { In my opinion, the white knight has committed to g5 too early. Since the f7-square is available now, Black can challenge the knight by means of ...Nh6-f7. White's most logical continuation is } 13. O-O { planning to put pressure on e6 by means of Re1. Nevertheless, Black can defend the e6-pawn by playing } 13... Na6 { It transpires that we always have ...Nc7 in response to Re1. } 14. Bc3 Nh6 15. Nd2 Nf7 $5 { This idea is quite typical for positions in which the white knight has already been committed to g5. It goes without saying that White is not willing to exchange his g5-knight. } 16. Nh3 Nc7 17. Rae1 Kd7 $13 { [%cal Ga7a5,Ga5a4] This position occurred in the game 1/2-1/2 (57) Tate,A (2342) -Najer,E (2648) Chess.com INT 2020. Black managed to take all the important squares under control. He is now ready to start gaining space on the queenside by advancing the a-pawn. } ) 12... Nh6 13. Ne2 Nd7 14. Bf4 Be7 $1 { This is a key move to remember. The exchange of the dark-squared bishops would have been highly favourable for White. We should always prevent White from establishing his knights on f4 and g5, especially with the dark-squared bishops being exchanged. A logical follow-up would be } 15. Bxh6 Rxh6 16. O-O Bd6 17. g3 Nf6 18. Ng5+ Ke7 $11 { [%cal Gf6g4] The inclusion of the moves h2-h4 and ...h7-h5 is clearly in Black's favour. He is now ready to install a knight on g4, thus getting an excellent counterplay. } *
