1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 Qa5+ 7. Nd2 { This is by far White's most challenging continuation. The knight is only temporarily blocking the c1-bishop. Later on, White will play either Nf3 or Nb3 followed by the typical Bg5. For the time being, the knight is well placed on d2 since ...Qa6 can always be met with c2-c4. In this line, White should avoid exchanging queens at any price. After the natural } 7... e6 8. Nf3 { is the most popular option. Usually, White is planning to proceed with 0-0 followed by Nb3, and Bg5. } ( { The main alternative is } 8. Ne2 { This move is connected with the idea of playing 0-0 followed by Nf3 and Bg5. As we will see, however, the knight is often badly placed on e2. } 8... Ne7 { The most natural continuation. In all these lines, f5 is the best square for the knight. } 9. b4 { An interesting attempt to exploit Black's last move. Gaining space on the queenside is an important part of White's strategy. On the downside, the advance b2-b4 creates weaknesses on the light squares. } ( { It's very important that } 9. O-O { can be met by } 9... Qa6 $1 { Remember that due to tactical reasons, the move ...Qa6 works only when White has a knight on e2! } 10. c4 Nf5 11. b3 { The most natural continuation. By overprotecting the c4-pawn, White is planning to proceed with Nf3 followed by Bg5. As we will see, Black shouldn't be tempted by the h4-pawn. } ( { Slow is } 11. g3 { since it allows } 11... Bb4 12. b3 c5 { [%cal Gb8c6] Black is already fighting for an advantage since White's centre is falling apart. The next move is going to be ...Nc6. Practice has seen } 13. Nf3 { which occurred in the game 1-0 (41) Maurizzi,M (2489) -David,A (2517) Chartres 2021. At this point, Black should have played } 13... Nc6 { when the following sequence looks pretty logical - } 14. a3 Ncxd4 15. Nfxd4 cxd4 16. axb4 Qxa1 17. cxd5 Qa6 18. b5 Qb6 $15 { White still needs to prove compensation for the exchange. } ) 11... c5 $1 { This precise move is the main reason why ...Qa6 is justified in positions with the white knight being on e2. Now, White cannot release the central tension in a favourable way. } 12. dxc5 ( { White's problem is that the thematic } 12. Qb1 $2 { will be answered with } 12... cxd4 $17 { Had the white knight been on f3 (instead of e2) , in this position, White could have played cxd5. Now, however, the e2-knight will be hanging. } ) 12... Nc6 13. a3 $2 { This slow move is already a serious mistake. } ( { White should have played } 13. Qc3 { with the idea of cxd5. } 13... Bxc5 { In my opinion, this is the simplest answer. } ( { A decent alternative would be } 13... O-O-O 14. b4 d4 15. Qb3 Nxe5 $13 { when Black has very good counterplay. } ) 14. cxd5 Bd4 15. Nxd4 Ncxd4 16. Qc4 exd5 17. Qxa6 bxa6 $13 { Black has an excellent counterplay in this complex endgame. Objectively speaking, the position is equal. } ) 13... Bxc5 $17 { [%cal Ga8d8] 0-1 (40) Lagarde,M (2648) -Bluebaum,M (2669) Chalons en Champagne 2021 } ) 9... Qb5 $1 { [%cal Ga7a5] You should remember this typical idea. Besides the obvious idea of exchanging the queens, Black is also planning to strike on the queenside with ...a7-a5. } 10. c4 { The most principled choice. After the exchange on c4, White is going to activate his d2-knight. On the other hand, however, the d5-square becomes available for the black knight. } ( { In case of } 10. Qb3 { Black can immediately strike with } 10... a5 11. bxa5 ( { Another direction is } 11. c4 dxc4 12. Nxc4 Nf5 { From this position, the knight not only attacks the d4-pawn but also takes the important d6-square under control. The game might continue } 13. bxa5 Bb4+ 14. Kf1 Bxa5 $13 { Now, it becomes clear how important is that White does not have Nd6+. Practically speaking, Black's play is easier in view of his superior pawn structure. } ) 11... Rxa5 12. Qxb5 Rxb5 13. a4 Ra5 14. Rb1 { This position occurred in the game 0-1 (46) Liang, J (2408) -Khamrakulov, D (2512) New York 2021. At this point, the simplest would have been } 14... b5 15. axb5 Rxb5 16. Ra1 Nf5 $13 { Black managed to solve all the problems. After completing the kingside development, he can consider the thematic ...c6-c5 advance. } ) 10... dxc4 11. Nxc4 Nd5 { Even though the position is objectively balanced, Black's play is easier because White's position is a bit overextended. The lines provided below illustrate the nature of the position. } 12. a4 { This is the most challenging option. } ( { In case of } 12. O-O { Black would be happy to force a transition into an endgame by means of } 12... Nb6 13. Nb2 Qxd3 14. Nxd3 a5 $11 { Black has nothing to worry about. In order to compensate for his structural problems, White should play energetically. } ) 12... Nxb4 13. O-O Qd5 14. Qc3 { White has enough compensation for the pawn in view of his better development. The threat of Ba3 is particularly annoying in this position. In order to solve the problems, Black should play the precise } 14... Qe4 $1 15. Ba3 N8a6 16. Rab1 Qxe2 { The simplest. } ( { Another possibility is } 16... Nd5 17. Qd2 Bxa3 18. Nxa3 O-O $13 { with excellent counterplay. } ) 17. Bxb4 Nxb4 18. Rxb4 Bxb4 19. Qxb4 b6 $13 { Obviously, White has sufficient compensation for the exchange but nothing more. } ) 8... Nh6 9. O-O Nf5 { We have reached a very important theoretical tabiya. This position has been tested in a bunch of high-profile games. The most challenging continuation is considered to be } 10. Nb3 { [%cal Gc1g5] opening the way of the c1-bishop with a tempo. If allowed, White will proceed with Bg5. Note that the white knight is on b3 only temporarily. Provided that White has enough time, he will execute the maneuver Nb3-c1-e2-g3, thus challenging the f5-knight. As we will see a bit later, in such a scenario, Black does not have a good reaction. } ( { The second most popular move is } 10. c4 { Nowadays, however, Black has more than one good way of dealing with this idea. An important position arises after } 10... Be7 11. g3 O-O 12. b3 Rd8 { [%cal Gc6c5] The most straightforward continuation. Black is ready to attack the centre with ...c6-c5 followed by ...Nc6. The idea of the last move is to recapture on d5 with a rook in response to cxd5. Keep in mind that in this line the queen is optimally placed on a5. The move ...Qa6 would be a huge positional mistake since the black queen would be misplaced in this position. } ( { Another very promising continuation is } 12... Nd7 13. Bb2 Rfd8 { [%cal Gd8d3] Due to the opposition along the d-file, Black is ready to proceed with ...dxc4. An instructive line would be } 14. a3 dxc4 $1 { Played at the right moment. Now, 15. bxc4 is impossible in view of 15...Nxe5!. } 15. Nxc4 Qd5 $13 { [%cal Gc6c5] Now, it becomes clear why the black queen is excellently placed on a5. We are now ready to destroy White's centre by means of ...c6-c5. 0-1 (46) Stearman, J (2280) -Donchenko,A (2595) San Francisco 2019 } ) 13. Bb2 c5 $1 { The most straightforward. It's even better to go for this advance with the knight being still on b8. The reason is that Black can increase the pressure on the centre by means of ...Nc6. A high-profile game saw } 14. cxd5 Rxd5 15. Nc4 Qa6 16. Qe4 cxd4 17. Nxd4 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 Nc6 $17 { [%cal Ga8d8] 0-1 (34) Moiseenko,V (2542) -Murzin,V (2513) Sochi 2021. Black has a huge advantage. His next move is going to be ...Rad8, winning the battle for the important d-file. White's position is way too overextended. } ) ( { Another important idea is } 10. a4 { gaining space on the queenside. This is the only case when Black can go for } 10... Qa6 { The reason is that the thematic reaction } 11. c4 { [%csl Rb4] weakens the b4-square. Therefore, Black can seize the opportunity to play } 11... Bb4 12. b3 c5 { [%cal Gb8c6] planning to further increase the pressure with ...Nc6 on the next move. As we have pointed out earlier, with the white knight being on f3, we should reckon with } 13. Qb1 { threatening cxd5.This move marks the beginning of a sequence that allows Black to solve the problems. Remember that this counterplay works only after the inclusion of the moves a2-a4 and ...Bb4. Otherwise, we should refrain from ...Qa6. } ( { The move } 13. dxc5 { played by Dominguez, deserves attention as well. His game against Caruana continued } 13... Nc6 14. Ba3 Bxd2 15. Nxd2 Nxe5 16. Qe2 Ng4 $13 { 0-1 (38) Dominguez Perez,L (2758) -Caruana,F (2835) Lichess.org INT 2020. Black has an excellent chances to overtake the initiative in this complex position. Eventually, Caruana managed to win the game. } ) ( { The continuation } 13. Ba3 Nc6 14. dxc5 Bxd2 15. Nxd2 Nxe5 { transposes to the game Dominguez - Caruana. } ) 13... Nxd4 14. Nxd4 cxd4 15. cxd5 exd5 16. Nf3 O-O { So far, everything was forced. Now, White has some choice. The most natural move seems to be } 17. Bb2 { completing the development and planning to regain the pawn under optimal circumstances. } ( { In case of } 17. Nxd4 { Black manages to arrange his pieces by means of } 17... Nd7 18. Nf3 Rfe8 19. Bb2 Nf8 $13 { Black enjoys an excellent counterplay. He is ready to follow with ... Ne6 and ...Rad8. } ) 17... Nc6 18. Ng5 { The only attempt to create some practical problems. } ( { An online game saw } 18. e6 $6 { which is basically a dubious pawn sacrifice. The game went } 18... fxe6 19. Ng5 d3 20. Qd1 g6 21. Nxe6 Rf7 22. Ng5 { 0-1 (40) Pranav, A (2494) -Mohammad, N (2461) chess24.com INT 2022. At this point, Black's most precise continuation would have been } 22... Rd7 23. Qf3 Rf8 24. Qg3 d4 $15 { when White does not have sufficient compensation for the pawn. } ) 18... d3 { Black will give the pawn back in order to eliminate White's initiative. The position arising after } 19. Rd1 Rae8 20. Qxd3 Qxd3 21. Rxd3 d4 $13 { gives Black an adequate counterplay. } ) 10... Qa6 { Now, as c2-c4 is impossible, playing ...Qa6 is perfectly natural. } 11. Qd1 { It goes without saying that White should refrain from exchanging queens. The next move is going to be Bg5 followed by bringing the knight all the way to g3. Black should play energetically in order to prevent this scenario from happening. My preference here is } 11... c5 { We start our counterplay before White manages to achieve his perfect regroupment. } ( { The following cooperative line shows what happens when Black plays passively. } 11... Nd7 12. Bg5 b6 13. Nc1 c5 14. c3 Rc8 15. Ne2 g6 16. Ng3 $16 { Black does not have favourable way of dealing with the eventual exchange of the knights. Taking on g3 will enable White to put an annoying pressure along the f-file On the other hand, if White manages to spoil our structure with Nxf5, there will be no safe heaven for the black king. } ) 12. dxc5 { This is the best move according to the computer. Now, Black should invest some time in order to regain the pawn. } ( { In case of } 12. Nxc5 Bxc5 13. dxc5 Qc4 14. c3 Qxc5 { we reach a typical Caro-Kann structure. Without the inclusion of the moves h2-h4 and ...h7-h5, Black would have been even slightly better. Now, the position is balanced because White has the g5-square for his bishop. } 15. Nd4 { The idea of removing the strong f5-knight is quite logical. } ( { A decent alternative would be } 15. Bg5 Nc6 16. Re1 Qb6 $13 { Black is doing fine. Later on, he can keep playing on the queenside by means of simple moves such as ...Rac8 followed by ...Na5-c4. For the time being, our king is perfectly safe in the centre. } ) 15... Nxd4 16. cxd4 Qb4 { Once again, without the inclusion of the moves h2-h4 and ...h7-h5, Black would have been slightly better in this typical French structure. Now, the position is just balanced. A GM game continued } 17. a3 Qb6 18. b4 Nc6 19. Be3 a5 20. bxa5 { This position occurred in the game 1-0 (61) Vokhidov, S (2552) -Salem, A (2679) Chess.com INT 2022. At this point, Black should have opted for the following sequence: } 20... Qxa5 21. Rb1 Qxa3 22. Rxb7 Qa6 23. Rb1 Ne7 $13 { Black firm control of the light squares gives him decent counterplay. } ) ( { A strategically interesting position arises after } 12. Bg5 cxd4 13. Nbxd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Nc6 15. Nxc6 Qxc6 16. a4 { Even though Black is doing statically fine, White's g5-bishop is quite annoying. Additionally, having committed to ...h7-h5, Black cannot find a safe place for the king. Remember that the easiest way of solving the problems in this structure is going for an endgame with heavy pieces. This is what happened in the game Adams, M - Salem, A. This encounter continued } 16... Rc8 17. a5 Be7 18. Bxe7 Kxe7 { Usually, in this structure, the endgames with heavy pieces are quite advantageous for Black due to the possibility of playing along the semi-open c-file. On the downside, White can try to exploit Black's slightly weakened kingside. All in all, the position is balanced. } 19. c3 Qb5 20. Qd4 { This position occurred in the game 1-0 (38) Adams, M (2698) -Salem, A (2690) Malmo 2022. Now, Black could have played } 20... Rc4 21. Qxa7 Rhc8 $13 { with an excellent counterplay. } ) 12... Nd7 { This is Black's idea. White cannot keep his extra pawn for too long. Therefore, he should play } 13. Bg5 { In this position, my preference is } 13... Bxc5 { which was also played by Eljanov. In order to successfully accomplish our light-square strategy we are ready to part with the dark-squared bishop. Additionally, with this move, Black is fighting against the possible Nbd4. That being said, the computer likes 13...Nxc5 as well. } 14. c3 { This position occurred in the game 1/2-1/2 (57) Swiercz,D (2665) -Eljanov,P (2681) Chess.com INT 2022. With his last move, White is preparing Nbd4. After the eventual exchanges on d4, we will get a French structure in which the black knight will be quite problematic on d7. Therefore, Black should have played the prophylactic } 14... Qa4 $1 { White's most principled way of fighting for an advantage is } 15. Qd2 O-O 16. Nbd4 Bxd4 17. Nxd4 { Getting rid of the powerful f5-knight is the cornerstone of White's strategy. Black should take the bull by the horns by playing } 17... Nxe5 { The position arising after } ( { The structure arising after } 17... Nxd4 $6 18. cxd4 { is quite problematic for Black due to the misplaced knight. Black does not have enough counterplay on the queenside to compensate for the weakened kingside. } ) 18. Nxf5 exf5 19. Rfe1 f6 20. Bf4 Ng6 21. Qxd5+ Rf7 $13 { is obviously unclear. Black, however, enjoys an adequate counterplay. } *
