{In this example, we are going to examine another interesting gambit line. The starting position of this variation arises after} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 Qa5+ 7. b4 Qxb4+ 8. Nd2 {By means of this pawn sacrifice, White wants to force the black queen into the exposed b4-square and to open the b-file for the rook. Now, we need to reckon with the threat of Rb1. Also, White can try to make use of his lead in development by means of c2-c4.} e6 {This is the most natural continuation. One of the ideas is to answer} 9. Rb1 {with} Qe7 {defending the b7-pawn. The closed nature of the position makes White's lead in development less significant. Nevertheless, White definitely has compensation due to his space advantage and Black's weakened kingside. At this point, the most logical move is} 10. c4 {As mentioned above, White should try to play as energetically as possible. If he delays the advance c2-c4, Black will close the position with ...b7-b5. The main crossroads is being reached after} Nh6 11. Ne2 Nf5 {Besides attacking the h4-pawn, Black is ready to complete the development by means of simple moves such as ...Qd7 and ...Be7. Once again, energetic play is required from White.} 12. Ng3 {The most challenging continuation. As a rule in this structure, White tries to get rid of the strongest black piece the f5-knight.} ({The natural} 12. Nf3 {turns out to be a bit slow. It allows} dxc4 13. Qxc4 b5 {Black not only eliminates the pressure on the b-file, but also grabs space on the queenside. After protecting the c6-pawn with the queen, he will be ready to develop the knight via a6.} 14. Qc3 {White tries to keep the queen as active as possible. This position occurred in the game 0-1 (36) Maneluk, D (2349) -Khudyakov, S (2239) Cheliabinsk 2022} ({In case of} 14. Qc2 Qd7 $13 {[%cal Gb8a6] Black enjoys an excellent position. The next move is going to be ...Na6.}) 14... a5 $1 {[%cal Ge7b4] Making use of the position of the white queen in order to win more space on the queenside. Now, White should reckon with the annoying threat of ...Qb4. At this point, the following sequence seems pretty logical -} 15. a3 Qd7 16. O-O Na6 17. Ng3 Nxg3 18. fxg3 Be7 19. Ng5 O-O $13 {White has compensation for the pawn but nothing more. The position is objectively balanced. In case of necessity, Black is always ready to give the dark-squared bishop for the white knight.}) 12... Nxh4 {Black has nothing better than accepting the challenge.} 13. Nde4 {This is the only way to pose Black some practical problems. Concrete analysis shows that White's compensation is enough for equality.} ({Wrong is} 13. Rxh4 $2 Qxh4 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Rxb7 Qd8 $19 {[%cal Gb8d7] when Black is winning. The next move is going to be ...Nd7. White does not have the slightest compensation.}) 13... dxe4 {This move practically forces a draw.} ({In case of} 13... Nxg2+ 14. Kf1 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Qd7 16. Kxg2 $44 {White enjoys a dangerous initiative in return for the pawns.}) ({An attempt to keep the position more complicated is} 13... Nf5 14. cxd5 cxd5 {Now, White faces a choice between two equally good alternatives.} 15. Nc5 {This move leads to a forced sequence resulting in a position with a material imbalance.Black is sacrificing the queen. The following sequence is logical and forced:} ({Another direction is} 15. Nxf5 dxe4 16. Qb5+ Qd7 17. Nd6+ Bxd6 18. exd6 b6 19. Qg5 Qxd6 20. Bf4 Qxd4 {So far, everything has been more or less forced. Black has four extra pawns, but White's initiative is rather dangerous. As always, the engine gives equality, provided that both sides play precisely. The following line is quite characteristic.} 21. Rd1 Qc3+ 22. Bd2 Qf6 23. Rxh5 Rxh5 24. Qxh5 g6 25. Qh7 Qe7 $11 {The position is balanced.}) 15... Nxg3 16. Rxb7 Qxb7 17. Nxb7 Nxh1 18. Qb5+ Nd7 {[%cal Ga8c8]} 19. Qc6 $1 {White should play this move. Otherwise, Black will consolidate with ...Rc8.} Bb4+ 20. Kf1 O-O 21. Qxd7 Rac8 22. Be3 Rc2 23. Kg1 Nxf2 24. Bxf2 Rxa2 $11 {Black has managed to obtain enough material for the queen. The position is objectively equal, but in a human game everything can happen.}) 14. Nxe4 Qd8 15. Bg5 {This move forces Black to go for a repetition.} Qa5+ 16. Bd2 Qd8 17. Bg5 Qa5+ 18. Bd2 Qd8 19. Bg5 {1/2-1/2 (19) Santos,J (2384) -Martins,B (2308) Leiria 2022} 0-1

