1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 { [%cal Gf1d3] With this move, White is preventing the natural ...e7-e6. On the next move, he is ready to follow up with Bd3 on the next move. The drawback of this continuation is that the b2-pawn is left unprotected. Therefore, Black's most principled answer is } 5... Qb6 { Black not only puts pressure on d4 and b2 but is also ready to attack the centre by means of ... e7-e6 and ...c6-c5. The only way to justify the previous move is } 6. Bd3 { Positionally speaking, this move is quite justified. White always tries to exchange the f5-bishop which is an important defender. On the other hand, White is basically sacrificing the important d4-pawn. Even though Black can handle this line in a positional manner, my suggestion would be the principled } 6... Qxd4 { Nowadays, modern computers prove that White's compensation is quite problematic in this line. } ( { Analysis shows that after } 6... Qxb2 $2 7. Bxf5 Qxa1 8. e6 $18 { White has a winning advantage. We will not go into detail, but everyone can check this position for himself. } ) 7. Nf3 Qg4 8. Bxf5 Qxf5 9. O-O { [%cal Gc2c4] This is the most important tabiya of the variation. Having completed the development, White is now ready to open the position with c2-c4. At the same time, the static nature of the position makes it very difficult for White to prove compensation. } ( { The immediate } 9. c4 { is well met by } 9... Qe4+ 10. Be3 e6 { This move is possible since it turns out that 11.Qb3 is not a threat. White has nothing better than } 11. Nbd2 ( { With the queen on d5, the move } 11. cxd5 { can be answered with } 11... Qxd5 $15 { Black has an obvious advantage. } ) ( { Black's point is that } 11. Qb3 $2 { will be met by } 11... Qxc4 12. Qxb7 Qb4+ $19 { After the exchange of the queens, White does not have the slightest compensation for the pawn. } ) 11... Qd3 12. Rc1 { White has nothing better than speculating on the position of the black queen. His idea is to proceed with Rc3 on the next move. } ( { After } 12. cxd5 exd5 $15 { Black's advantage is out of the question. Besides having a compact pawn structure, he will quickly complete the development. } ) 12... Bb4 { The most precise move. Besides completing the development, Black also prevents Rc3. Additionally, we are planning to answer } 13. cxd5 exd5 14. a3 { with } 14... Bxd2+ { It goes without saying that every exchange makes Black's play easier. } 15. Bxd2 { This position occurred in the game 0-1 (61) Hector,J (2466) -Domingo Nunez,R (2420) Ballerup 2023. At this point, Black could have played } 15... Ne7 16. Rc3 Qe4+ 17. Re3 Qg4 $15 { [%cal Gb8a6,Ga6c7,Gc7e6] with an advantage. Black's idea is to establish a solid blockade on the light squares. For instance, putting the knights on e6 and f5 would be a good start. } ) 9... e6 { The most solid and natural continuation. } ( { Recent practice shows that the alternative } 9... f6 { leads to much more complicated positions. } ) 10. c4 { The only logical move. White should try to open the position as soon as possible. Additionally, with his last move, he creates the threat of Qb3. Therefore, Black should start with } 10... Nd7 { One of the ideas behind this move is to answer Qb3 with ...Nc5. At the same time, Black proceeds with the development. } 11. cxd5 { The most logical and popular move. } ( { Of course, White can also start with } 11. Nc3 { In this case, Black's most precise reaction is } 11... Be7 { Eliminating the annoying g5-bishop is the cornerstone of our strategy. } 12. cxd5 ( { In case of a slow move such as } 12. Re1 { Black can consider } 12... Nc5 { planning to exchange the queens by means of ... Qd3. } ) 12... exd5 { [%cal Gd7c5,Gc5e6] This is the standard recapture. Besides keeping the b5-square under control, Black can use the e6-square for the purposes of his blockade. A typical idea is to follow with ...Nc5-e6. } 13. Re1 Nc5 { This key position occurred in two encounters. White failed to prove anything significant. } 14. Ne2 { [%cal Ge2d4] This move was played by Shevchenko in his game against Howell. The obvious idea is to proceed with Ned4. } ( { The attempt to further open the position by means of } 14. b4 $6 Ne6 15. b5 { is logical but slow. Black has enough time to coordinate his pieces - } 15... Bxg5 16. bxc6 bxc6 17. Nxg5 Ne7 $17 { This position occurred in the game 0-1 (35) Asgari, M (2160) -Sahin, S (2203) Ankara 2023. White does not have any compensation for the pawn. } ) 14... Bxg5 15. Ned4 Qd3 { Exchanging queens is the most practical solution. According to the computer, 15...Qg6 and 15...Qg4 are perfectly playable as well. } 16. Nxg5 Qxd1 17. Raxd1 Ne7 18. b4 { This position was reached in the game 0-1 (49) Shevchenko, K (2592) -Howell, D (2663) chess24. com INT 2020. Now, Black could have played } 18... Ne4 19. Nxe4 dxe4 20. Rxe4 Rd8 $11 { with equality. In my opinion, playing with Black is easier in view of White's overextended position. } ) 11... exd5 { Once again, we get this familiar structure. Most probably, we will transpose to a variation that has been covered under the 11.Nc3 move order. } 12. Re1 { The most sensible continuation. Now, Black should reckon with the advance e5-e6. } ( { After } 12. Nc3 Be7 { we tranpose to 11.Nc3. } ) ( { Obviously, we need to check the aggressive } 12. e6 $2 { Fortunately, this move does not work tactically. } 12... fxe6 13. Nd4 ( { After } 13. Re1 { Black should play } 13... Bc5 $19 { taking the d4-square under control. White does not have any compensation for the sacrificed material. } ) 13... Qf7 { Black is ready to proceed with the development. Even the advance ...e6-e5 comes into consideration. The tempting } 14. Nxe6 $2 { does not work in view of the following sequence } 14... Qxe6 15. Re1 Ne5 16. f4 Bd6 17. fxe5 Bc5+ 18. Kh1 Ne7 $19 { This position was reached in the game 0-1 (30) Djokic, M (2227) -Villegas, P (2367) Chess.com INT 2020. Black has a winning advantage. } ) 12... Nc5 13. Nc3 Be7 { We are back in the game Shevchenko - Howell which was examined under the 11.Nc3 move order. } *
