{This is the dream endgame that you might get in the structure with doubled pawns on the f-file. Since White is left only with his useless dark-squared bishop, he has nothing to oppose to our play on the light squares. Remember that in such structures, the advance ...b7-b5 is a typical way of fixing White's queenside majority. If allowed, Black can even follow with ...a7-a5-a4. Another part of our plan is to create kingside weaknesses by advancing the h-pawn. In such positions, the play is going for two results only.}  *

