[Black "Q+N vs Q+N"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[EventDate "2023.09.24"]
[FEN "r3r1k1/p4ppp/2p1np2/1p1q4/3P4/2PQ4/PP2NPPP/R4RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[PlyCount "15"]
[SetUp "1"]
[SourceVersionDate "2023.12.05"]

{ Another typically favourable for Black position is queen & knight versus queen & knight. In the position on the diagram, Black has managed to achieve the typically favourable ...b7-b5 advance. Note that putting the queenside majority into motion is not easy at all for White. Even if White manages to play b2-b3 followed by c3-c4, Black has enough resources to put pressure on d4. At the same time, by advancing the h-pawn (if possible, all the way to h3) Black can create an interesting play on the kingside. The following sequence shows how the play might develop in such positions. } 1... g6 { [%cal Gg8g7, Gh7h5] It's always useful to make this thematic move. Black is ready to proceed with natural moves such as ...Kg7 followed by the advance of the h-pawn. At the same time. with his last move, Black is getting ready to answer Ng3 with ...f6-f5. One of the most important advantages of the doubled pawns is that they allow you to win space without creating weaknesses. } 2. b3 Kg7 3. Rfd1 Rad8 4. Rac1 h5 5. Rc2 h4 { [%cal Gh4h3] } 6. h3 Rd7 7. c4 bxc4 8. bxc4 Qa5 $15 { It transpires that White's centre is rather exposed. Hence, Black can use all his pieces to put pressure on the central pawns. Additionally, the h4-pawn is an important asset both in the endgame and in the middlegame. Black is already slightly better. } *
