[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Endgame"]
[Black "Q&R vs Q&R"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[EventDate "2023.09.24"]
[FEN "r7/pp3pkp/2p1qpp1/8/3P4/2P5/PPQ2PPP/3R2K1 w - - 0 6"]
[PlyCount "6"]
[SetUp "1"]
[SourceVersionDate "2023.12.05"]

{ For a very long time, heavy pieces endgames were considered to be favourable for White in this pawn structure. The reason is simple. White has a straightforward way to create a central passed pawn, thus engaging at least one heavy piece. Modern computers, however, proved that things are not one-sided. First of all, very often Black manages to create an excellent counterplay on the e-file. Additionally, the advance of the h-pawn has the potential to make the white king constantly vulnerable. Last, but not least, if Black blocks the d5-pawn with a queen, the queen will also actively participate in the game. In the position on the diagram, the play might continue } 6. c4 Re8 7. Kf1 h5 $1 { Played at the right moment. If possible, we will push the pawn all the way to h3. } 8. h3 h4 $11 { [%csl Gh4] As a rule, almost all endgames in which Black has a pawn on h4 are acceptable for him. For instance, in this position, we are not afraid of exchanging the queens. In case of necessity, the king can easily block the potential passed pawn on the d-file. In positions with queens on the board, White should always reckon with ideas such as ...Qd6-h2. Very often, the advance ...g6-g5-g4 comes into consideration as well. } *
