[FEN "r4rk1/pp3ppp/2pq1p2/8/2PP4/8/PPQ2PPP/3R1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[PlyCount "11"]
[SetUp "1"]
[SourceVersionDate "2023.12.05"]

{ Endgames with queens and four rooks on the board are not dangerous for Black as well. Most likely, one pair of rooks is going to be exchanged on the e-file. In this case, we get back to the previous example. Let's see what White can achieve by trying to keep all the rooks on the board. A possible strategy is to play d4-d5 and double the rooks behind the passed pawn. The game might continue } 1... Rad8 2. d5 cxd5 3. cxd5 h5 $1 { Remember that this thematic advance is our best bet on counterplay. A typical position would arise after } 4. Rd3 Rfe8 5. Rfd1 Qb4 6. Kf1 Rd6 $11 { [%cal Ge8e5,Gh5h4] The d5-pawn is safely blocked. It turns out that White cannot support the further advance of the passer because he should take care of the king. Black can increase his attacking potential by means of simple moves such as ...h5-h4 and ...Re5. At any moment, the queen can appear on the kingside. } *
