{In this structure, queen and light-squared bishop are fighting very successfully against queen and knight. There are two reasons for that: 1) Black's bishop has the ability to control the entire board 2) There are no central outposts for the white knight. Once again, trying to create weaknesses by advancing the h-pawn is one of Black's key ideas. Another possibility is to fix White's queenside majority by means of ...b7-b5 followed by ...a7-a5-a4. Obviously, in this case, we should pay attention to the possible knight maneuver to c5. Even then, however, Black can put a bishop on d5, thus trying to prove that the c5-knight is useless.}  *

