{ The endgame with only light-squared bishops on the board is the worst possible scenario for Black. In this case, White can just bring the king to the queenside and start advancing his majority. Black does not have any counterplay on the kingside. The game might continue with } 1. c4 { This move makes a lot of sense. Now, Black cannot even try to fix the structure with ... b7-b5. } ( { Even if Black is in time to play ...b7-b5, however, White is still winning. The following line provides a good illustration. } 1. Kf1 b5 2. Ke2 Kf8 3. Kd2 Ke7 4. c4 $1 { This is the key idea that White needs to remember. Now, the white king will be directed to the queenside. } 4... bxc4 5. Be2 Kd6 6. Kc3 Bd5 7. g3 Be6 8. Bxc4 { [%cal Gc3b4,Gb4a5,Ga5a6] Black cannot avoid the exchange of the bishops. The pawn endgame is winning for White. For instance, after } 8... Kc7 9. Kb4 Kd6 10. Bxe6 fxe6 11. Ka5 $18 { Black is helpless. } ) 1... f5 2. g3 Kf8 3. c5 $1 { [%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f2,Gf2e3,Ge3d2,Gd2c3,Gd3c4,Gd4d5] This counterintuitive move is rather thematic. After bringing the king all the way to c3, White is planning to proceed with Bc4 and d5-d5. Black has absolutely nothing to do with this idea. The following line is quite illustrative. } 3... Ke7 4. f4 { Good positional move. White is fixing the kingside weaknesses. Now, the king can go to the queenside. } 4... Kd7 5. Kf2 Ke7 6. Ke3 Kd7 7. Kd2 Ke7 8. Kc3 Kd7 9. Bc4 Ke7 10. d5 cxd5 11. Be2 $18 { [%cal Gc3d4,Ge2f3] Mission completed. White is ready to follow with Kd4 and Bf3. His position is totally winning. } *
