1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Ne2 Re8 9. O-O Nd7 10. Bf4 Nf8 11. Qd2 Ng6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Rfe1 Be6 14. Ng3 Rad8 15. a3 Bd5 16. Rxe8+ Rxe8 17. Re1 Rxe1+ 18. Qxe1 Kf8 19. Nf5 Qe6 20. Qe3 Qxe3 21. Nxe3 Be6 { In this endgame, Black is deprived of any counterplay. White will gradually start advancing the queenside pawns. Of course, the white king will be directed to the queenside. Note that if we add a pair of rooks, Black will hold without problems. } 22. g3 { It's useful to start with this move designed to restrict the black knight. Another idea is to gain further space with f2-f4. } 22... Ne7 { The knight has nothing to do on g6. Black wants to go ...f6-f5 followed by bringing the king to the centre. } ( { The attempt to fix the queenside with } 22... b5 { does not work either. The following sequence is quite instructive - } 23. Kf1 Ne7 24. Ke2 Ke8 25. Bc2 $1 { [%cal Ga3a4] An important move in White's strategy. The idea is to prepare a3-a4, this provoking the advance ...a7-a6. White's idea can be seen after } 25... g6 26. Kd2 Kd7 27. a4 { [%cal Ga4b5,Gc6b5,Gb2b3,Gc3c4] } 27... a6 { This move is forced. Otherwise, White will create two connected passed pawns in the centre by means of axb5 followed by b2-b3 and c3-c4. } 28. Bd3 Kc7 29. a5 $16 { We can now see why provoking ...a7-a6 was so important. Now, the eventual appearance of the white knight on c5 would be very annoying for Black. It goes without saying that the thematic b2-b3 followed by c3-c4 is always on the agenda. } ) 23. f4 g6 24. Kf2 Ke8 25. c4 Kd8 26. Ke2 { [%cal Ge2d2,Gd2c3] This is the right strategy. The king is heading towards the queenside. After bringing the king to c3, White will start advancing his majority. Meanwhile, Black has nothing to oppose to this plan. The following couple of moves are quite logical - } 26... Kc7 27. Kd2 f5 28. Kc3 Kd6 29. b4 f6 30. h4 Bf7 31. Be2 $1 { [%cal Ge2f3] Another good idea. Given the fact that White is planning to proceed with a3-a4 followed by b4-b5, the bishop will be ideally placed on f3. The game continued } 31... Be6 32. Bf3 Bf7 33. a4 Be6 34. b5 $16 { [%cal Gc3b4,Gc4c5,Ga4a5] White's advantage is almost decisive. He is ready to proceed with Kb4 followed by c4-c5 and a4-a5. The fact that Vitiugov eventually lost can be explained by the fast time control. } 34... Bf7 35. Kb4 b6 36. c5+ Kc7 37. a5 bxc5+ 38. Kxc5 cxb5 39. Kxb5 Nc8 40. Kc5 Nd6 41. Nd5+ Bxd5 42. Kxd5 Kd7 43. h5 Nb7 44. a6 Nd6 45. hxg6 hxg6 46. Bg2 Nb5 47. Kc5 Nc3 48. Bc6+ Kc7 49. Be8 g5 50. Kc4 Ne4 51. Kd5 Nxg3 52. fxg5 fxg5 53. Ke5 f4 54. d5 f3 55. Bb5 f2 56. d6+ Kd8 *
