1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qc2 Re8+ 9. Ne2 h5 10. O-O h4 11. h3 Nd7 12. Be3 Nf8 13. Qd2 Ng6 14. Nf4 { White's last move is dubious. When facing this structure, many white players are convinced that simplifications are always in their favour. As we have already seen, however, this is far from the truth. Black's reaction is rather instructive - } 14... Bxf4 $1 { In this structure, Black is always ready to give the dark-squared bishop for a knight. Later on, if we manage to exchange the light-squared bishops as well, White will be left with his useless dark-squared bishop. } 15. Bxf4 Be6 { [%cal Gd8d7, Ge6f5] Black is already threatening to proceed with ...Qd7 followed by ...Bf5. It turns out that White cannot easily prevent this simple idea. Note that the middlegame with opposite-coloured bishops arising after Bxg6 is definitely in Black's favour. In such positions, the strong light-squared bishop would provide Black with a huge attacking potential on the kingside. } 16. Rfe1 Qd7 17. Re2 Bf5 18. Bh2 Bxd3 19. Qxd3 Rxe2 20. Qxe2 Re8 { Mission completed. Practically speaking, White's position is already more difficult. Now, Black should optimally arrange his pieces in order to carry out his light square strategy. } 21. Qd2 { At this point, Black should have played } 21... Ne7 { [%cal Ge7f5] First of all, we need to prioritize the activity of the knight. We are now ready to put it on the active f5-square. } ( 21... Qd5 { Even though this move keeps a slight advantage, I consider it less precise. The game continued } 22. b3 a5 23. Re1 Rxe1+ 24. Qxe1 a4 25. Qd1 axb3 26. axb3 b5 27. Bc7 Nf8 28. Qf3 Qd7 29. Bb6 Ne6 30. c4 bxc4 31. bxc4 Qb7 32. Bc5 Qb1+ 33. Kh2 Qc2 34. Qxc6 Qxf2 35. Qa8+ Kh7 36. Qe4+ f5 37. Qf3 Qc2 38. Bb6 Kg6 39. d5 Ng5 40. Qf4 Ne4 41. c5 Qd1 42. Qxh4 Qxd5 43. Qf4 Nxc5 44. Qg3+ Kh7 45. Qh4+ Kg8 46. Bxc5 Qxc5 47. Qd8+ Qf8 48. Qg5 Qd6+ 49. Kg1 g6 50. Qe3 Qf6 51. Qf3 Kg7 52. Kh1 Qe5 53. Kg1 Kf6 54. Qc6+ Qe6 55. Qc3+ Qe5 56. Qc6+ Kg5 57. Qf3 Qf4 58. Qe2 Qd4+ 59. Kh1 Kf6 60. Qa6+ Kg5 61. Qe2 Qd6 62. Qe1 Kf6 63. Qa1+ Ke6 64. Qe1+ Qe5 65. Qd1 Ke7 66. Qf1 Qe3 67. Qd1 Kf6 68. Qa1+ Kg5 69. Qf1 f4 70. Qd1 f6 71. Qd5+ Qe5 72. Qd1 Kh6 73. Qf1 Qe3 74. Qd1 Qg3 75. Qf1 Kg5 76. Qd1 Qe3 77. Qd5+ Kh6 78. Qg8 f3 79. gxf3 Qxf3+ 80. Kh2 Qf2+ 81. Kh1 Qg3 82. Qh8+ Kg5 83. Qc8 f5 84. Qd8+ Kh5 85. Qh8+ Kg5 86. Qd8+ Kf4 87. Qd6+ Kf3 88. Qd3+ Kf2 89. Qd2+ Kf1 90. Qd1+ Qe1 91. Qf3+ Qf2 92. Qd1+ Qe1 93. Qf3+ Qf2 94. Qd1+ Qe1 { 1/2 - 1/2 } ) 22. Re1 Nf5 23. Rxe8+ Qxe8 24. Bf4 Qe4 25. b3 g5 $15 { White's position is practically very unpleasant. The queenside majority is useless while Black's kingside play may become rather annoying. } 1/2-1/2
