{A very similar situation was reached in the game Tissir, M - Shimanov, A, 2019. This model game will give an even better feeling of how powerful the light square strategy can be. In this position, Black played} 16... Bxf4 17. Bxf4 Qd7 {[%cal Ge6f5] Just like in the previous example. Black is ready to proceed with ...Bf5 on the next move. The following couple of moves are pretty natural -} 18. Re2 Bf5 19. Bxf5 Qxf5 20. Rxe8+ Rxe8 21. Be3 b5 $1 {[%csl Ra3,Rb2,Rc3,Rd4] Another thematic move. As we have seen on multiple occasions, fixing the queenside with the advance ...b7-b5 is rather typical in this structure.} 22. Rd1 Qd5 23. Qc2 Ne7 $1 {Another key idea! As we have seen in the previous example, the knight should be rerouted to the more active f5-square.} 24. Re1 Nf5 25. Bd2 Re6 $1 {In general, Black is quite OK with the exchange of the rooks. Shimanov, however, wants to execute this exchange on his own terms. The game continued} 26. Rxe6 fxe6 27. Qd3 a5 $1 28. Kf1 a4 $17 {Black is positionally winning. Besides having full control of the white squares, he is playing with an extra pawn. Since this is a blitz game, the remaining moves will be left without comments. Nevertheless, I encourage you to see how Shimanov managed to convert his advantage into a full point.} 29. Be3 Nd6 30. Bc1 Kf7 31. Kg1 Qf5 32. Qxf5 Nxf5 33. Kf1 Ke7 34. Ke2 Kd6 35. Kd3 Kd5 36. Bd2 Nd6 37. Bc1 Nc4 38. f3 Nd6 39. Bf4 Nf5 40. Bd2 Ne7 41. Bc1 Nc8 42. Bd2 Nb6 43. Be3 Nc4 44. Bc1 g6 45. Kc2 Na5 46. Kd3 c5 47. dxc5 Kxc5 48. Bh6 Nc4 49. Kc2 Kd5 50. Bc1 e5 51. Kd3 f5 52. Kc2 e4 53. fxe4+ Kxe4 54. Bg5 f4 55. Bf6 Ne3+ 56. Kd2 Nxg2 57. b3 axb3 58. c4 bxc4 59. a4 Ne3 60. a5 c3+ 61. Bxc3 Nc4+ 62. Ke2 Nxa5 0-1

