{Exactly the same position occurred in another game of Rasmus Svane. Not without the help of his opponent, Black managed to score an instructive victory.} 19. Kf1 $2 {Obviously this typical blitz move is a huge mistake since it allows} Bc4+ {[%cal Gg6g5] It turns out that the knight has no squares in response to the advance ...g6-g5. Therefore, White played} 20. Ne2 {voluntarily pinning himself. Obviously, he wants to get rid of the pin by means of b2-b3. At this point, Svane played another precise move -} a5 $1 {[%cal Ga5a4] The idea is to fix the queenside structure by means of ...a5-a4. At the same time. if White plays b2-b3, then Black will be able to create queenside weaknesses with ...a5-a4.} ({We don't have time to increase the pressure on e2 by playing} 20... Re7 {in view of} 21. b3 {when White manages to untangle.}) 21. b3 Bf7 22. Nf4 g5 23. Nd3 b6 {Black is using his pawns rather skilfully. As often happens in this structure, there are no suitable squares for the white knight. The game continued} 24. Rxe8+ Rxe8 25. Re1 Ra8 $1 {Of course! Black should keep at least a pair of rooks in order to successfully attack the targets in White's camp. Now, the idea is to create queenside weaknesses with ...a5-a4. The game went} 26. Re7 a4 27. c4 axb3 28. axb3 Ra3 $17 {with a huge advantage for Black. Svane managed to convert it in an instructive way.} 29. Nc1 Ra1 30. Re1 b5 31. c5 Rb1 32. f3 Bd5 33. Kf2 Kf7 34. Ne2 Rxb3 35. Ra1 Rb2 36. Ke3 Rb3+ 37. Kf2 Bc4 38. Ra7+ Kg6 39. Nc1 Rc3 40. Na2 Rc2+ 41. Ke3 Rxa2 42. Rc7 Bd5 0-1

