1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Ne2 Re8 9. Qc2 h5 10. O-O h4 11. h3 Nd7 12. Bf4 Nf8 13. Qd2 Be6 14. c4 Qd7 15. b3 Rad8 16. Rad1 Bc7 17. Rfe1 a5 18. Bxc7 Qxc7 19. Qf4 Qxf4 20. Nxf4 {At this point, Black should decide what type of ending he wants to play. Note that Black's h4-pawn is a tremendous asset in every endgame position. In the game, Black played} g6 {which is perfectly normal. In principle, in this structure, we are never afraid to fight with a knight against White's light-squared bishop.} ({It's even more important to see what happens if we exchange one pair of rooks by means of} 20... Bd7 21. Rxe8 Rxe8 {In this position, Black is doing perfectly fine, as long as he keeps his rook on the board. In positions with a pawn on h4, however, even the exchange of the rooks is not one-sided. White's problem is that he cannot simply bring the king to the queenside. Black will always have a kingside counterplay based on ...g7-g5 followed by ...f6-f5, and ...g5-g4.} 22. Bf1 ({Obviously, the attempt to exchange the rooks by playing} 22. Kf1 g6 23. Re1 {is best answered with} Rd8 $1 {The game might continue} 24. Ke2 Be6 25. Ke3 f5 {[%cal Gg6g5] The advance ...f6-f5 is an important part of Black's strategy in every endgame. As pointed out earlier, the possibility to gain space without creating weaknesses is one of the essential advantages of the doubled pawns. Now, White should always reckon with the advance ...g6-g5.}) ({We don't need to react in response to} 22. d5 {In such positions, you can just follow with the universally good move} g6 $13 {[%cal Gg8g7,Gf6f5,Gg7f6] planning to proceed with ...f6-f5 followed by ...Kg7-f6. The structure arising after} 23. dxc6 Bxc6 {is quite acceptable for Black. White's queenside majority is not that mobile. At the same time, thanks to the h4-pawn, Black can easily create targets on the kingside.}) 22... Ne6 {Exchanging the knights is a good idea when the rooks are on the board.} 23. Nxe6 fxe6 $11 {This is the safe choice after which the position is completely equal.} ({If you want to keep the position more complicated, I can suggest} 23... Bxe6 {With rooks on the board, White cannot make use of the queenside majority. Whenever White plays d4-d5, we can just take and play ...Bd7. Later on, our king will try to block the white passer. On the other hand, Black can start advancing the kingside pawns. Once again, our far-advanced h4-pawn is tremendously important.})) 21. d5 cxd5 {An ambitious continuation. In the future, Black will try to prove that White's central passed pawn is a liability.} ({Of course, completely possible would have been} 21... Bd7 $11 {with equality.}) 22. cxd5 Bd7 23. d6 $2 {This is already a mistake since the d6-pawn can be easily surrounded.} ({The safe choice would have been} 23. Rxe8 Rxe8 24. Rc1 f5 25. Rc7 Re1+ 26. Kh2 b5 $11 {when the position is equal.}) 23... Rxe1+ 24. Rxe1 Bc6 $17 {Black is winning a pawn. Later on, Tari managed to convert his huge advantage.} 25. Re7 Rxd6 26. Bc4 Rd1+ 27. Kh2 Rd7 28. Bxf7+ Kg7 29. Rxd7 Bxd7 30. Bd5 g5 31. Nd3 b6 32. Nb2 b5 33. Nd3 Be6 34. Bc6 Bd7 35. Bd5 Ne6 36. Bxe6 Bxe6 37. Nc5 Bd5 38. f3 Kf7 39. Kg1 Ke7 40. Kf2 Kd6 41. Nd3 a4 42. bxa4 bxa4 43. a3 Bc4 44. Nb2 Bb5 45. Nd1 Kc5 46. Ke3 Kc4 47. Ke4 Bd7 48. Ne3+ Kb3 49. Kd4 Kxa3 50. Kc3 Ka2 51. Nd5 a3 52. Nb4+ Kb1 53. Kb3 a2 54. Nxa2 Be6+ 55. Kb4 Bxa2 56. Kc5 Kc2 57. Kd6 Kd3 58. Ke7 Ke3 59. Kxf6 Kf4 60. Kg6 Bc4 61. Kh5 Bf1 0-1

