{ This position was reached in the game Kacharava, N - Jojua, D, 2020. White managed to place his pieces on active and good squares. At every moment, Black should reckon with the potential advance d4-d5. On the other hand, the h4-pawn would be a valuable asset in every endgame. In the game, Black decided to untangle by means of } 19... Bd7 20. Rxe8 Rxe8 21. Bc2 { White keeps preparing the advance d4-d5. In this position, the simplest way of solving all the problems is } 21... Ne6 { This idea is based on our knowledge that the endgame rook and bishop versus rook and bishop is perfectly fine for Black. The presence of the h4-pawn makes things even better. } 22. Nxe6 Qxd2 23. Rxd2 Bxe6 { I choose to make this move main line for didactic purposes. } ( { The game continued with } 23... fxe6 $11 { which leads to full equality. } ) 24. f4 f5 $1 { This is a key move in every endgame. Fighting for space on the kingside is an important part of Black's strategy. } 25. Kf2 Kf8 $1 { [%cal Gf8e7,Ge7d6] Another key idea to remember. Once Black manages to put the king on d6, the advance d4-d5 is completely ineffective. The following sample line shows how the game might develop in such positions. } 26. Bd1 Ke7 27. Bf3 Rd8 28. Ke3 Kd6 ( { Another good option is } 28... f6 { [%cal Gg7g5,Gg5g4] planning the advance of the g-pawn. Note that the pawn endgame arising after } 29. d5 cxd5 30. Bxd5 Bxd5 31. Rxd5 $4 Rxd5 32. cxd5 Kd6 33. Kd4 b5 { is even lost for White! } ) 29. d5 cxd5 30. Bxd5 Re8 $11 { The draw is obvious. } 1/2-1/2
