{Once again, we see this endgame with light-squared bishops and a pair of knights. As we already know, in such positions, Black should keep the rooks on the board. Additionally, when the black pawn is already on h4, Black can even play for a win. The winning ideas were beautifully demonstrated by Halkias in this model game. In this position, he played} 19... Ne6 {As mentioned earlier, when the rooks are still on the board, the exchange of the knights is perfectly OK for Black.} 20. Ne2 a5 {Winning space on the wings is never a mistake in these endgames. Obviously, another possibility would have been ... f6-f5 followed by ...Kf6.} 21. Rd1 Rd8 {I like this idea. The rook has nothing to do on e8 anymore. In anticipation of the typical advance c3-c4, Halkias puts the rook on d8. It turns out that White has difficulties finding a concrete plan.} 22. Bc2 Bc8 23. Bb3 b6 {[%cal Gc8a6] Black indicates his intention of playing ...Ba6. Therefore, White responded with} 24. Bc4 {The position is still objectively equal. It seems, however, that playing with Black is easier. In the next stage, Halkias starts gaining space on both wings.} b5 25. Bd3 a4 26. a3 f5 {[%cal Gg7f6,Gg6g5,Gg5g4] White is left without counterplay. Now, at any moment, he should reckon with .. .Kf6 followed by ... g6-g5-g4.} 27. Bc2 Kf6 28. f3 {This is already a slight inaccuracy since White weakens the e3-square. For a human player, however, it's difficult to sit and wait.} Nc7 {[%cal Gc7d5] The knight is going to be immediately rerouted to d5. Another idea is ...Be6-c4. Meanwhile, White is completely paralyzed.} 29. Kf2 Be6 30. Nf4 Bc4 31. Bd3 $2 {This is already a huge mistake after which it's probably impossible to save the game.} ({White should have played} 31. Nd3 {when a possible continuation would have been} Bxd3 32. Bxd3 Kg5 33. Bf1 Kf4 $15 {[%cal Gc7d5] with ...Nd5 to follow. Even though Black's advantage is obvious, White should be able to hold.}) 31... g5 32. Ne2 Nd5 $19 {[%cal Gd8e8] Black enjoys full domination. The next move is ...Re8. Very soon, White's position will start falling apart.} 33. Nc1 Re8 34. Rd2 Nf4 35. Bc2 Rd8 36. Bd3 c5 37. Bxc4 bxc4 38. Ke1 cxd4 39. cxd4 Rb8 40. Kf2 Ke6 41. Ke3 Kd5 42. Kf2 Rb6 43. Kf1 c3 44. bxc3 Rb1 45. Rd1 Kc4 46. d5 Nxd5 47. Kf2 Rb2+ 0-1

