1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Ne2 Re8 9. O-O Nd7 10. Bf4 {This system is favoured by solid players who fight for a very tiny edge in the opening. Objectively speaking, Black does not have theoretical problems in this line. The game continued} Nf8 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. Re1 {As we know, White would like to exchange all the rooks as well as the queens. At this point, Svane played the precise} g6 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Ge2g3,Gf6f5] This typical move is actually prophylactic in nature. We are playing against the white knight. The idea is to answer} 13. Ng3 {with} Rxe1+ 14. Qxe1 f5 {[%csl Rg3] Black not only gains space on the kingside, but also restricts White's minor pieces.If White plays passively, we can proceed with ...Bd7 followed by ...Ne6, and ...h7-h5-h4.} 15. Qe8 {This pseudo-active move is typical for a blitz game but quite ineffective in reality. After} Rb8 {it turns out that the white queen has nothing to do on e8. Black manages to easily untangle. The position of interest arises after} 16. Qe2 Be6 17. Bc4 Re8 18. Re1 Bd7 19. Qd2 Rxe1+ 20. Qxe1 Be6 21. Bxe6 Nxe6 {As we can easily see, White cannot start advancing the queenside pawns. At the same time, Black's active pieces, as well as the march of the h-pawn, can create problems.} 22. Nf1 Qd5 23. b3 Nf4 {By attacking on g2, Black provokes the weakening} 24. f3 Ne6 {In my opinion, this move is rather passive.} ({Better would have been} 24... Qa5 25. b4 Qd5 $15 {with an obvious advantage for Black. White's queenside majority does not have value.}) 25. Qe3 f4 {[%cal Gh7h5]} 26. Qe4 Qd6 {Another passive move that allows White to stabilize the position.} ({Better would have been} 26... Qa5 $1 27. Qc2 Nc7 $17 {[%cal Gc7b5] followed by ...Nb5 or ...Nd5. White's position is falling apart.}) 27. Nd2 b5 28. Kf2 a5 29. Qe5 Qxe5 30. dxe5 Kf8 31. Ke2 Ke7 32. Kd3 f5 33. exf6+ Kxf6 34. Ke4 g5 35. b4 a4 36. a3 h5 37. c4 Nf8 38. cxb5 cxb5 39. Kd5 Ne6 40. Ne4+ Kf5 41. Nd6+ Kf6 42. Nxb5 g4 43. Nd6 gxf3 44. gxf3 Ng5 45. Ne4+ Kf5 46. Nxg5 Kxg5 47. b5 Kh4 48. b6 Kh3 49. b7 Kxh2 50. b8=Q h4 51. Qxf4+ 1-0

