1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Ne2 Re8 9. O-O Nd7 10. Bf4 Nf8 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. Ng3 {In my view, this move is slightly imprecise. More flexible would have been 12.Qd2, thus connecting the rooks and creating the possibility of Qf4. At this point, Black played} g6 {[%cal Gf6f5] This typical idea is designed to restrict White's minor pieces by means of ...f6-f5.} 13. Qc2 {Even though the computer does not change the evaluation after this move, I consider it to be a slight inaccuracy. The problem is that too many white pieces will be staring at the f5-pawn. More logical would have been either 13.Qd2 or 13.Ne4.} f5 14. Rfe1 Be6 {[%cal Gf8d7,Gd7f6] Despite the objective equality, Black's play is easier. His potential kingside threats are more real than White's queenside majority. Now, Black is ready to proceed with the maneuver ...Nd7-f6.} 15. Rad1 {White keeps playing on general grounds.} ({More practical would have been} 15. Qd2 {planning either Qg5 or Qh6.}) 15... Nd7 {[%cal Gd7f6] Black keeps improving the position. The knight is now going to occupy the perfect f6-square.} 16. Ne2 Nf6 17. g3 $6 {This is already an inaccuracy. Probably the idea was to follow with Nf4. White, however, shouldn't have weakened the light squares without a good reason.} ({Better would have been} 17. c4 {when the position is still balanced.}) 17... Nh5 $1 {[%cal Gf5f4] Very precise move. The threat is ...f5-f4. We clearly see that the f5-pawn has a lot of attacking potential.} 18. f4 $2 {This is already a sign of a panic. White radically prevents the advance ... f5-f4, but weakens all the light squares around the king.} ({Better would have been} 18. Qd2 Bd5 19. Nc1 f4 20. Rxe8+ Rxe8 21. Re1 {when Black is only very slightly better. For sure, White can hold the position.}) 18... Bd5 $17 {Black has a huge advantage. Moves such as ...Bf3 or just ...Nf6 followed by doubling the rooks on the e-file will be played sooner or later. Later on, Black managed to win the game without too much of an effort.} 19. Nc1 Bf3 20. Be2 Be4 21. Bd3 Nf6 22. Nb3 Re7 23. Nc5 Rae8 24. Qd2 b6 25. Nxe4 fxe4 26. Bc2 Kg7 27. Bb3 e3 28. Qe2 Ne4 29. Bc2 Nf2 30. Rb1 Qd5 0-1

