{ The advance ...c6-c5 is also a common idea in this structure. By exchanging the d4-pawn, Black eliminates White's space advantage and gains access to the important e5-square. Let's take a brief look at an interesting example. This position occurred in one of the Titled Tuesday games of Daniil Lintchevski. In this position, he played } 15... c5 { This move usually works when our pieces are more active. Given the fact that White's minor pieces are heavily restricted by the f5-pawn, Black can afford to play in this way. The following couple of moves are quite logical - } 16. dxc5 Qxc5 17. Rxe8 Rxe8 18. Re1 { At this point, Black should have played the simple } 18... Rxe1+ 19. Qxe1 Qd5 20. Bb1 h5 $15 { [%cal Gd7c6,Gf8e6] followed by ...Bc6 and ...Ne6. It's clear that Black's activity and kingside attacking potential are far more important than White's pawn majority. } *
