{ Time has come to examine White's most critical line against our system with 4. . .Nf6. The first important crossroads is being reached after } 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qc2 Re8+ 9. Ne2 h5 10. O-O h4 { Note that this move is rather important. Otherwise, White can proceed with Ng3. At the same time, as we know from the previous lecture, gaining space on the kingside is always favourable for Black. } 11. h3 { This move is played almost automatically. White is fixing the h4-pawn and preventing the advance ...h4-h3. } ( { An interesting alternative is } 11. Bf4 { White is generally interested in exchanging the dark-squared bishops in this line. Besides, with his last move, he prevents the maneuver ...Nd7-f8. At this point, Black's most precise reaction is } 11... Na6 { [%cal Ga6c7,Gc7e6] When ...Nd7 is impossible, a6-c7 is the alternative route for the knight. } ( { Premature is } 11... h3 $6 12. Rfe1 hxg2 { since Black is behind in the development. The game might continue } 13. Bh7+ Kh8 ( { Worse is } 13... Kf8 $2 { when after } 14. Qd3 $18 { [%cal Gd3g3] followed by Qg3 White is going to develop a devastating attack. } ) 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Ng3 Be6 16. Re4 $40 { [%cal Ge4h4] White's attack might become very dangerous. The next move is Rh4. } ) 12. Bxd6 { This move was played by Ian Nepomniachtchi. The idea is connected with spoiling Black's structure by means of Bxa6. } ( { After } 12. Rfe1 Nc7 13. Qd2 Ne6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 $11 { Black has nothing to worry about. All the typical ideas that we have examined in the previous lecture can be applied here. } ) 12... Qxd6 13. Bxa6 bxa6 14. h3 { This position was reached in the game 1-0 (49) Nepomniachtchi,I (2779) -Alonso Rosell,A (2570) Chess.com INT 2023. In this concrete case, Black's doubled pawns on the a-file are not a liability. Black gets the opportunity to play along the b-file. In the game, Alonso Rosell played 14...Bf5 which is perfectly OK. Even more flexible, however, would have been } 14... a5 $13 { followed by ...Rb8. For the time being, Black does not clarify his intentions regarding the development of the light-squared bishop. Very often, ...Bb7 followed by ... c6-c5 can be a good option. } ) 11... Nd7 12. Bd2 { [%cal Ga1e1,Gf2f4,Gf4f5] This is the most challenging continuation. The bishop is very well placed on d2. White's plan is to continue with Rae1 followed by f2-f4-f5. Later on, the attack will continue with Nf4 followed by the maneuver Qd1-g4. } 12... Nf8 13. Rae1 Bc7 { This is my main recommendation. The idea is to answer the advance f2-f4 with ...Qd6. } ( { An interesting alternative is } 13... Bd7 $5 { The idea of this somewhat mysterious move will become clear in a while. } 14. f4 { The most principled continuation. } ( { Slow moves such as } 14. c4 { would allow } 14... g6 15. Bc3 f5 { [%csl Gf5,Gf7,Gg6,Gh4] when Black manages to obtain the dream pawn structure on the kingside. } ) 14... c5 { A classical approach to the position. When your opponent is attacking on the wing, you should strike in the centre. Without ...Bd7, this move would have been premature in view of } 15. d5 { followed by c3-c4. In this case, however, we have } 15... b5 { Now, the idea of Black's 13th move becomes clear. The threat is ...c5-c4 on the next move. } 16. b3 { [%cal Gc3c4] White insists on the advance c3-c4. It turns out, however, that things are far from simple. } ( { In case of } 16. c4 bxc4 17. Bxc4 f5 $13 { [%cal Gf8h7,Gh7f6] Black is doing fine. A reasonable idea is to improve the knight with ...Nh7-f6. At some point, White will definitely regret playing f2-f4. } ) 16... c4 $1 { This pawn sacrifice justifies Black's entire concept. Black's piece activity, as well as the vulnerable white king, will give Black full compensation for the pawn. } 17. bxc4 bxc4 18. Bxc4 Qc7 { This position occurred in the game 0-1 (39) Guseinov, G (2661) -Anton Guijarro, D (2691) Chess. com INT 2023. At this point, Black should have played } 19. Bd3 Qc5+ 20. Nd4 Rac8 $13 { with an excellent counterplay. Most likely, Black will get the pawn back under favourable circumstances. } ) 14. f4 { The most dangerous continuation. This advance is the point of White's previous play. } ( { An important alternative is } 14. Nf4 { [%cal Gc2d1,Gd1h5] This move is often connected with the maneuver Qd1-h5. White mainly relies on his lead in the development. Therefore, Black should develop as fast as possible. The most precise continuation is } 14... Be6 $1 { Remember that we are always happy to exchange our light-squared bishop for a knight. } 15. Nxe6 { This is the positional way of handling the position. } ( { The aggressive } 15. Qd1 Qd6 16. Qh5 { is very well met by } 16... b5 $1 { Once again this thematic move is working very well. Black sacrifices a pawn in order to obtain the bishop pair. } 17. Qxh4 ( { The alternative } 17. g3 { can be answered with } 17... hxg3 18. fxg3 Bc4 19. Bxc4 bxc4 20. Qg4 c5 $15 { Black's position should be preferred in view of the vulnerable white king. } ) 17... Ng6 { This is the idea behind Black's previous move. Now, White should part with his light-squared bishop. The position arising after } 18. Bxg6 fxg6 19. Qg3 Bf7 { [%cal Gg6g5] } 20. h4 b4 $15 { is better for Black. The powerful bishop pair provides more than enough compensation for the pawn. } ) 15... Nxe6 16. Bc4 { White hopes that his active light-squared bishop will contribute to the kingside play.As always, before starting our counterplay in the centre, we will provoke the advance f2-f4. The optimal line goes } ( { An alternative is } 16. Bh7+ { when Black's most precise response is } 16... Kf8 $1 { The concrete idea of this move will become clear in a while. } ( { Of course, } 16... Kh8 { is playable as well. The game might continue with } 17. Bf5 Qd6 18. f4 { This position was reached in the game 1/2-1/2 (34) Ostrovskiy,A (2414) -Antal,G (2534) Charlotte 2018. At this point, Black could have played } 18... c5 19. dxc5 Nxc5 $13 { with sufficient counterplay. } ) 17. Bf5 Qd6 18. f4 Ng5 $1 { This was the point behind Black's previous play. He is now ready to proceed with ...g7-g6 followed by ...f6-f5. This typical operation works better when the king is on f8. A correspondence game saw } 19. Qd1 g6 20. Bc2 f5 21. Rxe8+ Rxe8 22. fxg5 Qh2+ 23. Kf2 Qg3+ { with perpetual. 1/2-1/2 (23) Sileika,A (2119) -Ragnarsson,J (2142) ICCF email 2020 } ) ( { Another interesting try is } 16. Qd1 { This position occurred in the game 1-0 (43) Mazur, S (2441) -Naderi, M (2178) Mashhad 2019. The idea of bringing the queen to the kingside is quite typical for the setups with Rae1. Once again, however, Black has enough counterplay - } 16... g6 17. Qg4 Qd6 18. f4 { Provoking the weakening f2-f4 advance is very important. Now, we can already start our counterplay in the centre with } 18... Ng7 19. Qxh4 c5 { Suddenly, it turns out that White's position is overextended. A logical line would be } 20. f5 g5 21. Qg4 cxd4 22. cxd4 Nh5 $11 { [%cal Gd6h2,Gh2g3] when Black's kingside play is enough to maintain the balance. } ) ( { Dubious is } 16. Bf5 $6 { Black can play } 16... Qd6 17. f4 Nf8 $15 { [%cal Gg7g6] Provoking f2-f4 is a huge achievement for Black. He is now planning to proceed with ...g7-g6 followed by ...f6-f5. Later on, the maneuver ...Nf8-h7-f6 comes into consideration. } ) 16... Qd6 17. f4 b5 18. Bb3 c5 $1 { This is the key idea. White has nothing better than simplifying into an equal endgame. } 19. Bxe6 Rxe6 20. Rxe6 fxe6 { This is the simplest. } ( { More ambitious is } 20... Qxe6 21. dxc5 Qd5 22. Be3 Re8 $13 { when the vulnerable white king gives Black sufficient compensation for the pawn. } ) 21. Qe4 ( { Nothing changes } 21. Be3 { when after } 21... Bb6 $11 { the position is equal. 1/2-1/2 (35) Ninov,N (2446) -Gunduz,U (2349) Ayvalik 2022 } ) 21... Rd8 22. Be3 Bb6 23. dxc5 Bxc5 $11 { with equality. 1/2-1/2 (31) Babazada,K (2479) -Abasov,N (2643) Baku 2023 } ) ( { The move } 14. c4 { gains space in the centre but weakens the d4-pawn. This continuation does not fit well with Rae1. } 14... Ne6 { [%cal Gg7g6] This is a typical reaction. Black immediately puts pressure on d4. } 15. Be3 ( { In case of } 15. Bc3 { , we react in the same way - } 15... g6 { Depending on the circumstances, Black has two major ideas: 1) Exchanging the light-squared bishops by means of ...Ng7 followed by ...Bf5. This idea works very well if Black first provokes f2-f4 with ...Qd6 2) Gain space on the kingside with ...f6-f5. Obviously, this plan is more justified when the white bishop is on e3. At this point, a possible continuation would be } 16. d5 Qd6 17. f4 Ng7 18. dxc6 bxc6 $15 { Black is already slightly better in view of the vulnerable white king. } ) 15... g6 $13 { Again, Black enjoys a decent counterplay. } ) ( { Another typical idea for this line. White is preparing the maneuver Ng1-f3, thus taking the h2-square under control and questioning the h2-pawn. A reasonable reaction would be } 14. Kh1 { [%cal Ge2g1,Gg1f3] } 14... g6 15. Ng1 Be6 16. Nf3 Qd7 { Now, White should constantly reckon with ...Bxh3. } 17. Re3 { This position occurred in the game. 1/2-1/2 (26) Celik,H (2363) -Di Nicolantonio,L (2369) Vaujany 2022. Obviously, Black can force a draw by means of ...Bxh3. Nevertheless, our superior piece activity and better coordination allow us to hope for more. A logical follow-up would be } 17... Bd5 18. Be4 Rxe4 $1 { This elegant pawn sacrifice creates huge problems for White. } 19. Rxe4 f5 20. Ree1 Qd6 { It turns out that White does not have a satisfactory defence against .. .Bxf3. The only possibility is } 21. Ne5 f6 22. Bf4 Ne6 23. Bh2 fxe5 24. Bxe5 Qf8 $15 { Even though Black's advantage is obvious, there is a lot of fight ahead. } ) 14... Qd6 { [%cal Gg7g6,Gf6f5] An important move in Black's strategy. We should prevent the advance f4-f5 at any price. Our positional idea is to proceed with ...g7-g6 followed by ...f6-f5. Therfore, White should go for the energetic } 15. c4 { Now, 15...g6 would be answered with 16.c5 followed by f4-f5 on the next move. Fortunately, I have found an interesting novelty in this position - } 15... f5 $14 { I have found this interesting pawn sacrifice while preparing the camp materials. Later on, the same idea was recommended by GM Pavel Eljanov in his course My Caro-Kann - Part 4. By working independently, we have reached the same conclusion. With his last move, Black is sacrificing a pawn in order to obtain a long-term initiative. The critical position occurs after } 16. Bxf5 Bxf5 17. Qxf5 Re6 $1 { [%cal Ga8e8] Black is planning to increase the pressure with ...Rae8. Our compensation is based on three factors: 1) White's king is slightly vulnerable 2) The pawns on f4 and d4 make White's position overextended 3) Black enjoys superior piece activity. White cannot just keep making natural moves since Black has a clear way of developing the initiative - ...Rae8 followed by ....Bb6, and ...Ng6. At some point, White's position might fall apart. The best, and most principled, continuation is } 18. d5 ( { Another interesting line is } 18. c5 Qd7 19. d5 cxd5 20. Nd4 { White is trying to transform the advance. Black, however, can force massive simplifications, thus reaching an equal position - } 20... Rxe1 21. Bxe1 Qxf5 22. Nxf5 Ng6 23. Bxh4 Bxf4 24. Rf3 b6 25. Bf2 bxc5 26. Bxc5 a5 $11 { The equality is obvious. } ) ( { A natural move would be } 18. Qd3 { Nevertheless, this continuation is way too passive. Black can keep developing the initiative by means of simple moves - } 18... Rae8 19. Nc1 { White tries to force simplifications. } ( { Dubious is } 19. Nc3 $6 { in view of } 19... Bb6 { when it turns out that White cannot keep the pawn. After } 20. Kh1 Qxd4 21. Qxd4 Bxd4 $15 { Black is slightly better in view of his superior pawn structure. } ) ( { After } 19. Kh1 Re4 20. b3 Qd7 $44 { White is completely tied. Black should just improve the knight. Depending on White's play, we will follow with either ...Ng6, or ...Nh7-f6. } ) ( { Nothing special gives the sequence } 19. c5 Qd7 20. f5 Re4 21. d5 cxd5 22. Nc3 R4e5 $13 { Black keeps an excellent counterplay in view of the weak white king. } ) 19... Rxe1 20. Bxe1 Ne6 21. Ne2 Qd8 { [%cal Ge6c5] Black has an excellent compensation. White should now reckon with the idea ...Nc5-e4. } ( { A more concrete approach would be } 21... Bb6 22. Bxh4 Nxd4 23. Nxd4 Bxd4+ 24. Kh1 Re3 $44 { Once again, with a very strong compensation. } ) ) 18... Ree8 { [%cal Gd6c5] The most precise. Black retreats with the rook without the inclusion of ... cxd5. Now, White should reckon with the possible ...Qc5. You don't need to remember anything else in this line. Nevertheless, I will provide some lines, just for the sake of completeness and objectivity. } 19. Kh1 { White removes the king from the dangerous a7-g1 diagonal and is planning to answer } 19... cxd5 { with } 20. Nc3 { Once again, we see a transformation of an advantage. White gives the pawn back in order to achieve superior piece activity. } ( { Harmless is } 20. Qxd5 { when after } 20... Qxd5 21. cxd5 Ng6 22. Nc3 Ne7 { [%cal Ge7f5] Black has the powerful positional threat of ...Nf5. The game will probably continue with } 23. f5 Bg3 24. Re4 f6 $11 { [%cal Gg8f7,Ga8d8] followed by ...Kf7 and ...Rad8. Black is out of danger. } ) ( { After } 20. cxd5 Ng6 $44 { [%cal Ga8d8] Black enjoys full compensation. The next move is going to be ...Rad8. } ) 20... dxc4 21. Nd5 Ng6 { The most natural continuation. } ( { The endgame arising after } 21... Bb6 22. Bc3 Qg6 23. Qxg6 fxg6 24. Nxb6 axb6 25. Rxe8 Rxe8 26. f5 Rc8 $11 { is playable as well. The position is objectively equal. } ) 22. Bc3 { White is playing for domination. Fortunately, Black has enough resources to neutralize the initiative. The following couple of moves are forced } 22... Rxe1 23. Rxe1 Rd8 24. Nxc7 Qxc7 25. Qg5 { The most dangerous idea. Black should now reckon with f4-f5. The precise reaction here is } 25... Qc8 $1 { planning to answer f4-f5 with ...Rd5. } 26. f5 { The most straightforward. } ( { Another possibility would be } 26. Rf1 Rd3 $1 { [%cal Gd3g3] Another key point to have in mind. Black's idea is ...Rg3. The following sequence is a good illustration of how the game might develop here. } 27. f5 Rg3 28. Qd2 Ne7 29. Be5 Rd3 30. Qg5 f6 31. Bxf6 Rg3 32. Qxh4 Nxf5 33. Rxf5 Qxf5 34. Qxg3 Qxf6 $11 { After all the fireworks, we have reached an equal endgame. } ) 26... Rd5 27. Rf1 ( { Another way to force a draw is } 27. Bxg7 Qxf5 28. Qh6 f6 29. Bf8 Nxf8 30. Re8 Rd1+ 31. Kh2 Qc5 32. Qg6+ Kh8 33. Qxf6+ Kg8 34. Qg6+ $11 { with a perpetual. } ) 27... Qd7 $11 { White cannot make any progress. For instance, 28.Qg4 will be answered with 28...Ne5. The position is equal. } *
