{ Now, we are going to examine the line with Be3 and c3-c4. Statistically speaking, this is White's most popular option. The position of interest arises after } 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qc2 Re8+ 9. Ne2 h5 10. O-O h4 11. h3 Nd7 12. Be3 Nf8 13. c4 { We have reached a very important tabiya for the variation with 4...Nf6. In this line, White is trying to play in the centre. His next move is going to be Rad1. Note that at every moment, we should reckon with ideas based on c4-c5 followed by d4-d5. Therefore, having good control of the d5-square is vital for Black. In this line of thought, I will suggest the natural } 13... Be6 { [%cal Ga8c8] Black not only develops the bishop but also takes the d5-square under control. Our usual idea is to continue with ...Rc8 followed by ...Bb8. Very often, the battery along the diagonal b8-h2 might be annoying for White. } 14. Rad1 Rc8 15. Rfe1 { For the time being, both sides are mobilizing their pieces. } ( { In case of } 15. Nf4 Bb8 16. Rfe1 Qc7 { we transpose to one of the lines that is examined below. } ) 15... Bb8 { Another key move. Now, at every moment, White should reckon with either ...Qc7, or ...Qd6. } 16. b3 { This flexible prophylactic move is also advocated by the computer. In many lines, it's important for White to have the c4-pawn protected. } ( { In my opinion, the idea of } 16. Nf4 { is slightly dubious. Black has more than one way to handle the position. } 16... Qc7 { Quite a natural response. The queen invasion to h2 will be a constant threat now. } ( { Even simpler would be } 16... b5 $1 17. c5 Bxf4 { As we know, the idea of giving the dark-squared bishop for the knight is quite typical for this variation. After having provoked c4-c5, this idea is even more effective. } 18. Bxf4 Qa5 $13 { Black enjoys an excellent counterplay. } ) 17. Kf1 Bd7 { Given the vulnerability of the white king, clearing the e-file for the rook makes a lot of sense. From now on, White should always reckon with ...Ne6. } 18. b3 { It's difficult for White to come up with something concrete. Therefore, he is making generally useful moves. Later on, he can try to induce some exchanges with Bc1. } ( { The direct } 18. d5 { backfires after } 18... cxd5 19. Nxd5 Qh2 { The position looks tremendously dangerous for White. It's not a surprise that in an online blitz game, White immediately went wrong. After } 20. Be4 $6 b5 $17 { he was already in huge trouble. 0-1 (31) Petriashvili, N (2432) -Oparin, G (2655) Chess.com INT 2021 } ) 18... Rcd8 $1 { This is the precise move. The potential pressure on d4 might become an important factor in the future. } ( { Premature is } 18... Ne6 $6 { After } 19. Nxe6 Bxe6 20. f4 $14 { White's position should be preferred in view of the space advantage. It's not easy for Black to create counterplay here. 1-0 (43) Suarez Gomez,J (2447) -Xiong,J (2700) Chess. com INT 2021 } ) 19. Bc1 { One of the natural continuations. } ( { A tactical mistake would be } 19. Qe2 $2 { After } 19... Qxf4 20. Bxf4 Rxe2 21. Rxe2 Bxf4 $19 { Black is winning. } ) ( { In response to } 19. Bf5 { Black's most precise reaction is } 19... Bxf5 20. Qxf5 b5 { immediately creating counterplay. A possible line is } 21. cxb5 Qa5 22. a4 Bxf4 23. Qxf4 cxb5 $13 { In this complex position, Black has every chance to overtake the initiative. } ) 19... Ne6 { Now, everything is ready for this move. The following sequence provides a good illustration of Black's ideas. } 20. Nxe6 Qh2 $1 21. Bh7+ Kh8 22. Re4 Rxe6 23. Bf5 Rxe4 24. Qxe4 Bxf5 25. Qxf5 Qh1+ 26. Ke2 Qxg2 $15 { Black is already better. } ) ( { Another logical idea is } 16. Bf4 { As we know, White is usually interested in exchanging the dark-squared bishops. Black's best response in this case is } 16... Bxf4 17. Nxf4 Qa5 $1 { [%cal Ga5g5] Remember this idea. When the dark-squared bishops are exchanged and White has a knight on f4, the idea of bringing the queen to g5 is very typical. } 18. Qd2 { White hopes that he might have slightly better chances in the endgame. } ( { The position arising after } 18. b3 Qg5 19. Qc1 Bf5 20. Bxf5 Qxf5 $13 { We know that positions featuring queen and knight versus queen and knight are typically good for Black. Additionally, in this case, White's position tends to be a bit overextended. } ) 18... Qxd2 19. Rxd2 Bd7 20. Rxe8 Rxe8 21. Re2 Rd8 $11 { Of course, we should keep at least one pair of rooks! The position is equal. } ) ( { Another important move is } 16. Nc3 { White supports the advance d4-d5, but leaves the king without support. Now, the most precise way of building a battery is } 16... Qd6 $1 ( { Worse is } 16... Qc7 { since after } 17. f4 { Black does not have the typical idea of } 17... Ng6 $2 { White can just proceed with } 18. d5 cxd5 19. cxd5 Bd7 20. d6 $16 { With the queen on d6, this idea wouldn't have been possible. } ) 17. f4 Ng6 $1 { This is the point. White cannot take twice on g6 because the pawn on c4 is hanging. Now, we can see the logic behind the move b2-b3. After } 18. Ne4 Qc7 19. Rf1 b5 $13 { Black enjoys an excellent counterplay. } ) 16... b5 { We should start our counterplay before White manages to create positional pressure. } 17. Kf1 { White wants to execute one of his typical ideas - Ng1-f3. This position occurred in the game 1-0 (71) Celik,H (2360) -Dudin,G (2408) Podgorica 2021. At this point, Black could have played } 17... Qd7 18. Ng1 bxc4 19. bxc4 Ng6 $13 { Since the c4-pawn is hanging, this move becomes possible. White does not have Nf3 in view of ...Bxh3. Black is doing completely fine. } *
