1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Ne2 Re8 9. O-O Nd7 10. Bf4 Nf8 11. Qd2 { As we have already discussed, After playing Rfe1, White wants to simplify the position with Bxd6 followed by Qf4. } 11... Ng6 { This is the most precise reaction. Besides putting the knight on an active square, Black takes the f4-square under control. } 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Rfe1 { White usually starts with this move before proceeding with Ng3. This continuation is a bit more flexible since it waits for Black to clarify the position of his light-squared bishop. } ( { The immediate } 13. Ng3 { is well met by } 13... Qf4 14. Qc2 Bd7 $11 { [%cal Ga8d8,Gg6f8,Gg7g6,Gf6f5] Black is doing perfectly fine. Later on, he can proceed with ...Rad8 followed by ...Nf8,...g7-g6, and ...f6-f5. } ) 13... Be6 14. Ng3 Nf4 { A thematic reaction to Ng3. Of course, we are interested in exchanging White's bishop. } 15. Ne4 { In this structure, the knight is usually heading for the c5-square. } ( { Another game saw } 15. Bf1 Rad8 16. Ne4 Qc7 17. Nc5 { This position occurred in the game 1-0 (32) Amilal, M (2437) -Valle Luis, L (2342) Chess.com INT 2023. Now, the simplest would have been } 17... b6 18. Nxe6 Nxe6 $44 { [%cal Gg7g6,Gf6f5,Gh7h5] In this structure, the knight is fighting very well against White's light-squared bishop. Black can already consider gaining kingside space with the typical moves ...g7-g6 followed by ...f6-f5, and ... h7-h5. } ) 15... Qc7 16. Nc5 Nxd3 { This is equalizing on the spot. } ( { If you want to keep the position more complicated, you can play } 16... g6 17. Nxe6 Nxe6 $13 { with a nice counterplay. We have already discussed this type of position. } ) 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Qxd3 e5 $11 { This position occurred in the game Movsesian, S - Riazantsev, A, 2019. The position is equal. } *
