1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 { I have decided to suggest this trendy line, even though I have much more experience with 4...Bf5. The reason is that resulting positions are more dynamic and the structure is instructive in itself. } 5. Nxf6+ { The most natural reply, here are the alternatives in brief: } ( 5. Qd3 $5 { is the most interesting sideline here, it is strongly resembling the 5.Qe2 line in the Two Knights variation. Black's best is } 5... Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Qd5 $1 { and the difference (d2-d4 instead of Ng1-f3) is rather in Black's favour since the central pawn needs protection: } 7. Bd3 ( 7. Qe3 Bf5 8. c4 Qe4 9. Nf3 e6 10. Be2 Qxe3 11. Bxe3 ( 11. fxe3 Nd7 12. O-O Be7 $13 ) 11... Bb4+ $1 12. Nd2 Nd7 13. O-O O-O $13 ) ( 7. Qf4 Bf5 8. c4 Qe4+ 9. Ne2 { Szpar - Pacan Milej, Zagnansk Swietokrzyskie GM, 2022, when } 9... Qxf4 10. Bxf4 Nd7 11. O-O-O e6 { is the easiest reaction, for example } 12. Nc3 h5 $5 13. h4 ( { it is important that } 13. d5 $6 { is met by } 13... cxd5 14. cxd5 e5 $15 ) 13... Be7 $13 ) 7... Qxe4+ 8. Bxe4 Be6 $1 { Such light-squared strategy yields Black a decent game. } 9. Bd3 ( 9. Be3 Bd5 10. f3 Nd7 11. Bd3 e5 $11 ) ( 9. Ne2 Bd5 10. Nc3 e6 $5 11. Be3 Na6 $13 ) 9... g6 10. Ne2 Bg7 11. Be3 f5 $1 { (an essential move, which frees the f7-square for the bishop) } 12. O-O-O Nd7 13. Nf4 Bf7 14. Rhe1 O-O $13 ) ( 5. Ng3 { does also exist here, as well as in the Two Knights variation, but it is even less convincing in the view of the vigorous } 5... h5 $5 6. h4 ( 6. Bc4 $14 h4 7. N3e2 Bf5 $13 { Gokerkan - Niemann, Sitges, 2022 } ) 6... c5 $5 7. Nf3 Bg4 ( 7... Nc6 $5 8. Be3 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bg4 $13 ) 8. Be3 { Vallejo Diaz - Bluebaum, Leon, blitz, 2021, when } 8... e6 $5 9. dxc5 Qc7 { is good - } 10. Qd2 ( 10. b4 Nd5 11. Bb5+ Nc6 $36 ) 10... Bxc5 11. Bb5+ Ke7 12. O-O-O Bxe3 13. Qxe3 Rc8 14. Rd2 a6 $13 ) 5... exf6 6. Be3 $5 { The most interesting and sound sideline - White wants to push c2-c4. } ( 6. Bc4 { is probably more popular, but Black has two reliable answers: } 6... Na6 $5 { has lately gained a lot in popularity: } ( 6... Bd6 $5 7. Qe2+ Be7 $5 ( 7... Qe7 8. Qxe7+ Kxe7 9. Ne2 Be6 10. Bd3 a5 $5 11. O-O Rd8 ) 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Re1 Nd7 11. c3 Nf8 12. Bf4 Be6 13. Nd2 Qd7 14. a4 Bxc4 15. Nxc4 Ne6 16. Bg3 { Ivanchuk - Ushenina, Salamanca, rapid, 2023 } 16... f5 $5 17. Ne5 Qd5 $13 ) 7. c3 ( 7. Ne2 Bd6 8. O-O Nc7 9. Bf4 ( 9. Bd3 O-O 10. c4 Re8 11. Be3 ( 11. Qc2 g6 12. Be3 Ne6 ( 12... f5 $5 13. Rfe1 b5 $13 ) 13. Rad1 { S. Zenelaj - J. Mesic, BIH-chT, Neum, 2022, with mutual chances after } 13... Bc7 14. d5 cxd5 15. cxd5 Ng7 $13 ) 11... f5 $5 12. Qd2 h6 13. Bf4 Qf6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Rad1 Bd7 16. b3 a5 $13 ) 9... O-O 10. Qd2 Re8 11. Rfe1 g6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Ng3 f5 $5 14. Rxe8+ Nxe8 $13 ) ( 7. Nf3 Bd6 8. Qe2+ Qe7 9. Qxe7+ Bxe7 10. Bxa6 ( 10. O-O Be6 $11 ) 10... bxa6 11. Bd2 Be6 { and it is far from easy for White to exploit the wrecked opponent's queenside: } 12. O-O ( 12. Ba5 h5 $1 13. h4 ( 13. O-O-O h4 $13 ) 13... Rb8 14. O-O-O Rb5 $13 ) 12... h5 13. Rac1 g5 $13 ) 7... Nc7 8. Qb3 $5 Qd7 $5 ( 8... Qe7+ $6 9. Ne2 b5 10. Bd3 Be6 11. Qc2 $16 { N. Pezelj - D. Fridman, EU-ch rapid Skopje, 2018 } ) 9. Nf3 Bd6 10. O-O O-O { looks balanced, for example } 11. Re1 a5 12. a4 Nd5 13. Bd2 ( 13. g3 b6 $1 14. Nh4 Qb7 15. Bd3 g6 $13 ) 13... b6 ( 13... Qd8 $5 ) 14. Nh4 ( 14. h3 Qb7 $13 ) 14... g5 $5 15. Nf3 Rb8 $13 ) ( 6. Bd3 { offers a pawn, which Black can confidently accept - } 6... Qxd4 7. Nf3 { as follows: } 7... Qb6 $5 { This relatively rare move is even more to my liking - Black keeps the Bf8-c5 idea in mind in order to press on f2. } ( 7... Qd5 $5 8. O-O Be6 9. Re1 Nd7 10. Bf4 ( 10. Qe2 $6 { Safarli - Vallejo Pons, Elllobregat, 2022, allows } 10... O-O-O $15 ) 10... Nc5 { Now Black forces new exchanges and is absolutely fine after } 11. Bf1 Qxd1 12. Raxd1 Be7 13. Nd4 a5 $13 ) 8. O-O Be6 { and now: } 9. Qe2 ( 9. c3 c5 $5 ( 9... Nd7 $5 10. Nd4 O-O-O $13 ) 10. Re1 Bd6 11. Qe2 Nd7 12. Bc4 Bc7 $11 ) ( 9. Re1 $6 Bc5 $15 { comes in confirmation of the last note } ) 9... Be7 10. a4 c5 $5 ( 10... a5 $5 11. c3 Nd7 12. Nd4 Ne5 $13 ) 11. a5 Qc7 12. Qe4 a6 13. Bf4 Qc6 $13 { Black is pretty solid and the first player can hope to equalize at best. } ) 6... Bd6 7. Bd3 Na6 $5 { A typical route of this knight in many lines, White has two options to deprive it of the b4-square. } 8. a3 ( 8. c3 { is the other way to stop the jump, but, as said, in accordance with White's 6th move this pawn is designed to advance to c4 in one go. } 8... Nc7 9. Ne2 O-O 10. O-O Nd5 11. Bd2 Qc7 $5 { Black has a choice of decent options, but this dark-squared strategy looks very much in the spirit of the featured variation: } ( 11... f5 $5 12. c4 Nf6 13. Qc2 Re8 14. Rad1 ( 14. f3 $6 Nh5 $1 15. Rae1 g6 16. Qc1 Be6 17. b3 Bc7 18. Bb1 { So far Harshini - Han Yichen, Pozarevac, 2022, when } 18... f4 $15 { is the simplest way to proceed } ) 14... Ne4 15. Bc1 h6 16. g3 Bd7 17. Bf4 Qf6 $13 ) 12. h3 ( 12. Ng3 Be6 13. Qf3 Rfe8 ( 13... Bf4 $5 ) 14. Bc2 ( 14. c4 Nb4 ) 14... b5 $13 ) 12... Nf4 $1 { reveals the idea - } 13. Nxf4 Bxf4 14. Re1 g6 { and now: } 15. Re4 ( 15. Bxf4 Qxf4 16. Qc1 Qxc1 $1 { A resolute reaction - in spite of the general understanding that the multiple exchanges will favour White, this queenless endgame is actually quite safe for Black. } ( 16... Qd6 $14 17. Qh6 $1 Rd8 18. h4 $14 ) 17. Raxc1 Be6 18. b3 ( 18. a3 Rfd8 $13 ) 18... Rfd8 19. Bc4 Rd6 20. Re2 ( 20. a4 a5 21. Re3 Kf8 22. Rce1 Ke7 $13 ) 20... Bxc4 ( 20... Kf8 $11 ) 21. bxc4 c5 22. d5 Ra6 $13 ) 15... Bxd2 16. Qxd2 Bf5 $5 { Despite the inferior structure Black does not usually mind exchanging all the minor pieces. } 17. Re2 Bxd3 18. Qxd3 Rad8 19. Rae1 Kg7 $13 ) 8... O-O 9. Ne2 Re8 10. O-O { Here Black has an interesting choice. } 10... Bg4 $5 { A reasonable idea to exchange this bishop and obtain promising counterplay on the dark squares. } ( { Alternatively, Black can rely on } 10... Nc7 $5 11. c4 f5 { , although Bc8 deserves a better fate. A possible continuation is } 12. Qd2 h6 13. Bf4 Qf6 { and it is arguable whether the d4-pawn is an asset or a target - } 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Rfd1 Be6 $13 ( 15... Qf6 $5 16. Rac1 Qg5 $13 ) ) 11. h3 ( 11. Re1 Nc7 12. h3 { does not differ much - } 12... Bxe2 13. Rxe2 g6 $13 ) 11... Bxe2 12. Qxe2 ( 12. Bxe2 Nc7 13. Bf3 { does hardly pose serious problems - } 13... Nd5 14. Bd2 f5 15. c4 Nf6 $13 ) 12... Nc7 13. Qf3 { It makes sense to keep the restrained c2-c3 in reserve. } ( { The exchange of Ne2 has removed one of the defenders of the central d4-pawn, which may quickly tell in a sample line like } 13. c4 g6 $5 14. Qd2 f5 15. Rae1 f4 $5 ( 15... Qd7 $13 ) 16. Bxf4 Rxe1 17. Rxe1 Bxf4 18. Qxf4 Ne6 $11 ) 13... g6 { Preparing the thematic expansion on the kingside. } 14. c3 ( 14. Rad1 { is similarly met by } 14... f5 15. c4 Qh4 ( 15... f4 $1 16. Bc1 Ne6 17. Be2 Bc7 18. Qc3 Qf6 $13 ) 16. b4 Rad8 17. d5 cxd5 18. cxd5 b6 $13 { Abdrlauf - Pultinevicius, Riga, 2023. } ) 14... f5 15. g3 h5 16. Bd2 Qd7 17. Rfe1 Nd5 18. Kg2 ( { No better is } 18. Rxe8+ Rxe8 19. Kg2 ( 19. Re1 $6 { is imprecise in the view of } 19... Rxe1+ 20. Bxe1 h4 $36 ) 19... Bf8 $5 20. h4 ( 20. Re1 Rxe1 21. Bxe1 Bh6 $13 ) 20... b5 $5 21. a4 a6 $13 ) 18... Rxe1 { The rooks will nevertheless be exchanged soon or later. } ( { Indeed, there it is not necessary to force the events, for instance, Black can play } 18... a6 $5 { , thus placing his last pawn on a light square as well with b7-b5 in mind. } ) 19. Rxe1 Re8 20. Rxe8+ Qxe8 21. Qe2 ( 21. c4 Nc7 22. Bc3 Bf8 23. d5 cxd5 24. cxd5 Qd7 25. Bc4 Ne8 $13 { typical development where Black is getting a real counterplay thanks to the nice blockade } ) 21... Qd7 $13 { Black is ready to meet any opponent's intention to break through. } *
