{ Now, we shall take a look at the plans based on 0-0-0. The arising positions in these lines are rather complex. Hence, the game is going for three results. } 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qc2 Re8+ 9. Ne2 ( { A fresh idea is } 9. Be3 h5 10. Nf3 { [%cal Ge1c1,Gg2g4] This plan can be rather dangerous if Black is not well prepared. White usually intends to proceed with 0-0-0 followed by g2-g4. The point behind Nf3 is that . ..hxg4 can be answered with Nh4. Black's most precise reaction is } 10... Be6 $1 { This is the optimal position for the bishop. Besides putting pressure on the queenside, from e6-square the bishop is also keeping an eye on g4. } 11. O-O-O Na6 { [%cal Gd8a5] Another precise move. Black can easily bring the knight into the game by means of ...Nc7-d5. Additionally, Black's last move is a prophylactic against c3-c4. } 12. g4 { White cannot waste time. Otherwise, Black will generate tremendous queenside activity with ...Qa5. The following sequence is pretty logical and straightforward: } 12... hxg4 13. Nh4 Qa5 14. Nf5 Bxf5 15. Bxf5 Nc7 16. Rhg1 $2 { This is already a step in the wrong direction. The problem is that Black can eliminate one of White's important attacking pieces - the e3-bishop. } ( { Better would have been } 16. Kb1 { planning to answer } 16... Nd5 { with } 17. Bc1 { Nevertheless, after } 17... Bf4 $13 { Black enjoys excellent counterplay on the dark squares. } ) 16... Nd5 17. Rxg4 { White has nothing better. } ( { Unfortunately, the idea } 17. Bh7+ Kf8 18. Qf5 { Does not work tactically. Black can play } 18... Qxa2 19. Qxg4 g5 { [%cal Ge8e3] when White does not have any kingside attack whatsoever. Black is threatening ...Rxe3. The game can continue with } 20. Rde1 Ba3 21. bxa3 Qa1+ 22. Kc2 Qxc3+ 23. Kd1 Rad8 $17 { White will hardly survive for too long. } ) 17... Rxe3 $1 { This is the point! Black is already clearly better. } 18. Rdg1 { This position was reached in the game 1/2-1/2 (33) Muzychuk, A (2504) -Salimova, N (2409) Baku 2023. Now, Black could have played } 18... g5 19. fxe3 Nxe3 20. Qf2 Nxg4 21. Rxg4 Kf8 $15 { White does not have compensation for the pawn. Additionally, Black can also create threats against the king by means of ...Bf4 and ...Re8. } ) 9... h5 10. Be3 { This is the optimal way of preparing 0-0-0. } ( { The problem with } 10. Bd2 { is that Black has } 10... c5 $1 { As we have pointed out in the previous lecture, this move works fine when we can create decent piece play. Given the fact that the white pieces are awkwardly placed on the d-file, the advance ...c6-c5 creates a lot of sense. So far, this move has been played in only one game. Therefore, I find the entire concept very practical. White's most natural continuation is } 11. O-O-O ( { Another possibility is } 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. O-O { White just wants to complete the development and start a piece play with Nf4. Black will respond with } 12... Nc6 13. Nf4 Ne5 { As I have mentioned in the previous lecture, getting control of the e5-square is one of the ideas behind the advance ...c6-c5. It turns out that Black enjoys decent piece play in this position. Since this position has never been seen in practice, you don't need to remember anything. The following line (not forced at all) is just a good illustration of what might happen in such positions. You can go through the moves for fun! } 14. Be4 Ng4 15. Rae1 Nxf2 16. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 17. Kxf2 f5 18. Bd5 Qh4+ 19. g3 Qxh2+ 20. Ng2 Rxe1 21. Bxe1 f4 22. gxf4 h4 23. Qg6 Be6 24. Bxe6 fxe6 25. Qxe6+ Kh8 26. Qf7 h3 27. Qh5+ $11 { The perpetual is a decent finish of such a complex and sharp battle! } ) 11... Nc6 12. dxc5 { This is the most principled choice. White wants to open the d-file in order to make use of the opposition. } ( { The only game which reached this position continued } 12. Be3 { 1/2-1/2 (66) Kyc,J (2230) -Rudzinska,M (2256) Katowice 2022. Now, the simplest would have been } 12... Qa5 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Bxc5 Qxc5 15. Nf4 Be6 $13 { [%cal Ga8d8] followed by ...Rad8. Black has excellent chances in this complex position. } ) 12... Bxc5 13. Nf4 Ne5 14. Bb5 Bd7 15. Be3 { This is the only continuation allowing White to at least ask some questions.Black has more than one solution in this position. The most straightforward seems to be } ( { After } 15. Bxd7 Qxd7 $13 { Black has nothing to worry about. } ) 15... Bxe3+ 16. fxe3 Qc7 17. Nd5 Qa5 18. Nxf6+ gxf6 19. Bxd7 Nxd7 20. Rxd7 Qxa2 $11 { The position remains balanced. } ) 10... Nd7 11. O-O-O { The most popular move. Note that in this line White is hardly going to deliever checkmate on the kingside. The main strategic idea consists of playing in the centre by means of c3-c4 and Nc3. Later on, White can consider c4-c5 followed by d4-d5. } ( { The immediate } 11. Ng3 { is not dangerous at all. Going for the h5-pawn is rather time-consuming. Black's most energetic reaction is } 11... Nb6 { [%cal Gb6d5] planning to follow with ...Nd5 on the next move. } 12. Nxh5 { The most consistent with the previous move. } ( { After } 12. O-O-O Nd5 13. Bd2 Nf4 14. Bxf4 Bxf4+ 15. Kb1 Qd5 $15 { Black is already better in view of his bishop pair. } ) 12... Nd5 13. O-O Bg4 $1 { forcing the knight back to the passive g3-square. It's important to start with this intermediate move before regaining the pawn. } 14. Ng3 Bxg3 15. hxg3 Nxe3 16. fxe3 Rxe3 $11 { Although the position remains balanced, playing with Black is easier. 0-1 (51) Duarte, L (2330) -Meskovs,N (2568) Lichess.org INT 2021 } ) 11... Nf8 12. c4 { Sooner or later, White should play this move. } ( { It's essential to know that } 12. h3 { planning g2-g4 should always be met with } 12... h4 { In this way, we make sure that White does not have play on the kingside. } ) ( { As usual, attacking the h5-pawn by means of } 12. Ng3 { is quite harmless for Black. Among the variety of good reactions, the simplest seems to be } 12... Be6 13. Kb1 g6 14. Ne4 b5 $13 { Gaining space on the queenside and fixing the domination on the light squares should be our priority. Black is always ready to give the dark-squared bishop for the knight. } ) 12... Be6 { This is Black's most popular choice. Later on, we are planning to create counterplay with ...Rc8 and ...b7-b5. Also, it's important that the e6-bishop keeps an eye on the c4-pawn, thus often making possible the idea of ...Ng6. } ( { The move } 12... h4 { is also quite interesting. Black keeps gaining space on the kingside, thus keeping the possibility of ... Bg4. This continuation has been analyzed in-depth by GM Pavel Eljanov. For more information, you can check his course My Caro-Kann - Part 4. } ) 13. Kb1 { Sooner or later, White should play this move. The king cannot remain on the c-file. } ( { It's very important to know that the immediate } 13. Nc3 { is very well met by } 13... Bb4 { Black will be more than happy to play ...Bxc3 followed by ... b7-b5, thus getting an excellent play on the light squares. } ) ( { An instructive positional mistake is } 13. Nf4 $2 { I guess you already know the right reaction - } 13... Bxf4 $1 { we will gladly give the dark-squared bishop for the knight. Of course, after } 14. Bxf4 { Black starts his play on the light squares by means of } 14... b5 { White's position is extremely dangerous. A possible continuation is } 15. d5 cxd5 16. c5 Qa5 17. Kb1 { This position occurred in the game 1/2-1/2 (44) Slobodjan,R (2452) -Koepke,C (2332) Germany 2019. Now, the simplest would have been } 17... Ng6 { [%cal Gg6e5,Ge5c4] The knight is heading towards the c4-square. After } 18. Bd6 Ne5 19. Bh7+ Kh8 20. Bf5 Nc4 $17 { Black enjoys an obvious advantage. } ) 13... Rc8 14. a3 { [%cal Ge2c3] The most critical continuation. By taking the b4-square under control, White prepares Nc3. As we already know, the immediate Nc3 will be answered with ...Bb4. In this position, you should know the move } 14... Ng6 { Once again, we make use of the fact that the c4-pawn will be hanging if White takes twice on g6. At the same time, with this move, Black frees the f8-square for the bishop. The main line goes } 15. Nc3 b5 16. c5 Bf8 { Now, White should act very energetically. Otherwise, Black will establish a solid blockade with ...Ne7-d5. The critical seems to be } 17. d5 cxd5 18. Bxb5 { Black's position seems very dangerous (and probably it is!) . Fortunately, we have a very interesting exchange sacrifice at our disposal. } 18... Bxc5 19. Bxe8 ( { Another option is } 19. Bxc5 Rxc5 20. Bxe8 Qxe8 21. Qa4 ( 21. Ka1 Qc6 $44 ) 21... Qc8 $44 { The position is totally unclear. Nevertheless, Black's safer king makes Black's position easier to handle in a human game. For instance, the idea ...Ne5-c4 is always very annoying for White. } ) 19... Qxe8 20. Qa4 { Logically, White wants to exchange material. After } 20... Bd7 { he has a choice. } 21. Qa6 { This is the top choice of the computer. Honestly speaking, though, computer evaluations are irrelevant here. Our main goal is to create practical difficulties for our opponent. } ( { Another fascinating line goes } 21. Qa5 Bf8 22. Rxd5 Ne5 { Once again, Black's position is full of counterplay. As always, the resource of ...Nc4 is very annoying for White. Note that after } 23. Qxa7 { we can consider sacrificing a second exchange by means of } 23... Rxc3 24. bxc3 Be6 25. Rhd1 Qc6 26. Rd8 Kh7 $11 { The position is objectively balanced. To be honest, however, I would always take Black due to the vulnerability of the white king. } ) 21... Bxe3 22. fxe3 Rxc3 $1 { This second exchange sacrifice is the key to our counterplay. The sequence } 23. bxc3 Qb8+ 24. Ka2 Be6 25. Rd4 Ne5 $44 { leads to unclear position with chances for both sides. Personally, in a practical game, I would be happy to play this position with Black. } *
